WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:09.120
[Amit Varma]: How do we become good at something? My answer to this may seem glib, but I can't help it

00:00:09.120 --> 00:00:14.540
[Amit Varma]: because it's true. You become good at something by doing it again and again. Constant iteration

00:00:14.540 --> 00:00:18.560
[Amit Varma]: is the only way to improve. And it helps if you love this thing that you're doing again

00:00:18.560 --> 00:00:23.640
[Amit Varma]: and again, you're more engaged with it, then you care about the result, as opposed to working

00:00:23.640 --> 00:00:27.320
[Amit Varma]: in a boring office job where you're paid to do the same thing for years and years, and

00:00:27.320 --> 00:00:31.520
[Amit Varma]: you're just going through the motions. Now, when I look back on my own life, I realized

00:00:31.520 --> 00:00:36.240
[Amit Varma]: that I got good at the things I am good at by doing them again and again. But in the

00:00:36.240 --> 00:00:40.560
[Amit Varma]: beginning, I sucked. I wanted to be a writer since I was five or six years old. But when

00:00:40.560 --> 00:00:45.440
[Amit Varma]: I look at the writing I did in my 20s, and even some of my 30s, it is cringeworthy. I

00:00:45.440 --> 00:00:49.760
[Amit Varma]: was bad to begin with. Everyone is bad to begin with whenever they start whatever they're

00:00:49.760 --> 00:00:55.360
[Amit Varma]: doing. The trick is to keep at it. I started my blog India Uncut around 2003. And for five

00:00:55.360 --> 00:00:59.800
[Amit Varma]: years, I did an average of five posts a day. The 8000 posts I wrote in this time made it

00:00:59.800 --> 00:01:05.720
[Amit Varma]: a fantastic gym for my writing muscles. Iteration made me better. Now how good I am an absolute

00:01:05.720 --> 00:01:10.640
[Amit Varma]: term is not for me to judge. But I was a quantum leap ahead of where I had been. A similar

00:01:10.640 --> 00:01:14.440
[Amit Varma]: thing happened when I started podcasting. When people discover the scene in the unseen,

00:01:14.440 --> 00:01:19.120
[Amit Varma]: I asked them to listen in reverse order. I didn't know what I was doing in my early episodes.

00:01:19.120 --> 00:01:24.240
[Amit Varma]: It took a lot of time and a lot of doing to become good and a lot of thinking about my

00:01:24.240 --> 00:01:28.920
[Amit Varma]: craft. Now the thing is, when I plunged into blogging or podcasting, I wasn't thinking

00:01:28.920 --> 00:01:34.120
[Amit Varma]: about first principles, building frameworks and so on. These happened after the fact when

00:01:34.120 --> 00:01:38.000
[Amit Varma]: I was well into my journey. When I teach my writing course, for example, I try to teach

00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:42.720
[Amit Varma]: all the frameworks and principles I've learned. But I also emphasize that you have to do the

00:01:42.720 --> 00:01:47.200
[Amit Varma]: hard yards yourself. Build reading habits, build writing habits. That's the best way

00:01:47.200 --> 00:01:52.560
[Amit Varma]: to learn. Well, my guest today has had a similar journey to mine. He's learned what he knows

00:01:52.560 --> 00:01:57.400
[Amit Varma]: from decades of doing it. While learning, he's built frameworks that allow him to now

00:01:57.400 --> 00:02:02.160
