[Guest]: crossed. I think it was 42 or 43 is when I said, Okay, I can't dream this dream anymore.

00:08:48.200 --> 00:08:54.480
[Guest]: It is not possible because you can't have a I mean, it's just physically impossible.

00:08:54.480 --> 00:08:59.120
[Guest]: And although having never attempted it, actually, it suddenly realized that your dreams have

00:08:59.120 --> 00:09:04.160
[Guest]: to change. And that I think was the beginning of the factor of saying listen, a lot of other

00:09:04.160 --> 00:09:08.760
[Guest]: stuff. And, you know, there's this when you start a business, when there's always this

00:09:08.760 --> 00:09:14.880
[Guest]: feeling of, at some point in the future, there will be a point at which some great thing

00:09:14.880 --> 00:09:20.020
[Guest]: will happen. And that great thing could be you becoming rich or you becoming X or Y,

00:09:20.020 --> 00:09:27.960
[Guest]: you do at some level, get this feedback from the life, your body and all of that stuff

00:09:27.960 --> 00:09:34.360
[Guest]: that you can no longer do have those crazy dreams and they have to be achieved in a relatively

00:09:34.360 --> 00:09:41.120
[Guest]: shorter amount of time. But increasingly, and perhaps the COVID thing is kind of changes

00:09:41.120 --> 00:09:47.880
[Guest]: at least for me. I can't dream of doing these things in the future. I need to do it now.

00:09:47.880 --> 00:09:52.720
[Guest]: This I think is where at least my mind has started to change saying listen, I'm 40x and

00:09:52.720 --> 00:09:59.120
[Guest]: that 40x is closer to 50 than it is to 40. And according to my kids, at the time I reached

00:09:59.120 --> 00:10:05.480
[Guest]: 50, I would have lived half my life. I wish they're right. But I do know that, you know,

00:10:05.480 --> 00:10:09.960
[Guest]: that concept of every day, start every day saying this is the beginning of the rest of

00:10:09.960 --> 00:10:16.000
[Guest]: my life, increasingly gets more desperate, saying I better live it now. Otherwise, it

00:10:16.000 --> 00:10:21.680
[Guest]: is it's going to be so far behind that. I mean, I'm just you can't live your life thinking

00:10:21.680 --> 00:10:25.840
[Guest]: of what is going to come and you have to live your life thinking of what you are today.

00:10:25.840 --> 00:10:31.000
[Guest]: And this perhaps is a slight change in my mind. I don't know how it is for you. And

00:10:31.000 --> 00:10:37.440
[Guest]: no, this is where I think you got to focus on those little things and the big things

00:10:37.440 --> 00:10:42.000
[Guest]: all at the same time. It's a weird thing. For instance, I have my my son is in the ninth

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:53.200
[Guest]: standard. And he told me a few months back, Dad, after three years, I'm going to be gone

00:10:53.200 --> 00:10:59.800
[Guest]: doing my college. And it hit me like a brick. And you know what, I knew this. It's not like

00:10:59.800 --> 00:11:06.000
[Guest]: I didn't know this, but it hit me like a brick because three years is not a lot of time.

00:11:06.000 --> 00:11:10.160
[Guest]: We've already spent two years into the corona. And well, three years into the no two years

00:11:10.160 --> 00:11:14.840
[Guest]: into the corona. But we've literally I mean, it's it's now it, you know, catching distance

00:11:14.840 --> 00:11:20.600
[Guest]: of the point where he kind of moves. So it's not just the fact that I am growing old, that

00:11:20.600 --> 00:11:25.680
[Guest]: things are happening that should have been long term future somewhere in the I mean,

00:11:25.680 --> 00:11:30.160
[Guest]: you know, at some point, I might get diabetes kind of thing to point with I better fix my

00:11:30.160 --> 00:11:36.320
[Guest]: life before I get it today. It's induced a sense of urgency in my thought process, which

00:11:36.320 --> 00:11:43.160
[Guest]: I don't think has happened before earlier. So dealing with this growing old stuff is

00:11:43.160 --> 00:11:47.520
[Guest]: just, you know, it's mind boggling. But how is it for you? I mean, you're you're you're

00:11:47.520 --> 00:11:52.520
[Guest]: also in that phase of life because you're you've from a career perspective, I think

00:11:52.520 --> 00:11:59.040
[Guest]: you've gone through multiple phases of very deeply immersing yourself into different things.

00:11:59.040 --> 00:12:02.880
[Guest]: Does it change in the late 40s?

00:12:02.880 --> 00:12:07.800
[Amit Varma]: I think what's happened like everything you said resonated with me. And you you know,

00:12:07.800 --> 00:12:13.600
[Amit Varma]: use that interesting phrase in terms of, you know, little things and big things, little

00:12:13.600 --> 00:12:19.760
[Amit Varma]: dreams and big dreams. And one of the things that I've realized is that as far as the little

00:12:19.760 --> 00:12:24.720
[Amit Varma]: things are concerned, they can be goals. But as far as the big things are concerned, there

00:12:24.720 --> 00:12:28.760
[Amit Varma]: should be processes in the sense that you know, when you're young, you have all these

00:12:28.760 --> 00:12:33.080
[Amit Varma]: goals, I'll do this, I'll do that x, y, z, I'll write so many books, blah, blah, blah,

00:12:33.080 --> 00:12:36.480
[Amit Varma]: you have all those goals. And those goals are further tied into, you know, after I do

00:12:36.480 --> 00:12:41.120
[Amit Varma]: the book, this is how successful it will be, or whatever it is. And I think you reach a

00:12:41.120 --> 00:12:46.240
[Amit Varma]: stage in life where you realize that one, those goals are probably not going to happen.

00:12:46.240 --> 00:12:51.600
[Amit Varma]: Two, that's not necessarily a bad thing, because those goals are very often tied into something

00:12:51.600 --> 00:12:55.080
[Amit Varma]: you should not have been chasing in the first place, which is a validation of others, you

00:12:55.080 --> 00:12:58.760
[Amit Varma]: know, which is why you don't just think I'll write a good book, you think I'll write a

00:12:58.760 --> 00:13:03.840
[Amit Varma]: good book that wins an award or becomes a bestseller. Right. And I think like, if there

00:13:03.840 --> 00:13:09.480
[Amit Varma]: is one realization that I want to keep with me every moment, it's that universal human

00:13:09.480 --> 00:13:14.640
[Amit Varma]: anxiety of what other people think of you, you got to let that go. And you got to realize

00:13:14.640 --> 00:13:19.880
[Amit Varma]: that no one is thinking of you, you know, everyone's got their heads up their own ass,

00:13:19.880 --> 00:13:23.520
[Amit Varma]: everyone's obsessed with themselves. So it doesn't matter that that you know, universal

00:13:23.520 --> 00:13:30.080
[Amit Varma]: anxiety, which is there is false. You also have to redefine what you mean by happiness.

00:13:30.080 --> 00:13:36.880
[Amit Varma]: And here's the thing, it is not a fixed thing that x will make me happy, and y will not.

00:13:36.880 --> 00:13:41.640
[Amit Varma]: What makes you happy is you decide what makes you happy, it's your state of mind. Right?

00:13:41.640 --> 00:13:48.040
[Amit Varma]: So now, do I want my happiness to be dependent on achieving some random thing which is not

00:13:48.040 --> 00:13:54.400
[Amit Varma]: in my control? Or do I want to sit back and say, let me enjoy the small joys? Right? So

00:13:54.400 --> 00:13:59.320
[Amit Varma]: what I try to do rather, and those small joys can be goals, those small joys could be that

00:13:59.320 --> 00:14:04.400
[Amit Varma]: you'll get me a nice steak for lunch, for example, which itself is a small joy, right?

00:14:04.400 --> 00:14:09.360
[Amit Varma]: And, and that can be a goal. But otherwise, it should more be processes that there are

00:14:09.360 --> 00:14:14.120
[Amit Varma]: things I like doing. For example, these days, when I think of the scene and the unseen,

00:14:14.120 --> 00:14:19.520
[Amit Varma]: I do not think that I will do a kick ass episode that will get x downloads or whatever, or

00:14:19.520 --> 00:14:24.360
[Amit Varma]: so many retweets or whatever. I just think that I'll have a great conversation, you know,

00:14:24.360 --> 00:14:28.960
[Amit Varma]: that I'll just sit with a friend, and I'll have a great conversation. And my joy in the

00:14:28.960 --> 00:14:33.920
[Amit Varma]: conversation we are having right now, is not dependent on the final product, that this

00:14:33.920 --> 00:14:40.520
[Amit Varma]: will be a conversation everybody will appreciate. It is the it is it comes from the fact that

00:14:40.520 --> 00:14:45.080
[Amit Varma]: I can sit across the table with an old friend, and I'm listening to him, and he's listening

00:14:45.080 --> 00:14:49.440
[Amit Varma]: to me, and we are both comfortable. And we are at a stage where we don't need to impress

00:14:49.440 --> 00:14:52.880
[Amit Varma]: each other or think about you know, all that shit is out of the window. There's no posturing

00:14:52.880 --> 00:14:57.160
[Amit Varma]: anymore. You know, you kind of what you are. So I'm giving this as an example of a sort

00:14:57.160 --> 00:15:02.100
[Amit Varma]: of a small joy. And I've realized that it is the small joys we should focus on except

00:15:02.100 --> 00:15:07.640
[Amit Varma]: that my lament still is that I am not mindful enough. And I also realized that all the goals

00:15:07.640 --> 00:15:12.580
[Amit Varma]: that I wanted to achieve and haven't achieved, they are still within my reach, except that

00:15:12.580 --> 00:15:16.920
[Amit Varma]: it's a mistake to keep those goals in mind. If you just build the processes, those goals

00:15:16.920 --> 00:15:20.280
[Amit Varma]: will happen. Like I tell myself that, okay, all these years, you know, I mean, it's been

00:15:20.280 --> 00:15:25.840
[Amit Varma]: interesting. I've five years, I was a professional poker player. And I kind of rambled around

00:15:25.840 --> 00:15:30.520
[Amit Varma]: and did other things for a while. So I, the regret I have is I could have written 9-10

00:15:30.520 --> 00:15:34.440
[Amit Varma]: books by now. I haven't. But the reason I haven't is that I didn't put the process in

00:15:34.440 --> 00:15:38.000
[Amit Varma]: place. The reason that didn't happen is I didn't have the writing habit where I sit

00:15:38.000 --> 00:15:43.840
[Amit Varma]: down every day, write for a number of hours, where I build the mindfulness where, you know,

00:15:43.840 --> 00:15:48.120
[Amit Varma]: your mind doesn't wander all the time. You know, I didn't build a discipline that when

00:15:48.120 --> 00:15:54.040
[Amit Varma]: I'm bored, instead of reaching for my smartphone, I reach for a book, maybe your book. So I

00:15:54.040 --> 00:15:57.760
[Amit Varma]: didn't kind of build all that. So I think what I have sort of realized and when I teach

00:15:57.760 --> 00:16:02.880
[Amit Varma]: my writing course, for example, my fourth webinar is just about process. And my point

00:16:02.880 --> 00:16:07.200
[Amit Varma]: there is that listen, you know, we can, we can master the craft at an intellectual level,

00:16:07.200 --> 00:16:11.160
[Amit Varma]: we can know what is a perfect sentence, how we are building rhythm, all that shit. But

00:16:11.160 --> 00:16:16.000
[Amit Varma]: if you don't actually get your ass on the chair and actually get it done, it's no good.

00:16:16.000 --> 00:16:20.600
[Amit Varma]: And you know, and when I teach my course, I often think that I wish I had, you know,

00:16:20.600 --> 00:16:25.080
[Amit Varma]: done such a course in my early 20s, I would have learned so much. But the biggest learning

00:16:25.080 --> 00:16:32.200
[Amit Varma]: that I would have had is from sort of the process aspect. So in a sense, as far as my

00:16:32.200 --> 00:16:35.320
[Amit Varma]: personal life is concerned, and I've been very lucky also to be part of the creator

00:16:35.320 --> 00:16:39.880
[Amit Varma]: economy. And that's given me satisfaction. Like earlier for me, the satisfaction of creating

00:16:39.880 --> 00:16:44.560
[Amit Varma]: was in creating, you know, and that I think has to be a core satisfaction. But we've reached

00:16:44.560 --> 00:16:48.900
[Amit Varma]: a stage where you can see that you can be, you know, which we'll discuss, you can be

00:16:48.900 --> 00:16:54.800
[Amit Varma]: independent of a lot of the constraints that otherwise constrain creators. So all of that

00:16:54.800 --> 00:16:59.280
[Amit Varma]: is great. Like every morning, when I wake up, I can easily, you know, look around me

00:16:59.280 --> 00:17:03.120
[Amit Varma]: and say, fuck, I'm so lucky to have this or so lucky to have that and whatever. And it's

00:17:03.120 --> 00:17:08.640
[Amit Varma]: not even a big deal. It's not like but that stuff is there that, you know, and obviously

00:17:08.640 --> 00:17:13.680
[Amit Varma]: we are human. We still, you know, we still think of goals. We still say ki haan yeh karna

00:17:13.680 --> 00:17:18.200
[Amit Varma]: hai, wo karna hai and all of that. I was interested in your sort of your sporting daydreams because

00:17:18.200 --> 00:17:22.240
[Amit Varma]: I think my mind has this default mode where it goes into Walter Mitty or like Mungheri

00:17:22.240 --> 00:17:25.680
[Amit Varma]: Lal ke Haseen Sapne kind of mode and all that. Does that happen to you also?

00:17:25.680 --> 00:17:31.160
[Guest]: All the time. In fact, every single thing that you think about that says, okay, well,

00:17:31.160 --> 00:17:35.880
[Guest]: I want to do this. It becomes that Mungheri Lal ke Haseen Sapne, what happens if I did

00:17:35.880 --> 00:17:43.200
[Guest]: that? And then for instance, if I found a cure to cancer, you know, then what happens?

00:17:43.200 --> 00:17:46.920
[Guest]: How am I going to deal with the fame and this thing of it? Will I give it away for free?

00:17:46.920 --> 00:17:51.120
[Guest]: I mean, this is this is nonsense because I'm not going to discover the cure to cancer in

00:17:51.120 --> 00:17:56.320
[Guest]: all probability. But if I did, it's just nice to think about it, right? Because like you're

00:17:56.320 --> 00:18:02.040
[Guest]: building a world of your own. And in that created world, you're kind of exploring things

00:18:02.040 --> 00:18:08.120
[Guest]: that otherwise would be nonsense if you ever try to do this on stage. The fact that I can

00:18:08.120 --> 00:18:13.480
[Guest]: talk about it openly is also a symptom of my age and perhaps the creator economy where

00:18:13.480 --> 00:18:17.640
[Guest]: such a view would not be considered out of place. Perhaps 10 years ago, if I made such

00:18:17.640 --> 00:18:21.720
[Guest]: statements, it would be like Deepak, you're just so full of yourself. It's just honesty,

00:18:21.720 --> 00:18:27.360
[Guest]: but it's all of us are full of ourselves. And I just introduced my children to the Truman

00:18:27.360 --> 00:18:32.780
[Guest]: Show. You know, so there was a point in my life where I thought the whole world actually

00:18:32.780 --> 00:18:38.520
[Guest]: plotted to revolve around me. I think all of us have that at some point in our lives.

00:18:38.520 --> 00:18:45.040
[Guest]: But the Truman Show was a manifestation of it. And, you know, he makes a statement that

00:18:45.040 --> 00:18:50.520
[Guest]: I'm this is going to be part of my like, letter to, you know, on the blog and on to our this

00:18:50.520 --> 00:18:58.920
[Guest]: thing itself. But he says, you accept the reality with which you are presented. And

00:18:58.920 --> 00:19:04.760
[Guest]: I think that is a clean, clear statement that is so true when you're older. Because now

00:19:04.760 --> 00:19:09.880
[Guest]: you've seen life in so many different vantage through so many different vantage points,

00:19:09.880 --> 00:19:15.240
[Guest]: that you suddenly realize that my, you know, my outrage, my emotion, my thought process,

00:19:15.240 --> 00:19:22.240
[Guest]: very few, little of it is a function of itself. So there was moments of grief in my life,

00:19:22.240 --> 00:19:29.760
[Guest]: where it was grief. But there were moments of grief where it was induced by the narrative

00:19:29.760 --> 00:19:36.400
[Guest]: of what was shown to me. And it has never been more obvious to me than it was today.

00:19:36.400 --> 00:19:39.960
[Guest]: So when they say, you know, you're young, you're, you're probably leftist in thought

00:19:39.960 --> 00:19:44.560
[Guest]: process, that the world should be equal and all that stuff. And as you grow older, you

00:19:44.560 --> 00:19:48.040
[Guest]: become this writer, because you see all these different things. And you say that stuff doesn't

00:19:48.040 --> 00:19:53.560
[Guest]: work. And this stuff also doesn't work. But the reality is somewhere in the middle. And

00:19:53.560 --> 00:20:00.920
[Guest]: we're happy to be in those gray areas. I think that the fact is that every outrageous

00:20:00.920 --> 00:20:07.880
[Guest]: act no longer outrages you anymore, because you're looking at the motivations behind it,

00:20:07.880 --> 00:20:13.480
[Guest]: and saying, listen, I don't have to react to it the same way that the listener want

00:20:13.480 --> 00:20:18.680
[Guest]: or the speaker wants me to react to it, simply because I know they're pointing us out in

00:20:18.680 --> 00:20:23.520
[Guest]: a certain direction. I mean, this is whether you call this certain TV channels where there

00:20:23.520 --> 00:20:31.880
[Guest]: is a sun sunny kind of thing, or whether it is a news that is innocuously misleading.

00:20:31.880 --> 00:20:36.480
[Guest]: It may be anything, it may be a commentator in like, I mean, Formula One recently, there

00:20:36.480 --> 00:20:42.360
[Guest]: was a there was a big issue with the last race. In the last race, the race director

00:20:42.360 --> 00:20:48.960
[Guest]: changed or interpreted the rules for his own sake. And to a person who's watched it for

00:20:48.960 --> 00:20:54.840
[Guest]: a while, it's not that that particular event was the problem. There was a history to it.

00:20:54.840 --> 00:20:58.920
[Guest]: There's a fact that Hamilton's been winning. There's a fact that people had been getting

00:20:58.920 --> 00:21:04.520
[Guest]: those boredom and such. You to have a final race that is exciting has not happened for

00:21:04.520 --> 00:21:10.780
[Guest]: like 10 years, you take that history in context, you can see why he made the decisions he did.

00:21:10.780 --> 00:21:16.280
[Guest]: But if you take it from the rulebook context, he was wrong. So it's very interesting because

00:21:16.280 --> 00:21:24.680
[Guest]: he brought more popularity to the game by that one act, then the fact that he was censured

00:21:24.680 --> 00:21:28.880
[Guest]: for it, and banned or whatever, he's been taken out of it and all that stuff. But it

00:21:28.880 --> 00:21:33.680
[Guest]: made the game made it made it exciting, which is what the whole game is designed to. Otherwise,

00:21:33.680 --> 00:21:37.480
[Guest]: what's the point was watching cars go at 300 kilometers per hour. It's exciting because

00:21:37.480 --> 00:21:42.080
[Guest]: there is some excitement in it and the commentary and all of this. But this is, this is where

00:21:42.080 --> 00:21:45.400
[Guest]: you realize that I would have never thought of this when I was younger, I would have made

00:21:45.400 --> 00:21:49.760
[Guest]: up stance saying he was wrong. And now I'm sitting there saying, dude, you know what,

00:21:49.760 --> 00:21:53.740
[Guest]: there's a bunch of things to it. And in the Truman show, there was a there was a particular

00:21:53.740 --> 00:21:59.680
[Guest]: piece of time when they had to cut the transmission of this 10,000 hours of continuous transmission

00:21:59.680 --> 00:22:03.480
[Guest]: and suddenly they had to cut it. And there was an empty screen. And one guy comes in

00:22:03.480 --> 00:22:09.200
[Guest]: and says, you know, the sponsors are threatening to cut that. And the director of this whole

00:22:09.200 --> 00:22:14.240
[Guest]: thing, he says, well, we've never had so many views of a blank screen of the actual show

00:22:14.240 --> 00:22:18.840
[Guest]: as we have of this blank screen going on right now. So it's true, right? Because you're you're

00:22:18.840 --> 00:22:26.080
[Guest]: the reason you're you're generating that excitement is now is considered bad in all traditional

00:22:26.080 --> 00:22:32.720
[Guest]: aspects. But you're getting exactly what you wanted out of it was viewership, sponsorship,

00:22:32.720 --> 00:22:40.320
[Guest]: recognition, fame, whatever it is. So maybe this growing old is just earlier, I would

00:22:40.320 --> 00:22:47.640
[Guest]: be like, that is wrong. Why? Why should that be the case? Now I'm like, no, maybe the process

00:22:47.640 --> 00:22:57.160
[Guest]: is the objective. The goal is not the objective. How I got there is what I wanted to achieve.

00:22:57.160 --> 00:23:03.000
[Guest]: Whether I get there or not is irrelevant. If I got my fame from not doing something,

00:23:03.000 --> 00:23:07.640
[Guest]: then from doing something, and the fame is what I wanted in the first place. So there

00:23:07.640 --> 00:23:13.600
[Guest]: we are. And it's very interesting. I'll probably segue into different contexts in this in finance

00:23:13.600 --> 00:23:20.000
[Guest]: itself. I have a very clear thought process over here, which is in finance, it is not

00:23:20.000 --> 00:23:27.920
[Guest]: the person who makes the highest returns that wins. Warren Buffett hasn't made great returns

00:23:27.920 --> 00:23:34.080
[Guest]: for the last 15 years. And he's still winning yet. And he's winning because, you know, people

00:23:34.080 --> 00:23:39.040
[Guest]: aren't, you know, selling his company or telling them that they need to replace this guy because

00:23:39.040 --> 00:23:42.320
[Guest]: he's not making great returns. They're still quoting anything that he says, they still

00:23:42.320 --> 00:23:49.480
[Guest]: go to him every time there's a crisis. The point is, he's done this without focusing

00:23:49.480 --> 00:23:54.080
[Guest]: on the one thing that everybody wants to focus on, which is can I make 10 rupees 20 rupees

00:23:54.080 --> 00:23:58.400
[Guest]: can I make 10 rupees 25 rupees? If I made it 25, am I better than the guy who made it

00:23:58.400 --> 00:24:06.760
[Guest]: 20? The answer is no. It's the guy whose embodiment of how he got there, which makes it exciting,

00:24:06.760 --> 00:24:12.600
[Guest]: he can make 10 rupees 12 rupees and he might still be more valuable as an as a person than

00:24:12.600 --> 00:24:18.320
[Guest]: the person who made 20 or 25. As you grow older, I think the stark realization that

00:24:18.320 --> 00:24:24.280
[Guest]: it's the it's the journey and not the destination. To me at least, I mean, it was a it was a

00:24:24.280 --> 00:24:28.560
[Guest]: proverb earlier, enjoy the journey. And now it's like, it's hitting you on the face. It's

00:24:28.560 --> 00:24:33.680
[Guest]: like, dude, this is it. This is what you are. Your journey is who you are, where you get

00:24:33.680 --> 00:24:39.580
[Guest]: from here. Even if you got into a lot of money or a lot of whatever, is just a byproduct

00:24:39.580 --> 00:24:46.360
[Guest]: of whatever you did to get there. So, although this is a very long segue from where we are.

00:24:46.360 --> 00:24:51.200
[Guest]: And what are your thoughts? I mean, do you do you feel now that you would focus a lot

00:24:51.200 --> 00:24:57.760
[Guest]: more on the journey? Like you said, the conversations, the fact that they give you those little joys

00:24:57.760 --> 00:25:04.160
[Guest]: than just the destination, which is, I mean, I don't know what the destination is anymore.

00:25:04.160 --> 00:25:08.320
[Guest]: It's like, I got somewhere and suddenly it became all hazy, right? I wrote a book, I

00:25:08.320 --> 00:25:12.960
[Guest]: want to write 10 more books, because I feel I've not written enough. And then I feel I've

00:25:12.960 --> 00:25:20.480
[Guest]: written too much in certain cases. What was the song? I forget. The one in which he says,

00:25:20.480 --> 00:25:26.040
[Guest]: I haven't said enough. I've said too much. And then I haven't said enough. So, I mean,

00:25:26.040 --> 00:25:30.200
[Guest]: at the time, you would never understand what the lyric meant. Suddenly at 47, I'm like,

00:25:30.200 --> 00:25:34.360
[Amit Varma]: okay, I know what that means. That's a very with or without you sentiment. I think this

00:25:34.360 --> 00:25:38.240
[Amit Varma]: whole thing about journey and destination ties into process and goals, right? That for

00:25:38.240 --> 00:25:42.480
[Amit Varma]: me, the journey is really the process and the goals take care of themselves. But to

00:25:42.480 --> 00:25:46.720
[Amit Varma]: double click on a couple of things you mentioned, one, the way I would view that Formula One

00:25:46.720 --> 00:25:53.000
[Amit Varma]: differently than you is I would just think that, okay, Hamilton and Max, whatever his

00:25:53.000 --> 00:25:58.160
[Amit Varma]: name is, and they're both going to die, the cars are both going to be scrap, you know,

00:25:58.160 --> 00:26:02.240
[Amit Varma]: eventually in the longer scheme of things, the longer that you look at it, so who cares.

00:26:02.240 --> 00:26:06.160
[Amit Varma]: So sometimes I kind of feel like that, but you want to enjoy the ride in the moment.

00:26:06.160 --> 00:26:10.700
[Amit Varma]: I also want to and by the way, that quote, which you referred to about I think it goes

00:26:10.700 --> 00:26:15.520
[Amit Varma]: to the effect of, if you're not a socialist at 18, you don't have a heart. If you're not

00:26:15.520 --> 00:26:20.600
[Amit Varma]: a capitalist at 25, you don't have a brain, which is resonant. And I think both of us

00:26:20.600 --> 00:26:24.720
[Amit Varma]: would kind of agree with that. But I want to double back on what you said about being

00:26:24.720 --> 00:26:30.200
[Amit Varma]: full of ourselves, you know, what some people might say. And I think here's the deal. Number

00:26:30.200 --> 00:26:35.560
[Amit Varma]: one, I think it's important as both of us would I think have the self reflection to

00:26:35.560 --> 00:26:41.520
[Amit Varma]: say that, you know, that there is no such thing called an adult in that sense of somebody

00:26:41.520 --> 00:26:46.200
[Amit Varma]: who has figured everything out, you know, so it's a little bit of posturing when you

00:26:46.200 --> 00:26:52.040
[Amit Varma]: act with that certain kind of like, you spoke about your Mungheri Lal moments, and I'm sure

00:26:52.040 --> 00:26:57.040
[Amit Varma]: I have them as well. And we are both in a sense complex messes, except that we learn

00:26:57.040 --> 00:27:03.120
[Amit Varma]: to kind of control the complexity and think about it a bit more. And I think one of the

00:27:03.120 --> 00:27:09.080
[Amit Varma]: important padaavs to, I don't know why I thought of that term from Kaun Banega Crorepati, but

00:27:09.080 --> 00:27:14.560
[Amit Varma]: one of the important padaavs that we have to kind of get past is to just stop posturing

00:27:14.560 --> 00:27:18.640
[Amit Varma]: at some points in time. We spend too much of our life posturing to others and even posturing

00:27:18.640 --> 00:27:24.160
[Amit Varma]: to ourselves about what kind of person we are. And I think maybe a time comes where

00:27:24.160 --> 00:27:29.400
[Amit Varma]: you give a little bit more to self reflection. And you stop a little bit of the posturing

00:27:29.400 --> 00:27:34.160
[Amit Varma]: and you get a little more comfortable in your own skin. This is who I am. If there is a

00:27:34.160 --> 00:27:40.560
[Amit Varma]: word T-H-A-T, I can only pronounce it as that, right? And I don't care if, you know, I don't

00:27:40.560 --> 00:27:44.880
[Amit Varma]: even want to consciously try too hard to correct it, because this is who I am. I'm happy kind

00:27:44.880 --> 00:27:48.880
[Amit Varma]: of being authentic. You are happy kind of being authentic. And I think one of the big

00:27:48.880 --> 00:27:52.680
[Amit Varma]: secrets of the creator economy really, and one of the things that I stress upon when

00:27:52.680 --> 00:27:57.600
[Amit Varma]: I speak to young creators, is that just be true to yourself, be authentic to yourself.

00:27:57.600 --> 00:28:02.880
[Amit Varma]: Because that is the only thing you have that sort of, you know, sets you apart from everyone

00:28:02.880 --> 00:28:05.200
[Amit Varma]: else. So, so yeah, that's, that's kind of

00:28:05.200 --> 00:28:10.360
[Guest]: interesting that you bring that up, because the creator economy is a lot about authenticity,

00:28:10.360 --> 00:28:17.480
[Guest]: right? So in the sense of, I think you and I've heard you walk us through a presentation

00:28:17.480 --> 00:28:23.560
[Guest]: of how to think about the creator economy. And it's interesting here, because this authenticity

00:28:23.560 --> 00:28:29.000
[Guest]: angle was always something that was shied, people told me that don't do it, don't be

00:28:29.000 --> 00:28:33.880
[Guest]: authentic, because there is this formal prose that you have to follow, certain things have

00:28:33.880 --> 00:28:38.120
[Guest]: to be in the passive voice, certain things have to be in the active voice, there is,

00:28:38.120 --> 00:28:41.960
[Guest]: you should have, you should start a sentence with Dear Sir, or whatever, it's like, it's

00:28:41.960 --> 00:28:46.720
[Guest]: like a set of rules that you have to follow. Which is why even today, when we when when

00:28:46.720 --> 00:28:52.520
[Guest]: I get, let's say, people who want to write for Capital Mind, they send us the stuff,

00:28:52.520 --> 00:28:56.760
[Guest]: it looks like this is manufactured from a textbook. And then I'm like, no, no, you

00:28:56.760 --> 00:29:05.000
[Guest]: don't want people and I feel lousy saying this. But I have to tell people unlearn the

00:29:05.000 --> 00:29:10.680
[Guest]: textbook writing process and move to. So what is it about the creator economy that has changed

00:29:10.680 --> 00:29:16.280
[Guest]: this whole thing? And, you know, you've seen this, I mean, you've you've been you India

00:29:16.280 --> 00:29:20.720
[Guest]: uncut was one of the most popular blogs. And I think that's when I first came in touch,

00:29:20.720 --> 00:29:25.760
[Guest]: we got in touch. That's where I met. I was also blogging at the time. And so I was talking

00:29:25.760 --> 00:29:31.920
[Guest]: money, you're talking so many other things. And then we saw the IPM fiasco at that time.

00:29:31.920 --> 00:29:37.680
[Guest]: And then onwards to that. It's a very interesting time, because I think India uncut was very

00:29:37.680 --> 00:29:45.160
[Guest]: refreshing because it was from the heart. It was like if I read Amit Verma in a magazine,

00:29:45.160 --> 00:29:50.760
[Guest]: they would somehow take you and put a suit on you. And you know, they would edit out

00:29:50.760 --> 00:29:56.560
[Guest]: the aspects that were you. So that it fit into this, say, business standard or whatever

00:29:56.560 --> 00:30:00.800
[Guest]: it was, I would think that I would like it's like, it's like when you write for one of

00:30:00.800 --> 00:30:05.700
[Guest]: these newspaper type things, you had to change your thought process, but or change your writing

00:30:05.700 --> 00:30:12.040
[Guest]: process. But on India uncut, I could see you as Amit Verma. It to me that was important,

00:30:12.040 --> 00:30:16.680
[Guest]: but suddenly it's become important to the whole world. It's not just me, it's the I

00:30:16.680 --> 00:30:21.360
[Guest]: mean, when I was when we were doing this, there was a small clique of people blogging.

00:30:21.360 --> 00:30:26.600
[Guest]: And we had a reasonable, I think, thought process on fan club. What's changed from that

00:30:26.600 --> 00:30:31.200
[Guest]: early blogging media to maybe the creator economy, as you've seen?

00:30:31.200 --> 00:30:35.240
[Amit Varma]: So a number of things that I'm happy to kind of take you in detail, like I did in the presentation

00:30:35.240 --> 00:30:40.000
[Amit Varma]: through all the various phases and all the things that have changed, but about the intimate

00:30:40.000 --> 00:30:46.420
[Amit Varma]: economy, what I call the intimate creator economy. Here's the thing. When we are consuming

00:30:46.420 --> 00:30:50.900
[Amit Varma]: content, when you're consuming art or consuming entertainment in the 70s or 80s, the stars

00:30:50.900 --> 00:30:55.320
[Amit Varma]: you admire are larger than life, right? They are not your friends, they are larger than

00:30:55.320 --> 00:30:59.560
[Amit Varma]: life they're up there, you're building temples for Amitabh Bachchan and so on and so forth.

00:30:59.560 --> 00:31:06.160
[Amit Varma]: That is, yeah, that is kind of what it is. And that's come a full circle today, where

00:31:06.160 --> 00:31:10.200
[Amit Varma]: a podcaster, like podcasters like you and me are a voice in somebody's head. So when

00:31:10.200 --> 00:31:15.000
[Amit Varma]: I listen to a podcast that I love, maybe by Bass Roberts or Tyler Cowen or whatever, somebody's

00:31:15.000 --> 00:31:19.160
[Amit Varma]: voice in my head, it feels like an intimate connection. Let me sort of draw a metaphor

00:31:19.160 --> 00:31:24.560
[Amit Varma]: I've spoken about before, to sort of illustrate that. Let's say, let's look at the audiovisual

00:31:24.560 --> 00:31:29.140
[Amit Varma]: medium, right? Let's say you go to watch a movie in a theatre, there's a certain distance

00:31:29.140 --> 00:31:33.360
[Amit Varma]: between you and the screen, right? And there's a similar distance between the camera and

00:31:33.360 --> 00:31:37.400
[Amit Varma]: the actors. So you'll have your grand western and there is that distance and there is that

00:31:37.400 --> 00:31:42.280
[Amit Varma]: scale. Now, when you watch something in a television, the TV screen is a couple of meters

00:31:42.280 --> 00:31:46.680
[Amit Varma]: away from you. And the camera is that much distance away from the actor. So you have

00:31:46.680 --> 00:31:51.120
[Amit Varma]: friends in Seinfeld and those kind of indoor settings, five, six people, that's, that's

00:31:51.120 --> 00:31:56.400
[Amit Varma]: what you get. If you're watching something on your laptop, it's, you know, it's less

00:31:56.400 --> 00:32:03.360
[Amit Varma]: than a meter. And a lot of made for YouTube content is like that. It's much closer. Now,

00:32:03.360 --> 00:32:08.040
[Amit Varma]: where I look at it in terms of audio, and why I always say that podcasting is very different

00:32:08.040 --> 00:32:13.400
[Amit Varma]: from radio, it's not radio on demand. The reason is that radio is more like television.

00:32:13.400 --> 00:32:16.880
[Amit Varma]: It's kind of broadcasting. I think of radio as you're driving in your car with four other

00:32:16.880 --> 00:32:21.600
[Amit Varma]: people in a radio speaking to all of you, it is playing on the speaker, just as a kind

00:32:21.600 --> 00:32:27.520
[Amit Varma]: of a metaphor, in the sense that because of all kinds of imperatives and incentives, in

00:32:27.520 --> 00:32:32.360
[Amit Varma]: India, for example, there'll be the high license fees and all of that. They don't have a choice

00:32:32.360 --> 00:32:38.600
[Amit Varma]: but to go wide and not to go too deep. As our mutual friend Trane Panicker says, you

00:32:38.600 --> 00:32:43.120
[Amit Varma]: are a mile wide and an inch deep, right? I love that phrase. And that's kind of what

00:32:43.120 --> 00:32:48.880
[Amit Varma]: radio is. Now in some places you like, I believe New York has some 70-80 FM stations and it's

00:32:48.880 --> 00:32:53.040
[Amit Varma]: a different whatever, but even there, there's only so far you can go. In India, you've just

00:32:53.040 --> 00:32:58.080
[Amit Varma]: got to play your Bollywood music and be very mainstream and you can't approach any niche.

00:32:58.080 --> 00:33:03.640
[Amit Varma]: Now podcasting is the most intimate thing of all. It's a voice in your head. And people

00:33:03.640 --> 00:33:07.960
[Amit Varma]: listening to me know this, like the kind of love I've got from my listeners. It makes

00:33:07.960 --> 00:33:14.040
[Amit Varma]: me tear up, right? You feel the connection, how deep it is. And I feel that way for podcasters

00:33:14.040 --> 00:33:20.440
[Amit Varma]: I listen to, or, you know, even people whose vlogs I watch these days on YouTube, for example,

00:33:20.440 --> 00:33:24.080
[Amit Varma]: you feel like you, you know, this person is your friend, you're worried that if you come

00:33:24.080 --> 00:33:28.680
[Amit Varma]: across him in the mall, you'll just slap him on the back and say, hey, how's your, you

00:33:28.680 --> 00:33:33.520
[Amit Varma]: know, how's your cold now? Are you better? That kind of thing. And this changes the way

00:33:33.520 --> 00:33:37.920
[Amit Varma]: that you approach your content then, because if you're on radio, you are kind of broadcasting,

00:33:37.920 --> 00:33:41.280
[Amit Varma]: you have a certain kind of voice, a certain kind of, you know, like Ameen Sayani will

00:33:41.280 --> 00:33:45.040
[Amit Varma]: speak in the Ameen Sayani way and he's beautiful and charming and it's lovely, but he belongs

00:33:45.040 --> 00:33:49.760
[Amit Varma]: to everyone. He doesn't belong to you alone. Right? And so people will ask me things while

00:33:49.760 --> 00:33:54.320
[Amit Varma]: podcasting that, you know, do I need to do voice modulation course and all of that and

00:33:54.320 --> 00:33:59.320
[Amit Varma]: all that nonsense. And I say, no, all you need to do is you need to talk normally, like

00:33:59.320 --> 00:34:03.280
[Amit Varma]: yourself, like the way we are talking to each other is the way we talk to each other, right?

00:34:03.280 --> 00:34:08.440
[Amit Varma]: There's, you know, just making sure we avoid cuss words, but that's pretty much, in my

00:34:08.440 --> 00:34:13.960
[Amit Varma]: case, not even that, frankly, but that's pretty much what it is. And that's what listeners

00:34:13.960 --> 00:34:18.760
[Amit Varma]: love that you are who you are, they feel like they know you, there's a straightforwardness

00:34:18.760 --> 00:34:23.560
[Amit Varma]: to it. And especially if you're not pretending, if you're not posturing, because over a period

00:34:23.560 --> 00:34:27.280
[Amit Varma]: of time, you can't fake it, you are who you are. Like, I used to watch Big Boss a lot

00:34:27.280 --> 00:34:31.200
[Amit Varma]: back in the day. I think I even I was kind of tweeting about like almost live tweeting

00:34:31.200 --> 00:34:37.480
[Amit Varma]: about it in 2008, 2009, whatever, you know, I just found it fascinating. And the thing

00:34:37.480 --> 00:34:41.960
[Amit Varma]: is, they know there's a camera, right? But they know there's a camera for a little while,

00:34:41.960 --> 00:34:46.120
[Amit Varma]: but then they lapse. And then they are who they are. You are who you are and your personality

00:34:46.120 --> 00:34:51.080
[Amit Varma]: expresses itself. So you can't fake it too much. You know, especially when you do a podcast

00:34:51.080 --> 00:34:55.800
[Amit Varma]: over a period of time like I have when I'm following my curiosities. I think people appreciate

00:34:55.800 --> 00:35:00.800
[Amit Varma]: that I might say something in one episode and 10 episodes later, I might say I was wrong

00:35:00.800 --> 00:35:05.920
[Amit Varma]: there or this is how my views have evolved, and so on and so forth. You know, and I think

00:35:05.920 --> 00:35:09.960
[Amit Varma]: that that's a massive feature. Now, as far as the people who, for example, come to you

00:35:09.960 --> 00:35:14.200
[Amit Varma]: and they sound like a textbook, one of the pieces of advice I give in my writing course

00:35:14.200 --> 00:35:20.240
[Amit Varma]: is, and it's really standard, it's not like a new insight from me, is that read out everything

00:35:20.240 --> 00:35:26.560
[Amit Varma]: you have written. If it sounds like something you would say, then that's fine. If it doesn't

00:35:26.560 --> 00:35:30.800
[Amit Varma]: sound like something you would say, you know, like, for example, after due consideration,

00:35:30.800 --> 00:35:36.280
[Amit Varma]: we have whatever you we don't talk like that, right? So then, if it then it is contrived,

00:35:36.280 --> 00:35:40.120
[Amit Varma]: and it will sound contrived to the reader also. And because they're not used to it,

00:35:40.120 --> 00:35:44.920
[Amit Varma]: they'll have to work that much harder to process it. And all good writers get this. Like a

00:35:44.920 --> 00:35:51.040
[Amit Varma]: classic example I give, which is a great example in across so many domains is Bob Dylan's blowing

00:35:51.040 --> 00:35:54.440
[Amit Varma]: in the wind, right? So your key line there is the answer my friend is blowing in the

00:35:54.440 --> 00:35:58.600
[Amit Varma]: wind. You could also instead of saying the answer my friend is blowing in the wind, you

00:35:58.600 --> 00:36:04.500
[Amit Varma]: could have said the response comrade is wafting in the breeze. Right? Now, why is that bad?

00:36:04.500 --> 00:36:09.120
[Amit Varma]: That is bad because answer is a word we will use when we are speaking not response. And

00:36:09.120 --> 00:36:14.880
[Amit Varma]: we will say my friend, we won't say comrade unless we are from whatever particular, yeah,

00:36:14.880 --> 00:36:20.120
[Amit Varma]: yeah, or the CPIM somewhere, but and we won't say wafting in the breeze, we'll say blowing

00:36:20.120 --> 00:36:24.400
[Amit Varma]: in the wind. It's really natural language like in one of my webinars, I talk a lot about

00:36:24.400 --> 00:36:29.560
[Amit Varma]: Shakespeare, whose language seems so archaic to us today, but it was a common speech of

00:36:29.560 --> 00:36:33.480
[Amit Varma]: his day. You know, if you look at how many words Shakespeare used that are more than

00:36:33.480 --> 00:36:38.700
[Amit Varma]: two syllables, there are very few, he's using the common language of the day, he's creating

00:36:38.700 --> 00:36:43.360
[Amit Varma]: great art, which at the same time, makes him a box office superstar. He was a Spielberg

00:36:43.360 --> 00:36:48.360
[Amit Varma]: plus Yash Chopra of his time. So I think that this just this one piece of advice to anyone

00:36:48.360 --> 00:36:52.600
[Amit Varma]: who's writing that read out what you have written. Does it sound like because you know,

00:36:52.600 --> 00:36:57.280
[Amit Varma]: Deepak, we know a lot of writer friends in common, right? Devangshu Dutta, Nilanjanaroy,

00:36:57.280 --> 00:37:01.400
[Amit Varma]: all of these people, Salil Tripathi, you know, whenever we read whenever I read anything

00:37:01.400 --> 00:37:05.560
[Guest]: by them, I can hear it in their voice. Yes, it's like they're talking. It's like they're

00:37:05.560 --> 00:37:11.160
[Amit Varma]: talking because it's natural to them. Because they're not trying too hard. They're not trying

00:37:11.160 --> 00:37:16.880
[Amit Varma]: to be too writerly or verbose or so many people will read this, I have to do something special

00:37:16.880 --> 00:37:21.240
[Amit Varma]: and all of that. They're just kind of being themselves. And of course, they're not making

00:37:21.240 --> 00:37:25.000
[Amit Varma]: a lot of the mistakes that we make in our speech, like I'll say very and I'll put adverbs

00:37:25.000 --> 00:37:29.120
[Amit Varma]: and I'll do um and ah and all of that because when we are talking, there's no filter. But

00:37:29.120 --> 00:37:35.120
[Amit Varma]: when you're sort of so you know, an old editor of mine Tim Delisle, once who wrote this great

00:37:35.120 --> 00:37:38.560
[Amit Varma]: book I'd recommend to all my listeners called the Cornell guide to how to write well, it's

00:37:38.560 --> 00:37:44.400
[Amit Varma]: on Kindle unlimited, you can read it in a couple of hours. He once said that good writing

00:37:44.400 --> 00:37:48.800
[Amit Varma]: is like enhanced conversation. So it's like, you know, that old phrase goes right as you

00:37:48.800 --> 00:37:52.960
[Amit Varma]: speak, people misunderstand it. They think it means that the way you're speaking, you

00:37:52.960 --> 00:37:57.520
[Amit Varma]: just write like that. That's not what it means. Because if you did that, you'd be reproducing

00:37:57.520 --> 00:38:01.200
[Amit Varma]: all the you know, the mistakes we make while speaking because we don't have a filter. So

00:38:01.200 --> 00:38:07.440
[Amit Varma]: the ums and the ahs and the run on sentences or whatever. No, it's that it's enhanced conversation.

00:38:07.440 --> 00:38:11.320
[Amit Varma]: But right as you speak means that when you write something and you when you say it out,

00:38:11.320 --> 00:38:17.240
[Amit Varma]: it should sound like it's you. And therefore that textbook thing goes away. If you just

00:38:17.240 --> 00:38:22.760
[Amit Varma]: you know, that textbook thing completely kind of goes away. And this is and this is something

00:38:22.760 --> 00:38:26.880
[Amit Varma]: I see in streams as well in the vlogs I watch, that people are just being themselves and

00:38:26.880 --> 00:38:32.600
[Amit Varma]: there is a charm to that. You know, creators today should not think that, oh my god, you

00:38:32.600 --> 00:38:37.040
[Amit Varma]: know, like, I occasionally teach this podcasting course, I do like two cohorts a year, unlike

00:38:37.040 --> 00:38:41.880
[Amit Varma]: my monthly writing course. And people will sometimes ask that, you know, what is my USP?

00:38:41.880 --> 00:38:46.480
[Amit Varma]: Like, should I even do it? Or what makes me special? I'm not a domain expert in anything.

00:38:46.480 --> 00:38:52.280
[Amit Varma]: And my point always is that, boss, you just have to be you, because you are on a journey,

00:38:52.280 --> 00:38:55.680
[Amit Varma]: which many other people share, intellectual journey, journey through life, they are at

00:38:55.680 --> 00:38:59.200
[Amit Varma]: different points of it. Some may even be ahead of you. But the fact that you are on that

00:38:59.200 --> 00:39:05.000
[Amit Varma]: journey immediately makes them empathize and makes them curious and makes that connection

00:39:05.000 --> 00:39:09.200
[Amit Varma]: happen. And here's the other thing, which feeds into something we were talking about

00:39:09.200 --> 00:39:13.320
[Amit Varma]: earlier, where I lamented the lack of mindfulness. Now I did a recent episode with the writer

00:39:13.320 --> 00:39:20.280
[Amit Varma]: Amitabh Kumar, which I just loved. And one of the things we discussed was how writing

00:39:20.280 --> 00:39:26.160
[Amit Varma]: every day, not only enriches your appreciation of life, because the act of writing every

00:39:26.160 --> 00:39:30.400
[Amit Varma]: day means you're sitting down, you're thinking about something that would otherwise just

00:39:30.400 --> 00:39:35.560
[Amit Varma]: have passed, and you're capturing it, it also changes a little bit of you. That every day

00:39:35.560 --> 00:39:41.140
[Amit Varma]: with whatever you write in a day, it can be a couple of hundred words a day, you are sitting

00:39:41.140 --> 00:39:48.600
[Amit Varma]: down in a quiet space. And, you know, get thinking about something that is kind of improving

00:39:48.600 --> 00:39:54.380
[Amit Varma]: you. And there, I think lies the magic that maybe I'm on a journey of trying to figure

00:39:54.380 --> 00:39:59.080
[Amit Varma]: something out, maybe trying to figure my society out or whatever. Now, I need not necessarily

00:39:59.080 --> 00:40:03.640
[Amit Varma]: be smarter or more knowledgeable than anyone listening to me. But the very fact that there

00:40:03.640 --> 00:40:08.960
[Amit Varma]: is that moment of examination, where I am sitting down and thinking about something

00:40:08.960 --> 00:40:12.840
[Amit Varma]: is something that others can share in. And then they can think with me and they can feel

00:40:12.840 --> 00:40:17.600
[Amit Varma]: part of the process. So which is and just an anecdote about this whole intimacy thing

00:40:17.600 --> 00:40:21.640
[Amit Varma]: that I did an episode with Abhinandan Sekri where we spoke for four hours when I went

00:40:21.640 --> 00:40:26.760
[Amit Varma]: to Delhi. One listener wrote in to me to say that I felt so much like I'm sitting with

00:40:26.760 --> 00:40:31.320
[Amit Varma]: two friends in a living room, that at one point I interrupted you before I realized

00:40:31.320 --> 00:40:37.360
[Amit Varma]: that I'm not there. Right. And I was so touched by this. You know, and I can only hope that

00:40:37.360 --> 00:40:40.560
[Guest]: people listening to us right now feel that way as well.

00:40:40.560 --> 00:40:47.120
[Guest]: No, no, it's, it's so true. Because sometimes in a conversation, that is the ultimate, right?

00:40:47.120 --> 00:40:52.760
[Guest]: Because you're, you know, that you're in there, and you're speaking. And so I often think

00:40:52.760 --> 00:41:02.840
[Guest]: about this. If in a podcast, and I almost force the user to stop there and say, hang

00:41:02.840 --> 00:41:09.080
[Guest]: on, I have a point that I want to make over here. That is when you know that you've touched

00:41:09.080 --> 00:41:14.760
[Guest]: the soul of the person who's on the other side. I don't know if people do it. I mean,

00:41:14.760 --> 00:41:19.200
[Guest]: nobody tells me like somebody has actually told you about this, which is like awesome.

00:41:19.200 --> 00:41:23.600
[Guest]: But I think that is the ultimate if I saw someone listening to my podcast, pause the

00:41:23.600 --> 00:41:27.480
[Guest]: podcast and say shit, you know what, this just triggered this thought in my mind that

00:41:27.480 --> 00:41:31.480
[Guest]: I have to kind of get out right now because it's there. It's part of the conversation

00:41:31.480 --> 00:41:38.600
[Guest]: that we're in on right now. And the realization that you can't because but so it's, it's,

00:41:38.600 --> 00:41:45.080
[Guest]: it's something that says you achieved something in that podcast. Or in the it's like, if you're

00:41:45.080 --> 00:41:49.680
[Guest]: having a conversation with someone, and there's one line that strikes you, and you take that

00:41:49.680 --> 00:41:54.480
[Guest]: away, and you will never forget that line, it may not make any sense for you to remember

00:41:54.480 --> 00:41:58.940
[Guest]: the context in which that conversation actually happened. But the fact that that line impacted

00:41:58.940 --> 00:42:04.480
[Guest]: you or something impacted you so deeply, is part of you know, your learning process and

00:42:04.480 --> 00:42:09.480
[Guest]: your joys and, and the fact that that conversation left you a little bit, you know, higher in

00:42:09.480 --> 00:42:14.720
[Guest]: dopamine levels or, you know, the thought process levels. This is, maybe this is just

00:42:14.720 --> 00:42:21.240
[Guest]: again, part of growing old, that you enjoy this a lot more than you enjoy partying and

00:42:21.240 --> 00:42:27.720
[Guest]: doing all the other stuff that, you know, perhaps you enjoy more as a kid. But this

00:42:27.720 --> 00:42:33.440
[Guest]: is the part where I think that that intimacy thing matters, and matters deeply in the sense

00:42:33.440 --> 00:42:39.760
[Guest]: that without it today, I feel like you're watching a news broadcast where somebody is

00:42:39.760 --> 00:42:46.760
[Guest]: just reading out from a teleprompter with no emotion other than where do I put the pause.

00:42:46.760 --> 00:42:51.860
[Guest]: So you know, and another point of what you just mentioned, which was, don't speak as

00:42:51.860 --> 00:42:59.040
[Guest]: you are speaking, I found that often I violated that construct. So for instance, I use a phrase

00:42:59.040 --> 00:43:05.240
[Guest]: called Abhayar and I use this Abhayar in my writing. I saw that and I found it charming.

00:43:05.240 --> 00:43:11.400
[Guest]: It was interesting because I was like, if someone put this question to me, I'd say Abhayar

00:43:11.400 --> 00:43:17.360
[Guest]: wait, this is not how this thing does. Instead of me, in a normal point, I would edit out

00:43:17.360 --> 00:43:22.200
[Guest]: the Abhayar wait and then tell you exactly what follows with that, right. But putting

00:43:22.200 --> 00:43:28.000
[Guest]: the Abhayar wait in the writing is somehow more appealing to the reader because he's

00:43:28.000 --> 00:43:32.480
[Guest]: almost like, okay, this is what he's trying to say, he's saying, you know, hold off. And

00:43:32.480 --> 00:43:37.760
[Guest]: for some strange reason, it works. I mean, it works at least for a few people who read

00:43:37.760 --> 00:43:43.360
[Guest]: what I have to write. But it's very interesting in that it works from an aspect of violating

00:43:43.360 --> 00:43:48.720
[Guest]: that very rule, which was a rule in my own head saying, you know, remove the, I should

00:43:48.720 --> 00:43:53.920
[Guest]: go to this Toastmasters thing. There was this R counter concept, there's a person who counts

00:43:53.920 --> 00:43:59.080
[Guest]: the number of errs and ahs and ums in the business, and you're supposed to reduce your

00:43:59.080 --> 00:44:05.640
[Guest]: R count over time. I'm like, no, in writing, you can have a little bit of an R count.

00:44:05.640 --> 00:44:12.160
[Amit Varma]: I think where it comes in is that that's a voice. If your voice is Abhayar, like in your

00:44:12.160 --> 00:44:17.000
[Amit Varma]: book, there are these moments of humor, which like I can't recall one offhand, but there

00:44:17.000 --> 00:44:23.060
[Amit Varma]: are these moments of humor in different places. I'm like, this is a typical Deepak Joke. Typical,

00:44:23.060 --> 00:44:27.200
[Amit Varma]: you know, and I'm sure you know what I'm talking about. But there are a whole bunch of those.

00:44:27.200 --> 00:44:30.720
[Amit Varma]: And it's very charming, because I know you, but even if I didn't know you, I would I would

00:44:30.720 --> 00:44:34.520
[Amit Varma]: know you a little better, just by seeing that and there you're being true to yourself. See,

00:44:34.520 --> 00:44:39.760
[Amit Varma]: I think one core point is this, and why this kind of content appeals to both of us, and

00:44:39.760 --> 00:44:46.040
[Amit Varma]: to so many people is that we live in a constructed world. Okay, everything is constructed. Like

00:44:46.040 --> 00:44:50.280
[Amit Varma]: you said, TV pay, things are being presented in a particular way. Radio pay, things are

00:44:50.280 --> 00:44:54.480
[Amit Varma]: being everywhere, things are being presented in a particular way. Social media is nothing

00:44:54.480 --> 00:44:59.400
[Amit Varma]: but people posturing and, you know, I am so virtuous, or I am so sanskari or whatever

00:44:59.400 --> 00:45:05.480
[Amit Varma]: shit it is, right? And where are the real connections? Right? And it is not true that

00:45:05.480 --> 00:45:09.960
[Amit Varma]: we are happy to be in this constructed world and all of that nonsense. I think people at

00:45:09.960 --> 00:45:15.320
[Amit Varma]: some level, crave those real connections, where, for example, when they listen to me

00:45:15.320 --> 00:45:21.240
[Amit Varma]: talking to a guest, maybe that, you know, sometimes we will have different point of

00:45:21.240 --> 00:45:26.820
[Amit Varma]: views and we'll, you know, discuss them in a civil way. But sometimes we won't be sure.

00:45:26.820 --> 00:45:31.920
[Amit Varma]: And that's also okay, because certainty is constructed when you come across it. Right?

00:45:31.920 --> 00:45:35.660
[Amit Varma]: So we are recording with all this Russia, Ukraine thing. And so much of the commentary

00:45:35.660 --> 00:45:41.120
[Amit Varma]: about it is going to be random people giving random gyan in hindsight, right? And constructing

00:45:41.120 --> 00:45:45.240
[Amit Varma]: narratives. I think, you know, I did an episode with Rukmini, the data journalist, and she

00:45:45.240 --> 00:45:49.640
[Amit Varma]: told me about this TV program she was watching at the time of some election, I think the

00:45:49.640 --> 00:45:54.800
[Amit Varma]: last UP election or whatever, where at one point, they had the wrong result. So then

00:45:54.800 --> 00:45:58.840
[Amit Varma]: all the experts started giving gyan on the wrong result that you see, this is what has

00:45:58.840 --> 00:46:02.540
[Amit Varma]: happened. And this has been mobilized and that has been mobilized. And then suddenly

00:46:02.540 --> 00:46:05.960
[Amit Varma]: they realized that the result is the other thing and has gone the other way. And the

00:46:05.960 --> 00:46:10.280
[Amit Varma]: same experts are giving gyan, you see, this is not hard to figure out this is the dynamic

00:46:10.280 --> 00:46:16.160
[Amit Varma]: here and all of that bullshit, right? And it is that constructed world. It is that artifice

00:46:16.160 --> 00:46:21.200
[Amit Varma]: that I think, you know, many of us, even if everybody has a bullshit detector, you may

00:46:21.200 --> 00:46:26.080
[Amit Varma]: not specifically know that what so and so is saying is bullshit, because you may not

00:46:26.080 --> 00:46:31.960
[Amit Varma]: know that domain. But you have a sense boss, you know, and then when you you have people

00:46:31.960 --> 00:46:35.880
[Amit Varma]: who are not trying to construct anything like you and I, we're not trying to present a point

00:46:35.880 --> 00:46:41.360
[Amit Varma]: of view or present this or whatever, you know, and there is a charm to that, which is why

00:46:41.360 --> 00:46:46.800
[Amit Varma]: you know, very early on, I remember, someone sent me some advice that, you know, your show

00:46:46.800 --> 00:46:50.280
[Amit Varma]: should be much crisper, you should make them 10 minutes, you divide it into point wise

00:46:50.280 --> 00:46:54.680
[Amit Varma]: format and all that. And I was like, boss, I'm not doing an explainer. I understand the

00:46:54.680 --> 00:46:58.960
[Amit Varma]: value of an explainer, you know, and the person who sent me this advice, by the way, went

00:46:58.960 --> 00:47:03.480
[Amit Varma]: on to YouTube and does really good explainer. So credit to him, you know, but I was doing

00:47:03.480 --> 00:47:09.240
[Amit Varma]: something different. And there's just a lot of value to that for me. And these are just

00:47:09.240 --> 00:47:13.800
[Amit Varma]: such, you know, in a sense, like, I wonder what you feel about this. But I think both

00:47:13.800 --> 00:47:20.560
[Amit Varma]: you and I, in a sense, are really lucky to be alive. And this old at this precise time,

00:47:20.560 --> 00:47:26.760
[Amit Varma]: because you think about it, we were born in the mid 70s, broadly, right. And we have grown

00:47:26.760 --> 00:47:33.880
[Amit Varma]: up in a sense in an analog world, right. And we've grown up in an analog world. And we

00:47:33.880 --> 00:47:38.160
[Amit Varma]: have had one kind of education where you read every book you get your hands on, because

00:47:38.160 --> 00:47:43.960
[Amit Varma]: books are scarce, you put put together a mixtape of music that you like, it is so special,

00:47:43.960 --> 00:47:49.320
[Amit Varma]: you're trying to woo someone, you make a mixtape for them. It is a big freaking deal, right?

00:47:49.320 --> 00:47:53.080
[Amit Varma]: It's it's it's, you know, when you write when you communicate with other people, when you

00:47:53.080 --> 00:47:57.640
[Amit Varma]: write letters to them, you write long letters, you actually sit down and you put a little

00:47:57.640 --> 00:48:01.840
[Amit Varma]: bit of yourself into each letter you write, and it's not all functional. And then we come

00:48:01.840 --> 00:48:07.960
[Amit Varma]: into the internet, when we are adults, and the whole world is kind of opened up for us.

00:48:07.960 --> 00:48:12.760
[Amit Varma]: And then we have a second education. And this is like another layer that is happening. And

00:48:12.760 --> 00:48:19.600
[Amit Varma]: the result is that where we are sitting, we've had these multiple educations, we've been

00:48:19.600 --> 00:48:23.840
[Amit Varma]: enterprising enough to kind of go with the different flows that we've gone with, but

00:48:23.840 --> 00:48:30.920
[Amit Varma]: we don't take it for granted. Like, I think people born, say, in 1995, will take some

00:48:30.920 --> 00:48:35.240
[Amit Varma]: of it for granted. And they may not even have experienced that heraf. They may not have

00:48:35.240 --> 00:48:40.360
[Amit Varma]: experienced boredom. What is the value of boredom? You know, does a kid who always has

00:48:40.360 --> 00:48:47.200
[Amit Varma]: a smartphone with her? And and there, you know, does she know that what it is for the

00:48:47.200 --> 00:48:52.440
[Amit Varma]: mind to be that empty space where it can just wander, and it can think about stuff. And

00:48:52.440 --> 00:48:58.160
[Amit Varma]: in that thinking, you also, you know, find things about yourself. Like one cliche that

00:48:58.160 --> 00:49:01.720
[Amit Varma]: I keep, I say cliche, because I keep coming back to it. It's not a cliche. It's a great

00:49:01.720 --> 00:49:06.760
[Amit Varma]: insight by Jonathan Hyatt, where he says that, sure, we have the internet and all of history

00:49:06.760 --> 00:49:11.320
[Amit Varma]: available to us. But everybody is consuming something that was made in the last three

00:49:11.320 --> 00:49:20.680
[Amit Varma]: days. Wow. Right. Wow. I want to find ways to break past that in my own life, I'm a victim.

00:49:20.680 --> 00:49:26.920
[Amit Varma]: This is not a lament about others. It's a it's a sort of complaint about myself to myself,

00:49:26.920 --> 00:49:31.040
[Amit Varma]: that too often, I'm like kind of sitting there and instead of reading a book, I'll go online

00:49:31.040 --> 00:49:35.840
[Amit Varma]: and I'll, you know, I'll go to sites, I'll play a little online chess and get my dopamine

00:49:35.840 --> 00:49:41.240
[Amit Varma]: and all of that. And I'll just do a bunch of different things. But I am going from moment

00:49:41.240 --> 00:49:45.440
[Amit Varma]: to moment from shallow moment to shallow moment to shallow moment to shallow moment. And I

00:49:45.440 --> 00:49:49.400
[Amit Varma]: think all of us, you know, everybody who's listening to this, also, I know you agree

00:49:49.400 --> 00:49:54.280
[Amit Varma]: with me, this is like a common struggle, that how do we get past this, because you almost

00:49:54.280 --> 00:50:00.160
[Amit Varma]: feel trapped. Like I played poker professionally for a few years, right? So I, it's one of

00:50:00.160 --> 00:50:04.600
[Amit Varma]: the things I looked into, like the first time I went to Goa, right. And I went to Goa for

00:50:04.600 --> 00:50:10.320
[Amit Varma]: three, four years without seeing a beach. Because I would just, you know, go to Panjim,

00:50:10.320 --> 00:50:14.760
[Amit Varma]: break into whatever hotel I'm in. And then I'd go to my offshore casino, which in those

00:50:14.760 --> 00:50:19.680
[Amit Varma]: days was Casino Royale. And there was another one called Pride. And over there, what a casino

00:50:19.680 --> 00:50:24.440
[Amit Varma]: does is that there are no windows. So you don't know, you don't have daylight or anything,

00:50:24.440 --> 00:50:30.140
[Amit Varma]: there are no clocks, they pump in oxygenated air to keep you fresh for long periods of

00:50:30.140 --> 00:50:34.800
[Amit Varma]: time. And so I remember once I started playing at two o'clock, and I thought, oh, it must

00:50:34.800 --> 00:50:38.480
[Amit Varma]: be four o'clock after a while of playing and I found it's nine o'clock, you have no sense

00:50:38.480 --> 00:50:42.800
[Amit Varma]: of time, time just passes, they want to keep people fresh and gambling, right? And I would

00:50:42.800 --> 00:50:45.800
[Amit Varma]: of course, play the one game there that is a game of skill, everything else you're playing

00:50:45.800 --> 00:50:52.400
[Amit Varma]: against the house. And I kind of studied that a bit, bought a couple of books on that which

00:50:52.400 --> 00:50:58.640
[Amit Varma]: are linked from the show notes. And from the 70s, 80s, 90s onwards, there is a science

00:50:58.640 --> 00:51:04.680
[Amit Varma]: about how to get people addicted, how to keep people addicted, to the extent that the noises

00:51:04.680 --> 00:51:10.160
[Amit Varma]: and the music that a slot machine makes is all particularly designed to trigger the brain

00:51:10.160 --> 00:51:14.760
[Amit Varma]: in different ways. So you keep sitting, and there are patterns by which somebody monitoring

00:51:14.760 --> 00:51:19.400
[Amit Varma]: it from a control room. If you're sitting at a slot machine, and you sat for two hours,

00:51:19.400 --> 00:51:23.720
[Amit Varma]: three hours, whatever someone from a control room can see from your patterns of play, and

00:51:23.720 --> 00:51:28.560
[Amit Varma]: their past data, when you're about to get up. And then they will send somebody down

00:51:28.560 --> 00:51:32.520
[Amit Varma]: who will say, sir, because you know, you've sat here for so long, you must be tired. Let's

00:51:32.520 --> 00:51:36.360
[Amit Varma]: give you a complimentary drink, and they'll give you a drink, and then you keep playing.

00:51:36.360 --> 00:51:40.480
[Amit Varma]: And this is a science that's there in the 80s or 90s. So everything that you see on

00:51:40.480 --> 00:51:46.160
[Amit Varma]: social media today, was mastered by the whole gambling business a long time back and why

00:51:46.160 --> 00:51:52.120
[Amit Varma]: the common thread is addiction. So today, all these big social media sites, they keep

00:51:52.120 --> 00:51:58.240
[Amit Varma]: us hooked, they keep us addicted in this constant feedback loop of shallow impressions. Like

00:51:58.240 --> 00:52:02.160
[Amit Varma]: one of the cleverest one was some social media sites. They did it so that when you earlier

00:52:02.160 --> 00:52:06.760
[Amit Varma]: when you hit the back button, you get out of the app. Today, in most of these sites,

00:52:06.760 --> 00:52:12.200
[Amit Varma]: you hit the back button, the page refreshes. Wow, like Pinterest, I think I see something

00:52:12.200 --> 00:52:17.280
[Amit Varma]: else will come up. So you can't leave, you're kind of stuck there, right? And you can spend

00:52:17.280 --> 00:52:23.480
[Amit Varma]: five hours on Instagram or whatever your social media poison of choice is. And you you've

00:52:23.480 --> 00:52:30.960
[Amit Varma]: been busy, you haven't been bored, you know, but and I think that is sort of the challenge

00:52:30.960 --> 00:52:35.680
[Amit Varma]: that people like you and I face and it ties in with that whole question of time like one

00:52:35.680 --> 00:52:40.040
[Amit Varma]: of the questions I wanted to ask you, when I was reading your book, is that like number

00:52:40.040 --> 00:52:44.160
[Amit Varma]: one, I wish again, I'd read your book in my 20s, because I would have made so many better

00:52:44.160 --> 00:52:48.640
[Amit Varma]: decisions. But critically, you know, you've given great advice on how to spend your money.

00:52:48.640 --> 00:52:53.040
[Amit Varma]: Tell me something about your thoughts on how to spend your time because time is an equally

00:52:53.040 --> 00:52:57.240
[Amit Varma]: scarce resource. And what you know, what's the thinking you've done on it? How do you

00:52:57.240 --> 00:53:03.320
[Guest]: how do you kind of maximize that? A lot of things lead into it, all of the stuff that

00:53:03.320 --> 00:53:08.200
[Guest]: you mentioned, one of the things that I'll talk about time is, there are certain times

00:53:08.200 --> 00:53:15.520
[Guest]: at which having a lot of options is complicated. It's that, you know, that, you know, choices,

00:53:15.520 --> 00:53:20.000
[Guest]: choices, choices, dialogue that happened. And I think when Harry met Sally, at some

00:53:20.000 --> 00:53:25.900
[Guest]: point, this was, this was a revelation to me, because having less to do at a certain

00:53:25.900 --> 00:53:32.440
[Guest]: point is actually a benefit. We don't realize it. And I'll tell you, you know, so many thoughts

00:53:32.440 --> 00:53:37.800
[Guest]: over here. So let me explore a few. So one of the things over here is my college days,

00:53:37.800 --> 00:53:44.480
[Guest]: I was in a college called KRSE Suratkal. We had a beach next to the college and in the

00:53:44.480 --> 00:53:48.400
[Guest]: beach, there was a big rock. And I would sit on that rock. And I would look at the sea

00:53:48.400 --> 00:53:53.600
[Guest]: and I would dream and think and sometimes you really know what you are going to think

00:53:53.600 --> 00:53:57.280
[Guest]: about. And sometimes you know exactly what you're going to think. And you would go there

00:53:57.280 --> 00:54:01.920
[Guest]: and you let your mind wander. It would go it would go strange places. And I remember

00:54:01.920 --> 00:54:09.160
[Guest]: those places today because I would remember something that is very difficult to do today

00:54:09.160 --> 00:54:13.200
[Guest]: because you have a phone that can instantly you can sit on the beach and keep listening

00:54:13.200 --> 00:54:19.680
[Guest]: to the waves and watch some random YouTube shots and all of that stuff and ruin the experience

00:54:19.680 --> 00:54:25.280
[Guest]: because you have to let that boredom build a thought thread of its own that allows you

00:54:25.280 --> 00:54:29.120
[Guest]: to explore and you're not building that you're just letting someone else dictate that from

00:54:29.120 --> 00:54:34.240
[Guest]: you because you know, a tennis shot that was fantastic. Of course, it's a great shot Federer

00:54:34.240 --> 00:54:42.760
[Guest]: and Nadal and all that stuff. But does that is that taking away from that building thought

00:54:42.760 --> 00:54:49.880
[Guest]: process that would have germinated an idea that could have been very different in your

00:54:49.880 --> 00:54:53.800
[Guest]: own thought process many years later. And I see this as it's both good and bad. I'll

00:54:53.800 --> 00:54:57.600
[Guest]: tell you why. In my college days, I didn't have too much of an input. The inputs were

00:54:57.600 --> 00:55:01.960
[Guest]: largely books, you would kind of look at them and kind of thing. Today, I have multiple

00:55:01.960 --> 00:55:07.320
[Guest]: sorts of thoughts of input. So whether it's electric vehicles at some level or that, you

00:55:07.320 --> 00:55:11.760
[Guest]: know, like some of the thoughts that you just we just talked about and you said, when people

00:55:11.760 --> 00:55:17.480
[Guest]: don't trust, you can't really trust what what people are saying, because all manufactured,

00:55:17.480 --> 00:55:23.400
[Guest]: you trust the authenticity of a person who's coming in. But in the past, people use this

00:55:23.400 --> 00:55:29.520
[Guest]: for religion. Religion was there was a God who could not be untrue to you. And he was

00:55:29.520 --> 00:55:35.040
[Guest]: your truth. And therefore it was your garden if multiple peoples kind of came in together

00:55:35.040 --> 00:55:40.720
[Guest]: and said, my God is my truth. And then they all said, maybe it's the same God and then

00:55:40.720 --> 00:55:46.520
[Guest]: they made it a religion. And in a way that was the same their their way to fight the

00:55:46.520 --> 00:55:51.720
[Guest]: fact that there was an unreal, you know, manufactured world out there, perhaps in whatever little

00:55:51.720 --> 00:55:56.600
[Guest]: way that was it was. But what's happened with time today, and perhaps spending time is more

00:55:56.600 --> 00:56:04.560
[Guest]: important than spending money is that you can choose to spend it in 100 different ways.

00:56:04.560 --> 00:56:10.280
[Guest]: But you can't choose to spend it on boredom unless you actually make an attempt to do

00:56:10.280 --> 00:56:14.320
[Guest]: so. Which means it's not it doesn't mean locking you up in a room. It means can you take a

00:56:14.320 --> 00:56:20.440
[Guest]: walk without having a phone and a your music on or you know, things like that. I know many

00:56:20.440 --> 00:56:25.360
[Guest]: people for whom this is just simply for me, it becomes like I need a Bluetooth headset

00:56:25.360 --> 00:56:31.020
[Guest]: and a podcast to be on so that I can walk. But I want to want something to keep triggering

00:56:31.020 --> 00:56:37.280
[Guest]: my thinking. And I'm like, at this point, I need some time to just think that that that

00:56:37.280 --> 00:56:44.520
[Guest]: song that Fursat Ke Raat Din, you know, that Fursat Ke Raat Din are not there anymore.

00:56:44.520 --> 00:56:49.960
[Guest]: And it's a valuable resource because that word Fursat has a very deep meaning to me.

00:56:49.960 --> 00:56:56.200
[Guest]: It is that the boredom germinates ideas and those ideas are very valuable for you to build

00:56:56.200 --> 00:57:04.420
[Guest]: in a later life. So with the kids now, with my kids, for instance, I see the minute they

00:57:04.420 --> 00:57:09.520
[Guest]: get bored, they want to touch a device and you know, accept something. The devices have

00:57:09.520 --> 00:57:16.000
[Guest]: figured it out. The device also figured out that you need some Fursat in terms of less

00:57:16.000 --> 00:57:20.040
[Guest]: activity when you're doing something. So I'll give you one of the examples. There's a YouTube

00:57:20.040 --> 00:57:27.280
[Guest]: Shorts and there's Instagram Reels. You can't forward them. You can only watch this short,

00:57:27.280 --> 00:57:32.960
[Guest]: they're not very long, but you can't go forward, you can't just skip to the end. So you actually

00:57:32.960 --> 00:57:37.840
[Guest]: have to watch the whole thing. And like, okay, they're doing this because they know that

00:57:37.840 --> 00:57:45.160
[Guest]: your mind is racing forward. And if you are given the option to go, you would go. But

00:57:45.160 --> 00:57:51.000
[Guest]: they want to keep you there. So they're building that that Fursat thing right there. But they're

00:57:51.000 --> 00:57:55.160
[Guest]: not giving you time to think that they're going to keep the screen on at all points

00:57:55.160 --> 00:58:00.360
[Guest]: in time. And this is, in one sense, very evil, because it takes away from that point of saying,

00:58:00.360 --> 00:58:04.280
[Guest]: listen, I just want to watch this, I want to go think about it. You're not giving me

00:58:04.280 --> 00:58:09.240
[Guest]: the opportunity to do so. But at the same time addicting me with all the addiction influences

00:58:09.240 --> 00:58:15.800
[Guest]: that you build. To get out of this, you have to have a mindset that says I will not conform.

00:58:15.800 --> 00:58:23.840
[Guest]: And I need to get out of this to just think. This is a point I think, very few of us, I'll

00:58:23.840 --> 00:58:28.280
[Guest]: give you one example. A lot of people I know told me this in the last two years. Deepak,

00:58:28.280 --> 00:58:37.080
[Guest]: I miss international travel. I said, why? Two hours or eight hours of just me. You can't,

00:58:37.080 --> 00:58:40.480
[Guest]: I mean, you may have a laptop or something like that. But many of them are like, you

00:58:40.480 --> 00:58:46.280
[Guest]: know, I use that time to think, because there is no internet at the time. Well, I hope not,

00:58:46.280 --> 00:58:51.080
[Guest]: but it's coming soon. But assuming that, you know, it's flaky is not going to happen. But

00:58:51.080 --> 00:58:54.360
[Guest]: you just have your laptop, at best you have some movie that's playing, but you can switch

00:58:54.360 --> 00:59:00.200
[Guest]: it off. But at the time, it's you time. And that you time I think is very important. And

00:59:00.200 --> 00:59:07.000
[Guest]: so people I know who travel have gotten cranky about it. In the sense that they said, listen,

00:59:07.000 --> 00:59:13.240
[Guest]: I don't have that time anymore. So I'm just losing it by, you know, not having those moments

00:59:13.240 --> 00:59:19.640
[Guest]: of relief and release. More important than money is finding the space that you can do

00:59:19.640 --> 00:59:24.760
[Guest]: this. Now, whether it takes money to do this or not, I don't know. But you know, it's like,

00:59:24.760 --> 00:59:32.360
[Guest]: sometimes we would just sit in a coffee shop and sip coffee and do nothing. And you know,

00:59:32.360 --> 00:59:36.920
[Guest]: sometimes just sit in front of each other and not even talk. Can we do that right now

00:59:36.920 --> 00:59:43.000
[Guest]: in any meaningful way? I think the day you do that you're richer than most other people are.

00:59:43.000 --> 00:59:49.000
[Guest]: And although I mean, we are also guilty because we're building a podcast that gives him so many

00:59:49.000 --> 00:59:53.320
[Guest]: ideas in so many different ways, that perhaps people are like, okay, you're listening, I'm

00:59:53.320 --> 00:59:57.960
[Guest]: listening to this, I'm getting my own ideas. But I'm not taking the time out right now,

00:59:57.960 --> 01:00:04.040
[Guest]: because I want to listen to what comes next. But I think it's important to bring that point out to

01:00:04.040 --> 01:00:09.320
[Guest]: say, get out there and be a little bit of, you know, finally, and this is where writing helps,

01:00:09.320 --> 01:00:14.280
[Guest]: right? Because writing discovers you in a way that you haven't discovered yourself. So when

01:00:14.280 --> 01:00:20.040
[Guest]: you write something down, you say, is that what I am what I'm thinking? And sometimes it is stupid,

01:00:20.040 --> 01:00:25.000
[Guest]: the sentences don't string together, they don't make any sense. But sometimes you'll find yourself

01:00:25.000 --> 01:00:28.840
[Guest]: becoming a Dave Barry. And I like Dave Barry, because he's one of the people who's really

01:00:28.840 --> 01:00:35.640
[Guest]: inspired me to be myself. Once he wrote a sentence that lasted an entire full page,

01:00:35.640 --> 01:00:42.360
[Guest]: and half of the next. And it ended with warning, warning, we are now reaching the end of the

01:00:42.360 --> 01:00:48.120
[Guest]: sentence. So, because the sentence just kept on rambling and going, I'm like, you know what,

01:00:48.120 --> 01:00:55.720
[Guest]: he can write like this. It's like I'm in his head. And he in the process of writing this,

01:00:55.720 --> 01:01:00.040
[Guest]: he's probably discovered a little boat about himself when he did it. And the only way I

01:01:00.040 --> 01:01:05.240
[Guest]: could have figured that out was when I wrote that Abeyar or whatever it was, it was me with my head

01:01:05.240 --> 01:01:11.480
[Guest]: writing what was on the what was on the page. And I think it ties into the concept of time in the

01:01:11.480 --> 01:01:16.840
[Guest]: sense of how do you spend how do you spend your time meaningfully is perhaps to not spend your

01:01:16.840 --> 01:01:25.320
[Guest]: time meaningfully is to find meaning in whatever you whatever you're thinking rather than in trying

01:01:25.320 --> 01:01:32.120
[Guest]: to spend your time doing something specific. When you talked about the process, one of the

01:01:32.120 --> 01:01:36.520
[Guest]: things that I think you should be included in in any longer term thought processes,

01:01:36.520 --> 01:01:41.960
[Guest]: the time to sit back and say, dude, I don't know what's happening. But this is my postmortem or

01:01:41.960 --> 01:01:47.960
[Guest]: my thought process is where I just let my mind think it should be the part of the process itself,

01:01:48.520 --> 01:01:52.920
[Guest]: rather than saying, this is the process and I'll go outside of it and think of the process

01:01:52.920 --> 01:01:56.440
[Guest]: at a later point. So give yourself that for 10 minutes of I don't know what this is,

01:01:56.440 --> 01:02:03.480
[Guest]: but I have to take some time out and think, do you find that fursat thing meaningful or exciting?

01:02:03.480 --> 01:02:09.960
[Amit Varma]: It's very meaningful. But what has happened is we've gotten so used to our addictions of

01:02:09.960 --> 01:02:14.760
[Amit Varma]: constant sensation and dopamine hits and all that it becomes difficult. Like I remember a long time

01:02:14.760 --> 01:02:20.120
[Amit Varma]: back, I'd recorded this episode with Santosh Desai on Indian society of the last 30 years.

01:02:20.120 --> 01:02:24.040
[Amit Varma]: And in the intro of that, I think I did some kind of dream sequence where I imagined

01:02:24.040 --> 01:02:29.400
[Amit Varma]: somebody just sitting in a cafe without a smartphone. And everybody else is looking

01:02:29.400 --> 01:02:33.080
[Amit Varma]: into a screen. And there is this one person who doesn't have anything and they're looking around

01:02:33.080 --> 01:02:37.720
[Amit Varma]: and gradually everyone notices this one person. And it's spooky because it's like a psychopath,

01:02:37.720 --> 01:02:42.520
[Amit Varma]: right? What kind of person would do something like that? And there was this interesting Twitter

01:02:42.520 --> 01:02:47.800
[Amit Varma]: thread by one of my writing students, Gurpreya, who is based in Bangalore. And the thread was

01:02:47.800 --> 01:02:51.720
[Amit Varma]: about how she's found a couple of times when she's sitting in a cafe by herself,

01:02:52.520 --> 01:02:57.320
[Amit Varma]: people on other tables, you know, girls or mixed groups or whatever will say, Oh, you're alone,

01:02:57.320 --> 01:03:01.640
[Amit Varma]: why don't you join us? Which is really interesting. But the interesting part, the part that really

01:03:01.640 --> 01:03:06.200
[Amit Varma]: struck me was she said that I wasn't looking into my smartphone. And she said that had I been looking

01:03:06.200 --> 01:03:10.440
[Amit Varma]: into my smartphone, nobody would have disturbed me. But I wasn't looking into my smartphone.

01:03:10.440 --> 01:03:15.080
[Amit Varma]: And therefore, there is this human connection and maybe new friends and whatever. And I find

01:03:15.080 --> 01:03:20.280
[Amit Varma]: that very touching. Right? And you know, it's where are those human connections is a question

01:03:20.280 --> 01:03:25.320
[Amit Varma]: you have to ask. And it's a question in multiple levels. And I'll throw you another related question,

01:03:25.320 --> 01:03:33.800
[Amit Varma]: which is, I have in recent years, been thinking about, okay, before I come to this, you had said

01:03:33.800 --> 01:03:37.640
[Amit Varma]: something earlier about how at one point, you thought you were the center of the world and

01:03:37.640 --> 01:03:42.360
[Amit Varma]: everything was made for you. So I quickly dug up this Douglas Adams quote, I love the quote about

01:03:42.360 --> 01:03:47.480
[Amit Varma]: a puddle. Have you heard it? No, no, no, no. So let me read this out for you. This is Douglas Adams.

01:03:47.480 --> 01:03:51.720
[Amit Varma]: Imagine a puddle waking up one morning and thinking, this is an interesting world I find

01:03:51.720 --> 01:03:56.760
[Amit Varma]: myself in an interesting hole I find myself in fits me rather neatly, doesn't it? In fact,

01:03:56.760 --> 01:04:02.120
[Amit Varma]: it fits me staggeringly well, must have been made to have me in it. This is such a powerful idea

01:04:02.120 --> 01:04:07.320
[Amit Varma]: that as the sun rises in the sky, and the air heats up, and as gradually the puddle gets smaller

01:04:07.320 --> 01:04:11.640
[Amit Varma]: and smaller, is still frantically hanging on to the notion that everything's going to be all right,

01:04:11.640 --> 01:04:16.280
[Amit Varma]: because this world was meant to have him in it was built to have a minute. So the moment it

01:04:16.280 --> 01:04:20.760
[Amit Varma]: disappears, catches him rather by surprise. I think this might be something we need to be on

01:04:20.760 --> 01:04:26.760
[Amit Varma]: the watch out for. Stop quote, right. And I just love this quote, our over inflated sense of

01:04:26.760 --> 01:04:31.400
[Amit Varma]: ourselves as a species and also at a personal level. And the question I was coming to is this

01:04:31.400 --> 01:04:38.600
[Amit Varma]: that Kant, not Amitabh Kant, but the philosopher Immanuel Kant, you know, once coined, like he

01:04:38.600 --> 01:04:43.400
[Amit Varma]: coined a number of categorical imperatives. And one of them was this, that never treat another

01:04:43.400 --> 01:04:50.440
[Amit Varma]: person as a means to an end, treat them as an end in itself. And I think of this and I think

01:04:50.440 --> 01:04:58.280
[Amit Varma]: that, is it the case that much of my life is really me being this puddle, me being at the

01:04:58.280 --> 01:05:04.120
[Amit Varma]: center of everything, and everybody else is a character in my play, they are instrumental to me.

01:05:05.240 --> 01:05:11.560
[Amit Varma]: And I'm not trying hard enough to look at them as real people. And I think that this is actually

01:05:11.560 --> 01:05:17.480
[Amit Varma]: perhaps a default mode for most of us. And you have to become mindful and try a little harder

01:05:17.480 --> 01:05:24.680
[Amit Varma]: to make those connections and to not sort of do this. You know, for example, Stephen Covey once

01:05:24.680 --> 01:05:29.640
[Amit Varma]: said, talking about conversation and listening, Stephen Covey said, most people don't listen to

01:05:29.640 --> 01:05:34.280
[Amit Varma]: understand, they listen to respond. Right. And what is the key point here, the key point is that

01:05:34.280 --> 01:05:39.320
[Amit Varma]: you and I are having a conversation, but I might be listening to you waiting to jump in at some

01:05:39.320 --> 01:05:44.040
[Amit Varma]: point. So I can show how clever I am, or how right I am, and so on and so forth. And it becomes my

01:05:44.040 --> 01:05:49.800
[Amit Varma]: ego. So then the conversation becomes completely about my ego. I'm not really listening. And I

01:05:49.800 --> 01:05:56.440
[Amit Varma]: arrived at the ethic of never interrupting any of my guests in conversation, you know, and I just

01:05:56.440 --> 01:06:01.080
[Amit Varma]: find that listening is beautiful when people open up to you. Like, first of all, it's an enormous

01:06:01.080 --> 01:06:05.880
[Amit Varma]: privilege when people open up to you. I did an episode with Mrinal Pandey, I asked her my first

01:06:05.880 --> 01:06:10.840
[Amit Varma]: question, she spoke for an hour. Yeah, I just sat and listened. And it was magic, you got to listen

01:06:10.840 --> 01:06:15.240
[Amit Varma]: to that. And so many people wrote in young people wrote in saying this made us cry. We send it to

01:06:15.240 --> 01:06:20.360
[Amit Varma]: our parents. Right. And if I interrupt her in the third minute, and I say, Oh, can you tell me a

01:06:20.360 --> 01:06:25.400
[Amit Varma]: little bit more about this? The magic is doesn't happen. The magic is gone. You know, so you kind

01:06:25.400 --> 01:06:29.480
[Amit Varma]: of sit back and listen. And even there, you could say I'm treating her as instrumental because I'm

01:06:29.480 --> 01:06:34.200
[Amit Varma]: getting a good episode out of it. We don't know our own, you know, there is a scene and the unseen

01:06:34.200 --> 01:06:39.720
[Amit Varma]: about the things that we do as well. So what are your thoughts on this? Like, when you, you know,

01:06:39.720 --> 01:06:45.800
[Amit Varma]: you grow older, you have family, you have kids, you know, they're real people, you know, you have

01:06:45.800 --> 01:06:51.800
[Amit Varma]: colleagues in this wonderful, incredibly swank high tech office of yours. So, you know, is this

01:06:51.800 --> 01:06:56.520
[Guest]: something you've thought about? Well, it happens all the time, to be honest, you know, it's very

01:06:56.520 --> 01:07:01.000
[Guest]: weird, because sometimes somebody comes to you with a problem. And I'm sure all of us have

01:07:01.000 --> 01:07:06.520
[Guest]: experienced this at some point. Amit, you know what, there's this thing that's happening with

01:07:06.520 --> 01:07:10.600
[Guest]: with Russia and Ukraine. And you know, I can't understand what's happening. And now you're

01:07:10.600 --> 01:07:14.760
[Guest]: listening. And you're not saying anything. And I'm going to, you know, Russia's attacked Ukraine,

01:07:14.760 --> 01:07:18.600
[Guest]: and it's doing all this thing. And then we're worried about what happens to, you know, the

01:07:18.600 --> 01:07:23.240
[Guest]: prices of crude, but how long can Russia attack? You know what, can it keep on attacking? Well,

01:07:23.240 --> 01:07:30.120
[Guest]: no. And while I'm talking to you about this, the clarity starts to appear in my own head.

01:07:30.120 --> 01:07:35.880
[Guest]: You almost don't have to do anything. You almost like literally looking at me and saying go on.

01:07:35.880 --> 01:07:43.320
[Guest]: And at some point, I come to a conclusion that the fear and the anger and the thing that I came

01:07:43.320 --> 01:07:49.800
[Guest]: with, half of it is evaporated simply because I've talked it out to you at one level. And I've

01:07:49.800 --> 01:07:57.560
[Guest]: discovered, I mean, this is me being a little sexist is that my XY chromosome, the Y portion

01:07:57.560 --> 01:08:05.400
[Guest]: missed that little element of understanding when it was only time to listen. And when it was time

01:08:05.400 --> 01:08:11.560
[Guest]: to give suggestions or take action to my wife to the to this day is like, this is only for listening.

01:08:12.360 --> 01:08:20.200
[Guest]: So I shut up and listen. And it's incredibly, you know, I'm a rational person, I like to say,

01:08:20.200 --> 01:08:25.960
[Guest]: but I none of us are rational. So this is one of my behavioral traits that just gets me is that I

01:08:25.960 --> 01:08:34.520
[Guest]: don't get it, that I have to just listen sometimes. And it's okay if it doesn't leave with an answer.

01:08:34.520 --> 01:08:38.680
[Guest]: And even if you know the answer, or if you know that there is there are five things I can suggest

01:08:38.680 --> 01:08:43.640
[Guest]: to you that would give you that would solve this problem. Sometimes I don't have to solve the

01:08:43.640 --> 01:08:49.400
[Guest]: problem. It's just that the person wants to enter talk or something like that. I use this often as

01:08:49.400 --> 01:08:54.520
[Guest]: a one way communication on Twitter to wait. At this point, I don't even care what people are

01:08:54.520 --> 01:09:00.840
[Guest]: responding to me about because I is not meant for a response. It is just me talking, but I can do

01:09:00.840 --> 01:09:05.800
[Guest]: that on Twitter because I'm comfortable with it. But in person, when a person sitting in front of

01:09:05.800 --> 01:09:11.800
[Guest]: it almost like, if he's telling me this, it's my duty to respond to that person and give him advice

01:09:11.800 --> 01:09:20.920
[Guest]: or give my gyan on it and all that. But much as I I mean, much as I find that this is a behavioral

01:09:20.920 --> 01:09:27.640
[Guest]: problem of us not listening, I think to a large extent, we're not we find you know, this concept

01:09:27.640 --> 01:09:32.520
[Guest]: of just listening is like reading a book, because the author is talking to you, you aren't talking

01:09:32.520 --> 01:09:37.000
[Guest]: to the author. Right? So and you have no problem with that, because that's what you want to do.

01:09:37.000 --> 01:09:41.320
[Guest]: You want to hear the why do we find it so difficult to do this in person is something that

01:09:41.880 --> 01:09:47.240
[Guest]: is astounding, because sometimes a person has great things to say. And you know what we are,

01:09:47.240 --> 01:09:52.760
[Guest]: you can see these religious sermons, you can see a talk on YouTube by somebody, and you want to

01:09:52.760 --> 01:09:57.960
[Guest]: watch that talk is it's a one way conversation, it's still coming at you, but the person is not

01:09:57.960 --> 01:10:02.680
[Guest]: talking to you directly. But if the person was sitting on the opposite side of the table,

01:10:02.680 --> 01:10:06.840
[Guest]: suddenly the whole thing changes into I don't want to listen to you anymore. I want to tell

01:10:06.840 --> 01:10:11.480
[Guest]: you what to say. I want to tell you my opinion in the middle. Why does this happen? And why?

01:10:11.480 --> 01:10:15.400
[Guest]: I mean, should it be prevented? Of course, I mean, I think we can always do things better.

01:10:15.400 --> 01:10:23.720
[Guest]: But at some point, I think, you know, freewheeling listening, what is the difference between are you

01:10:23.720 --> 01:10:29.080
[Guest]: hearing things? And are you actually listening to things is so for instance, I have a fundamental

01:10:29.080 --> 01:10:37.720
[Guest]: problem in being in a closed room in a seminar, I fall asleep. And this has been such a big

01:10:37.720 --> 01:10:43.320
[Guest]: problem for me even in the context of so like I say, you know, if I'm in a conference room,

01:10:43.320 --> 01:10:48.920
[Guest]: I better be the one talking. Because if I'm the one listening, then I'm going to fall asleep

01:10:48.920 --> 01:10:55.240
[Guest]: at some point. It's just that there's some part of my part of me that is just designed to I can

01:10:55.240 --> 01:11:00.520
[Guest]: absorb reading, I can absorb listening, or do you see the minute you put me in a position where I

01:11:00.520 --> 01:11:09.400
[Guest]: can talk and I'm not allowed to, it just, you know, I have to fight it a lot. I'm 47. So I've

01:11:09.400 --> 01:11:17.800
[Guest]: learned a little bit of, you know, how to deal with it. But it's surprising how little I do

01:11:17.800 --> 01:11:21.960
[Guest]: the same thing, for instance, when my kids want to talk to me. Because when the kids want to talk

01:11:21.960 --> 01:11:27.240
[Guest]: to you're like, I'm dad, I know everything, right? So you should do this. And suddenly,

01:11:27.240 --> 01:11:31.880
[Guest]: you're like, I don't know everything. My son recently, I don't know what they teach people

01:11:31.880 --> 01:11:38.120
[Guest]: in ninth standard these days, but this, it's far more complicated math than I've ever imagined.

01:11:38.120 --> 01:11:42.520
[Guest]: So he will come and say, Daddy, but what about this? And what about that? And you've read

01:11:42.520 --> 01:11:48.760
[Guest]: something on the internet. And I feel it's like my job to educate him about this. But he doesn't

01:11:48.760 --> 01:11:54.360
[Guest]: want me to educate him. He's already figured it out. He wants to tell me that he knows.

01:11:54.920 --> 01:11:59.480
[Guest]: And why can't I just listen to him and say, well, you know, this is great. Tell me more.

01:12:01.000 --> 01:12:06.280
[Guest]: I find it astounding that I can't it's I don't know whether everybody has this problem. Obviously,

01:12:06.280 --> 01:12:13.880
[Guest]: everybody doesn't because people but it it's, it's like you like hearing the sound of your

01:12:13.880 --> 01:12:20.360
[Guest]: own voice. And therefore, you have to have your voice in every conversation sounds terribly

01:12:20.360 --> 01:12:25.720
[Guest]: irrational to me, but it's who I am for some reason. And it's a part of me that I just don't

01:12:25.720 --> 01:12:33.240
[Guest]: like. It's like, you know, I wish I had. I wish for all those times that I had great conversations

01:12:33.240 --> 01:12:37.800
[Guest]: that I was more of a listener than a talker. So there was this book, I remember reading a

01:12:37.800 --> 01:12:41.880
[Amit Varma]: couple of decades back, random self-help book, I don't even know why I read it. It's called

01:12:41.880 --> 01:12:46.600
[Amit Varma]: men are from Mars, women are from Venus, by John Gray. And he speaks about exactly this thing. And

01:12:46.600 --> 01:12:51.080
[Amit Varma]: of course, he's essentializing and today, it's not politically correct to say that men have

01:12:51.080 --> 01:12:54.600
[Amit Varma]: innate traits and women have different whatever, everyone's supposed to be a blank slate,

01:12:54.600 --> 01:12:59.080
[Amit Varma]: which is, of course, not the case. But his point about men was that men are always in problem

01:12:59.080 --> 01:13:04.520
[Amit Varma]: solving mode. If you talk to them about a problem, they will want to offer you a solution, right?

01:13:04.520 --> 01:13:09.320
[Amit Varma]: And sometimes like you're like, you know, you were describing in your conversations with your wife,

01:13:09.320 --> 01:13:13.480
[Amit Varma]: sometimes they don't want solutions, they just want to be heard, they just want, you know,

01:13:13.480 --> 01:13:18.200
[Amit Varma]: they just want that kind of empathetic environment. And you don't actually have to, you know, put your

01:13:18.200 --> 01:13:24.120
[Amit Varma]: engineering cap on and solve the damn problem. And I think at some level, it's also, you know,

01:13:24.120 --> 01:13:29.640
[Amit Varma]: we are so focused on ourselves sometimes, that we feel that we have to show that we exist to

01:13:29.640 --> 01:13:34.040
[Amit Varma]: ourselves. But you know, it's like Descartes said, I think therefore I exist. It's really,

01:13:34.040 --> 01:13:41.560
[Amit Varma]: I solve your problem, therefore I exist. It's the ego, it's the whole male ego thing. And there's

01:13:41.560 --> 01:13:46.840
[Amit Varma]: definitely something to that because women don't do this. And if anything, if anything, and this

01:13:46.840 --> 01:13:51.560
[Amit Varma]: is really a problem with our society, if anything, they don't speak up enough and they listen,

01:13:51.560 --> 01:13:57.480
[Amit Varma]: you know, you'll have good listeners there. And there is, you know, this kind of confidence issue

01:13:57.480 --> 01:14:02.120
[Amit Varma]: there. And you see this dynamic playing out where if you have a meeting with men and women, just

01:14:02.120 --> 01:14:07.560
[Amit Varma]: listen to who talks more, listen to, you know, just those dynamics, who interrupts more,

01:14:07.560 --> 01:14:15.000
[Amit Varma]: like women will get interrupted more, by far, it's not even close. Right? If you just sit at a cafe

01:14:15.000 --> 01:14:19.480
[Amit Varma]: without a smartphone, so in full psychopath mode, and you just listen to the conversations around

01:14:19.480 --> 01:14:26.840
[Amit Varma]: you, it can actually kind of be very interesting in these different ways. So I'd say the thing is

01:14:26.840 --> 01:14:32.840
[Amit Varma]: not to beat ourselves up too much. The thing is just to be mindful of these things and just to

01:14:33.560 --> 01:14:40.840
[Amit Varma]: try to be aware. Because at some level, you also realize that, you know, and I don't know what the

01:14:40.840 --> 01:14:46.200
[Amit Varma]: listeners would feel about this, but sometimes you become aware of your own frailties, and you can do

01:14:46.200 --> 01:14:51.720
[Amit Varma]: something about them. And sometimes they're just ingrained in you. And at the most, you try to

01:14:51.720 --> 01:14:57.320
[Amit Varma]: control their manifestations and you try to sort of control your behavior the best you can and

01:14:57.320 --> 01:15:06.280
[Amit Varma]: mindfulness helps. But you know, sometimes you kind of accept, you know, accept the hard wiring

01:15:06.280 --> 01:15:11.560
[Amit Varma]: and say that, okay, this is a hard wiring, I won't be ruled by it. Like I think a lot of,

01:15:11.560 --> 01:15:16.600
[Amit Varma]: you know, we are of course, a product of a combination of nature and nurture, as Steven Pinker memorably

01:15:16.600 --> 01:15:23.160
[Amit Varma]: said, nature gives us knobs, nurture turns them. And the way I think of the progress of civilization

01:15:23.160 --> 01:15:29.400
[Amit Varma]: over the last few centuries, particularly the Enlightenment onwards, is that we are mitigating

01:15:29.400 --> 01:15:36.200
[Amit Varma]: our hard wiring. That nurture is, you know, one of the things that we were hardwired to do is think

01:15:36.200 --> 01:15:41.320
[Amit Varma]: independently about our hard wiring, which is not something any other creature has, only humans have

01:15:41.320 --> 01:15:47.960
[Amit Varma]: that. So I can look at myself and think that I am programmed to be like this, but I can fight it,

01:15:47.960 --> 01:15:55.640
[Amit Varma]: that I can sort of, you know, and that's a lot of the Enlightenment values stress towards that,

01:15:55.640 --> 01:16:01.160
[Amit Varma]: that we can intellectually imagine a better society. And then we can work towards it. And

01:16:01.160 --> 01:16:05.640
[Amit Varma]: of course, we are hardwired in many contradictory ways, we are hardwired as much for selfishness and

01:16:05.640 --> 01:16:11.560
[Amit Varma]: greed as we are also hardwired for altruism and empathy, right? It's which knobs you then decide

01:16:11.560 --> 01:16:15.800
[Amit Varma]: to focus on and how you kind of control your behavior. Sorry, that's a bit of a ramble.

01:16:15.800 --> 01:16:20.840
[Guest]: No, no, it's been quite interesting. Because I think this ties into the point of, I mean,

01:16:20.840 --> 01:16:27.480
[Guest]: coming back to say, the creator economy and the way things are, the fact that we are talking about

01:16:27.480 --> 01:16:33.880
[Guest]: this and recognizing, and this is actually a prime example, where in my mainstream media,

01:16:33.880 --> 01:16:41.160
[Guest]: and perhaps even on a radio talk show or anything like that, would you ever find some nuance like

01:16:41.160 --> 01:16:47.160
[Guest]: this being discussed to this extreme, without somebody saying, listen, there's not enough of

01:16:47.160 --> 01:16:53.560
[Guest]: an audience for this, or that, oh, no, no, my 90% of my audience wants a Bollywood discussion,

01:16:53.560 --> 01:17:00.040
[Guest]: or I wonder, so should we just focus? So this is where I think, you know, the times of today kind

01:17:00.040 --> 01:17:07.560
[Guest]: of coming back to this, we've changed the way we produce content in the sense that earlier it was

01:17:07.560 --> 01:17:12.760
[Guest]: blogging and now it's gone to, you know, and you've talked about it a little bit in your

01:17:12.760 --> 01:17:19.160
[Guest]: presentation, I think you said, the reason, the way to do things has moved from a blogging text

01:17:19.160 --> 01:17:26.680
[Guest]: interface to audio plus YouTube plus a bunch of other interfaces and so on. And this is where I

01:17:26.680 --> 01:17:31.240
[Guest]: mean, I think you probably will see this better. And I want to bring this back to you on that,

01:17:31.240 --> 01:17:37.800
[Guest]: you know, on that aspect. How does this change? I mean, so for instance, what are the constraints?

01:17:37.800 --> 01:17:42.760
[Guest]: So you're, you're, you're sitting here with a different world today than it was when we started

01:17:42.760 --> 01:17:48.440
[Guest]: off. And when we started off, I don't think when I was 20, I could have ever imagined that I would

01:17:48.440 --> 01:17:54.200
[Guest]: be talking and hundreds of people would be listening, without me being on some fancy TV

01:17:54.200 --> 01:17:59.640
[Guest]: channel or without some fans. It was almost impossible to imagine that people would listen,

01:17:59.640 --> 01:18:04.680
[Guest]: you could stand with a soapbox in the middle of MG Road, and two people will listen. And mostly

01:18:04.680 --> 01:18:11.560
[Guest]: they'll tell you to shut up. Right now, if they're telling you to shut up, it's probably a small part

01:18:11.560 --> 01:18:16.600
[Guest]: of the brigade, but there are enough people listening. Anyways, what happened here? And

01:18:16.600 --> 01:18:23.240
[Guest]: how did those little constraints and change over? You know, I think you have a great handle on this.

01:18:23.240 --> 01:18:31.000
[Guest]: And you've seen this evolve, because you've gone from being a mainstream media person, to a blogger

01:18:31.000 --> 01:18:38.040
[Guest]: to a sort of mainstream media person to a podcaster to now, broadcaster, plus educator,

01:18:38.040 --> 01:18:43.800
[Amit Varma]: plus so many other things. What's changed? Okay, so just for the listeners, the presentation

01:18:43.800 --> 01:18:47.960
[Amit Varma]: Deepak is referring to is a presentation I've given in a couple of places. I think I also did

01:18:47.960 --> 01:18:52.360
[Amit Varma]: it for Spotify podcasting day last year when they asked me to talk about the creator economy.

01:18:52.360 --> 01:18:57.320
[Amit Varma]: And I just shared it with Deepak and he said, let's chat about this. Now, here's the thing,

01:18:57.320 --> 01:19:02.040
[Amit Varma]: the world has changed so fast and so drastically that we almost don't notice. Now, I divide the

01:19:02.040 --> 01:19:07.720
[Amit Varma]: history of creation really into five periods. And one is got to Gutenberg, you know, G2G,

01:19:07.720 --> 01:19:11.560
[Amit Varma]: which is basically till the invention of the printing press, right? And I don't need to

01:19:11.560 --> 01:19:16.120
[Amit Varma]: elaborate what the scene there is that you can't achieve scale and blah, blah, blah, blah, blah.

01:19:16.120 --> 01:19:20.280
[Amit Varma]: Therefore, you don't have access to what other creators have created necessarily, it's limited,

01:19:20.280 --> 01:19:27.480
[Amit Varma]: and your audiences are limited, and so on and so forth. Now, then the second age is a mechanical

01:19:27.480 --> 01:19:32.600
[Amit Varma]: age, which is all the way to, let's say the early 2000s, where the printing press, television,

01:19:32.600 --> 01:19:39.000
[Amit Varma]: all of that is included. Then I talk about sort of the blogging and early social media age,

01:19:39.000 --> 01:19:44.760
[Amit Varma]: which is the aughties. And then there is a YouTube and Instagram age, which is the, you know,

01:19:44.760 --> 01:19:50.920
[Amit Varma]: 2010-11 onwards to 2019. And then number five, I grandiosely call it the age of the creator,

01:19:50.920 --> 01:19:57.000
[Amit Varma]: which is, you know, started in 2020, not necessarily enhanced by the pandemic, I think it

01:19:57.000 --> 01:20:01.960
[Amit Varma]: was kind of happening anyway. Now, let's quickly go back to the constraints that we faced or the

01:20:01.960 --> 01:20:06.680
[Amit Varma]: constraints that both of us would have faced as creators in the 90s. Number one, we don't have

01:20:06.680 --> 01:20:10.440
[Amit Varma]: the means of production. So if I want to write something, who's going to publish it, who's going

01:20:10.440 --> 01:20:15.640
[Amit Varma]: to get it out there, I have to, you know, send it to a newspaper or find a publisher or all of those

01:20:15.640 --> 01:20:22.360
[Amit Varma]: things, right? Number two, access, that I am dependent on gatekeepers for that to happen,

01:20:22.360 --> 01:20:26.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, and I have to meet, you know, there is a consensus on the truth, and there's a consensus

01:20:26.920 --> 01:20:31.080
[Amit Varma]: on style, and I have to go through them. If I'm writing for someone, I have to be, you know,

01:20:31.080 --> 01:20:35.720
[Amit Varma]: follow the news cycle, write about something which is topical. Number three, there are restrictive

01:20:35.720 --> 01:20:42.200
[Amit Varma]: formats. So if I want to write something, you know, an article is 800 words, a book is 100,000,

01:20:42.200 --> 01:20:48.200
[Amit Varma]: or whatever it is, if I'm a filmmaker, I can make a 24 minute episode for a serial because the other

01:20:48.200 --> 01:20:52.680
[Amit Varma]: six minutes, it would pair it up with ads, or a 90 minute Bollywood film or a three hour

01:20:53.320 --> 01:20:58.040
[Amit Varma]: Bollywood film. So those are the formats which are constraints on me also. The fourth constraint

01:20:58.040 --> 01:21:04.120
[Amit Varma]: is connecting with audiences, that I can randomly write or make something but I don't have a direct

01:21:04.120 --> 01:21:08.280
[Amit Varma]: connect with my audience where I'm speaking to them all the time and they're speaking to me.

01:21:08.840 --> 01:21:15.800
[Amit Varma]: And the final one is making money, where, you know, if I read something by you, Deepak, I'm

01:21:15.800 --> 01:21:19.480
[Amit Varma]: actually paying for it because time is money. I spent half an hour reading something you've written,

01:21:20.200 --> 01:21:24.680
[Amit Varma]: I value it. It's evident because time is money. I spent half an hour reading it, I value it.

01:21:25.480 --> 01:21:29.480
[Amit Varma]: You should have a way to capture some of this value directly. Now what used to happen in the

01:21:29.480 --> 01:21:34.360
[Amit Varma]: 90s is you write for a newspaper, they'll aggregate eyeballs, they'll get advertisers,

01:21:34.360 --> 01:21:39.960
[Amit Varma]: and you'll get a tiny, tiny chunk of that, right? You don't have a direct way of benefiting from the

01:21:39.960 --> 01:21:45.800
[Amit Varma]: value that you provide to others. Now this sort of, so these are the five sort of constraints

01:21:45.800 --> 01:21:52.600
[Amit Varma]: that I saw the means of production, the access slash gatekeepers problem, the restrictive forms,

01:21:52.600 --> 01:21:57.400
[Amit Varma]: and you know, direct connect with the audience and directly making money. Now this kind of started

01:21:57.400 --> 01:22:02.280
[Amit Varma]: changing with the blogging age in the sense that the means of production opened up for us, right?

01:22:02.280 --> 01:22:08.840
[Amit Varma]: And so I was at that time in Crickinfo, and part of mainstream media there, but I wanted to write

01:22:08.840 --> 01:22:14.120
[Amit Varma]: about other stuff. So I could just start a blog. And, you know, so no gatekeepers, therefore,

01:22:14.120 --> 01:22:18.680
[Amit Varma]: and in terms of form, I was freed, I didn't have to follow the news cycle, I can write about

01:22:18.680 --> 01:22:23.240
[Amit Varma]: whatever the hell I want. I don't have to do 800 words, I can do 80 words, eight words, because

01:22:23.240 --> 01:22:26.600
[Amit Varma]: there's no Twitter. So even microblogging happened, you can have eight words with a link.

01:22:26.600 --> 01:22:28.040
[Amit Varma]: I have seen some of your posts.

01:22:28.040 --> 01:22:32.280
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I used to do five posts a day. I think my record was 17 posts in a day. But,

01:22:32.840 --> 01:22:38.680
[Amit Varma]: you know, I did some 8000 posts in five years. So you are not constrained by the news cycle.

01:22:38.680 --> 01:22:44.520
[Amit Varma]: You're not constrained by word count, you can be 80 or 80,000. You're not the 80,000 blog posts

01:22:44.520 --> 01:22:50.040
[Amit Varma]: would be a big much. You're not constrained by style. You can find your own voice. You know,

01:22:50.040 --> 01:22:55.880
[Amit Varma]: you for example, if you were blogging, you could say, you know, no senior sub editor at Hindustan

01:22:55.880 --> 01:22:59.320
[Amit Varma]: Times is going to say that no, this, you know, you're not allowed to use this language.

01:22:59.960 --> 01:23:03.320
[Amit Varma]: And you could connect directly with audiences because you would have comments and all that. I

01:23:03.320 --> 01:23:07.800
[Amit Varma]: think my blog went beyond a certain level of traffic where the noise to signal ratio went out

01:23:07.800 --> 01:23:13.400
[Amit Varma]: of whack. So I disabled them like many other big blogs did, but you had a direct connect and people

01:23:13.400 --> 01:23:18.200
[Amit Varma]: would still write to me. But two things didn't happen here. It was still hard to make money from

01:23:18.200 --> 01:23:23.400
[Amit Varma]: your audiences directly, unless you were like a superb superstar tech blogger or whatever.

01:23:23.400 --> 01:23:28.360
[Amit Varma]: And mainstream media remained mainstream. Like when I started writing my blog, you know,

01:23:28.360 --> 01:23:32.440
[Amit Varma]: the Wall Street Journal came to me and said, Oh, why don't you write for us? Mint gave me a column,

01:23:32.440 --> 01:23:38.680
[Amit Varma]: which later won me the Bussier Prize. So many of the benefits from the blogging came in these

01:23:38.680 --> 01:23:43.560
[Amit Varma]: indirect ways, where I was validated by the mainstream media. And that was still very much

01:23:43.560 --> 01:23:49.000
[Amit Varma]: the model at that time. Right. So even when Nate Silver does what he does with his data analytics

01:23:49.000 --> 01:23:54.040
[Amit Varma]: and 525 and all, eventually NYT comes to him and says, Hey, you come for us. And that becomes,

01:23:54.040 --> 01:23:58.200
[Amit Varma]: you know, the next step. So there is a hierarchy of success and mainstream media

01:23:58.200 --> 01:24:04.680
[Amit Varma]: is still at the top. Now in the YouTube Instagram age that what 2012 to 2019,

01:24:04.680 --> 01:24:09.160
[Amit Varma]: and I'll probably put up a newsletter post and link it where I expand on these ideas. So it's

01:24:09.160 --> 01:24:13.320
[Amit Varma]: easier for people to refer to what happens is a means of production opens up for all media,

01:24:13.320 --> 01:24:18.120
[Amit Varma]: not just a written word, right, including audio visual, including podcasting, like the kind of

01:24:18.120 --> 01:24:23.000
[Amit Varma]: recording that we are doing now is doable within the budget of an individual. But 30 years ago,

01:24:23.000 --> 01:24:27.320
[Amit Varma]: it would simply not have been possible. And we were discussing before this that, you know,

01:24:27.320 --> 01:24:31.880
[Amit Varma]: you've built this beautiful YouTube cum podcasting studio, and you do a lot of your editing with

01:24:31.880 --> 01:24:38.040
[Amit Varma]: DaVinci Resolve, right? Now, DaVinci Resolve was originally a pro color grading software,

01:24:38.040 --> 01:24:43.000
[Amit Varma]: which later became a fantastic editing suite. And now it's available, there's a free version,

01:24:43.000 --> 01:24:47.000
[Amit Varma]: which basically does whatever you want it to do. And it's available. And even the paid version

01:24:47.000 --> 01:24:54.840
[Amit Varma]: doesn't cost much. And in 2010, DaVinci Resolve, only the color grading, not without the editing

01:24:54.840 --> 01:24:59.000
[Amit Varma]: suite, only the color grading you today get, which today you get a better version of that for free.

01:24:59.000 --> 01:25:06.360
[Amit Varma]: In 2010, it cost $800,000. My God, because this is what Hollywood used, you would not get it on

01:25:06.360 --> 01:25:12.760
[Amit Varma]: a PC or a laptop or your computer or whatever. There were special machines built for it. And

01:25:12.760 --> 01:25:17.320
[Amit Varma]: therefore, when films were sent for color grading, you'd pay big amounts of money, send it to the US

01:25:17.320 --> 01:25:22.360
[Amit Varma]: from India, for example, get it color graded, get it set back. And that's kind of what it was. And

01:25:22.360 --> 01:25:27.160
[Amit Varma]: this is just the extreme example that I can think of, right? And today, it's free on every PC and

01:25:27.160 --> 01:25:32.520
[Amit Varma]: every laptop, it's completely open. And, you know, genius is no longer constrained by the means of

01:25:32.520 --> 01:25:37.960
[Amit Varma]: production. Like when TikTok came to India, that first year and a half, and I love TikTok, because

01:25:37.960 --> 01:25:43.480
[Amit Varma]: for the rest of content also, there was a sort of class system in play in the sense that you saw a

01:25:43.480 --> 01:25:49.960
[Amit Varma]: certain profile of person who would on Instagram on whatever. TikTok democratized that because it

01:25:49.960 --> 01:25:54.840
[Amit Varma]: happened around simultaneously when Jio happened, and broadband access went everywhere, smartphone

01:25:54.840 --> 01:25:59.720
[Amit Varma]: access was much more common. And people could just point their cell phone camera at themselves

01:26:00.520 --> 01:26:06.280
[Amit Varma]: and shoot stuff. And the kind of creativity one got from villages, the kind of empowerment,

01:26:06.280 --> 01:26:12.360
[Amit Varma]: for example, for people of alternate sexualities, who suddenly see TikTok stars and TikTok content,

01:26:12.360 --> 01:26:19.560
[Amit Varma]: which is by people like them, right? Which in a geographically constrained area like a village,

01:26:19.560 --> 01:26:25.400
[Amit Varma]: you may not think there was someone like you may think that, you know, and suddenly that opens up

01:26:25.400 --> 01:26:30.200
[Amit Varma]: and then you realize one day that I can also create I can also do this. And you start with

01:26:30.200 --> 01:26:34.520
[Amit Varma]: low hanging fruit, like lip syncing to something or dramatizing a track that is already there.

01:26:34.520 --> 01:26:39.960
[Amit Varma]: And then you move on from there. And one saw that journey. And I briefly taught a course on TikTok

01:26:39.960 --> 01:26:45.720
[Amit Varma]: in Indian society also, but I did one course, one cohort of it and, and I did it on WhatsApp. So

01:26:45.720 --> 01:26:49.960
[Amit Varma]: WhatsApp University and the reason I did it on WhatsApp is I needed to share hundreds of vertical

01:26:49.960 --> 01:26:56.760
[Amit Varma]: videos, which was couldn't do it on zoom or anything else. So anyway, so that kind of so

01:26:56.760 --> 01:27:01.560
[Amit Varma]: to that extent, the means of production opened up, mainstream media started fading in power.

01:27:01.560 --> 01:27:06.200
[Amit Varma]: So you had creators like Casey Neistat, for example, the YouTube guy who's making enough

01:27:06.200 --> 01:27:11.240
[Amit Varma]: money who doesn't need to be signed by a Hollywood studio or Netflix or whatever.

01:27:12.200 --> 01:27:16.120
[Amit Varma]: Though it's all good if that happens, but he's making enough money YouTube creators start making

01:27:16.120 --> 01:27:20.920
[Amit Varma]: enough money where they don't have to think about validation from big mainstream houses. You look

01:27:20.920 --> 01:27:26.680
[Amit Varma]: at YouTube creators today like Mr. Beast and so on. It's not you know, it wasn't necessary. And

01:27:26.680 --> 01:27:32.120
[Amit Varma]: the technology enabled you now to go beyond all formats. And maybe creators were slow to catch up

01:27:32.120 --> 01:27:36.680
[Amit Varma]: to it and all of that. But you no longer had to do 24 minutes or 90 minutes or whatever you could

01:27:36.680 --> 01:27:41.320
[Amit Varma]: think in terms of just any damn thing. Yeah, five minutes to five hours,

01:27:41.320 --> 01:27:44.920
[Amit Varma]: to five hours, I have streams which have gone on for six, seven hours and all that.

01:27:44.920 --> 01:27:50.360
[Amit Varma]: And the whole sort of the whole streaming economy on Twitch and even YouTube is insane. And that's

01:27:50.360 --> 01:27:54.760
[Amit Varma]: another sort of way in which intimate content comes up where you see people in their everyday

01:27:54.760 --> 01:27:59.640
[Amit Varma]: lives just doing whatever, and those connections form. And creators began to form communities of

01:27:59.640 --> 01:28:04.840
[Amit Varma]: fans, where you know, you could set up a discord server, or you know, you could form those kinds

01:28:04.840 --> 01:28:10.520
[Amit Varma]: of communities for yourself set up a Patreon page. And that's the next point that you could take,

01:28:11.240 --> 01:28:15.320
[Amit Varma]: you know, you could monetize directly without necessarily being part of a big platform,

01:28:15.320 --> 01:28:20.280
[Amit Varma]: except that in this time till maybe 2019, most of it would still come from ads and sponsors.

01:28:20.280 --> 01:28:25.080
[Amit Varma]: So you don't have the middleman in between, right? So if I'm making audiovisual content,

01:28:25.080 --> 01:28:29.720
[Amit Varma]: I don't have to sell it to a star plus, I can take it to YouTube directly. But it's still ads

01:28:29.720 --> 01:28:33.640
[Amit Varma]: and sponsors where the money is coming from, you're still not taking enough money directly

01:28:33.640 --> 01:28:39.160
[Amit Varma]: from the consumer. Now, all this has been upended 2020 onwards. One, the means of production have,

01:28:39.160 --> 01:28:44.760
[Amit Varma]: of course, opened up even further, right? And people have started vlogs and all of that with

01:28:44.760 --> 01:28:49.160
[Amit Varma]: their smartphone and just gone way beyond. Mainstream media, I believe, has disintegrated

01:28:49.160 --> 01:28:54.920
[Amit Varma]: and become completely irrelevant. It's not even a factor. New formats have emerged intimate content

01:28:54.920 --> 01:29:00.360
[Amit Varma]: has grown. Every creator can now build their own community. You know, you can use discord servers,

01:29:00.360 --> 01:29:05.400
[Amit Varma]: you can do newsletters, you can kind of do whatever, you know, and creators can now make

01:29:05.400 --> 01:29:10.680
[Amit Varma]: money directly from fans, where the whole buy me a coffee thing like 10 years back, if you told me

01:29:10.680 --> 01:29:14.840
[Amit Varma]: that a creator is going to say that if you enjoyed my content, pay for it yourself, I would have said

01:29:14.840 --> 01:29:19.400
[Amit Varma]: no way that's going to work because micropayments, friction, all of that. It really works. You know,

01:29:19.400 --> 01:29:24.440
[Amit Varma]: I have myself experienced enough love from my listeners that has kept me independent,

01:29:24.440 --> 01:29:28.520
[Amit Varma]: that I don't need to work that it's fine, you know, so the whole thing of four podcasters don't

01:29:28.520 --> 01:29:32.920
[Amit Varma]: make money is not true anymore. I'm independent, I'm getting by, it's kind of worked for me. And

01:29:32.920 --> 01:29:37.320
[Amit Varma]: you can make it in different ways when you form communities and think outside the box.

01:29:37.320 --> 01:29:43.400
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, because I know that enough people have enough exposure to me that there's a certain

01:29:43.400 --> 01:29:48.440
[Amit Varma]: credibility, I can then sell an online writing course. And people will come for that. And

01:29:48.440 --> 01:29:52.200
[Amit Varma]: obviously, it cannot be a cynical exercise, you got to do a good job. Otherwise, you don't come

01:29:52.200 --> 01:29:57.560
[Amit Varma]: back. You know, and and then over a period of time, what happens is that people initially sign

01:29:57.560 --> 01:30:01.400
[Amit Varma]: up for the course, because they've heard the podcast, and they know you're legit. But then

01:30:01.400 --> 01:30:04.840
[Amit Varma]: they sign up for the course, because other people who've done the course tell them that, hey,

01:30:04.840 --> 01:30:08.440
[Amit Varma]: you know, this is a good course, it meant something to me. So in all these ways,

01:30:08.440 --> 01:30:15.320
[Amit Varma]: it's changed the game for creators, to the extent that creators now can sort of think,

01:30:15.320 --> 01:30:21.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, outside those early boxes. And some advice, I'll quickly go through six pieces of

01:30:21.240 --> 01:30:26.840
[Amit Varma]: advice that I give creators, since we are on the subject. One is, it is no longer necessary to

01:30:26.840 --> 01:30:31.960
[Amit Varma]: scale. Back in the day, you have your top point 5% to manage to scale and make a lot of money,

01:30:31.960 --> 01:30:37.080
[Amit Varma]: everyone else, it's a labor of love. Now, you can reach what Kevin Kelly calls 1000 true fans,

01:30:37.080 --> 01:30:41.640
[Amit Varma]: where Kevin Kelly wrote this essay more than a decade ago, where he said that if you get 1000

01:30:41.640 --> 01:30:46.920
[Amit Varma]: true fans will pay $100 a year each, that's $100,000, you don't need more than that, right?

01:30:46.920 --> 01:30:52.360
[Amit Varma]: And the amounts can vary, and most people would get by with less. And that became such a reality

01:30:52.360 --> 01:30:58.360
[Amit Varma]: with Substack, because a typical Substack annual subscription is $100. And there are tons of people

01:30:58.360 --> 01:31:02.440
[Amit Varma]: who have never been heard of before. You know, like Bill Bishop, who writes, you know, a gentleman,

01:31:02.440 --> 01:31:07.320
[Amit Varma]: I think in his 50s, who writes a newsletter on China called cynicism, right? cynicism, not not

01:31:07.320 --> 01:31:14.040
[Amit Varma]: cynicism, and, and 1000s of paid up subscribers. So you have people making tons of money and,

01:31:14.040 --> 01:31:18.520
[Amit Varma]: you know, making it work for them. So you don't have to aim for scale, you just have to,

01:31:18.520 --> 01:31:23.080
[Amit Varma]: you know, and there's another writer, I forget her name, who wrote another essay recently,

01:31:23.080 --> 01:31:28.200
[Amit Varma]: taking off from that and talking about 100 true fans who will pay $1,000 each. And there are

01:31:28.200 --> 01:31:34.520
[Amit Varma]: people who are actually successful with that model. Right. And because what happened, what

01:31:34.520 --> 01:31:40.280
[Amit Varma]: happened was that, as a creator, you discover a niche, which otherwise would not have existed.

01:31:40.840 --> 01:31:44.520
[Amit Varma]: You know, the other when when there's mainstream media, and they're going broad, and they're not

01:31:44.520 --> 01:31:50.600
[Amit Varma]: going deep, not only do they not cater to niches, they don't do those niches don't form because

01:31:50.600 --> 01:31:56.120
[Amit Varma]: nobody knows out there. And then something happens, and boom, they blow up. So the LGBT

01:31:56.120 --> 01:32:00.920
[Amit Varma]: thing that you talked about the niches there. Yeah. And that's, of course, a huge niche. It's

01:32:00.920 --> 01:32:07.320
[Amit Varma]: not even a niche. It's like, it's just, you know, so huge to creators, I think should think in terms

01:32:07.320 --> 01:32:12.280
[Amit Varma]: of reach and revenue. You do some things for each and you do some things for revenue. And

01:32:12.280 --> 01:32:18.200
[Amit Varma]: reaches the first thing you build, you know, you build credibility, you build trust. And then sort

01:32:18.200 --> 01:32:22.440
[Amit Varma]: of the revenue happens and you have to be clear and you can't do everything for revenue. Like,

01:32:22.440 --> 01:32:27.160
[Amit Varma]: and this is me thinking, this is all post hoc me thinking in hindsight, it wasn't planned like this.

01:32:27.160 --> 01:32:31.960
[Amit Varma]: But the fact is, like all my blogging years, I made nothing from blogging, right? Directly. It

01:32:31.960 --> 01:32:37.080
[Amit Varma]: was a labor of love. I enjoyed doing it. Similarly, you know, the seen and the unseen has existed for

01:32:37.080 --> 01:32:41.880
[Amit Varma]: more than five years. And for the first three and a half years, I made nothing zero, right? It was a

01:32:41.880 --> 01:32:47.080
[Amit Varma]: labor of love. I just enjoyed doing it. So I did it. But it worked out because it got me that trust,

01:32:47.080 --> 01:32:52.280
[Amit Varma]: it got me that credibility, it got me the reach, and then the revenue kicks in in various other

01:32:52.280 --> 01:32:58.360
[Amit Varma]: ways. So you've got to kind of define what you're doing and why. And three, build a community of

01:32:58.360 --> 01:33:02.840
[Amit Varma]: your fans once upon a time you couldn't, like, you know, people when who do my writing course,

01:33:02.840 --> 01:33:07.640
[Amit Varma]: those who want to be journalists will sometimes say that, you know, is there an editor at TOI,

01:33:07.640 --> 01:33:11.640
[Amit Varma]: you can give the email ID, we'll write to them, we'll write to people at Express. And of course,

01:33:11.640 --> 01:33:17.080
[Amit Varma]: I help them in whatever way I can. But my main advice is, don't do that. For a number of reasons.

01:33:17.080 --> 01:33:21.000
[Amit Varma]: One, there'll be a gatekeeper, you'll have to follow a particular house style, you'll have

01:33:21.000 --> 01:33:25.960
[Amit Varma]: to cater to the news cycle. Two, your work will appear sporadically. And therefore you're not

01:33:25.960 --> 01:33:29.480
[Amit Varma]: writing enough. And if you're not, you know, you become excellent at something by doing it again

01:33:29.480 --> 01:33:36.440
[Amit Varma]: and again, you want to write as much as you can. And three, it's very dispersed all over the place

01:33:36.440 --> 01:33:40.520
[Amit Varma]: and you're not building a community of fans. So if I read something by Deepak Chinoy in Hindu

01:33:40.520 --> 01:33:44.360
[Amit Varma]: Sun Times, and I say, wow, this guy really knows what he's talking about. But the next moment I've

01:33:44.360 --> 01:33:49.000
[Amit Varma]: forgotten about it. Whereas if I click on a link on social media, and I read a great piece by

01:33:49.000 --> 01:33:53.400
[Amit Varma]: Deepak Chinoy, and there's a thing subscribe to my newsletter, I put in my email ID, everything you

01:33:53.400 --> 01:33:58.120
[Amit Varma]: subsequently do comes to me, that email database, by the way, belongs to you. For every creator on

01:33:58.120 --> 01:34:02.840
[Amit Varma]: Substract, the email database belongs to the creator, you can so I automatically become part

01:34:02.840 --> 01:34:08.360
[Amit Varma]: of a community of Deepak Chinoy fans, you can send me more pieces, you can crowdsource funds

01:34:08.360 --> 01:34:13.560
[Amit Varma]: from me for various things. Tomorrow, when you have a podcast, you notify me I subscribe to that.

01:34:13.560 --> 01:34:18.520
[Amit Varma]: Tomorrow, if you teach a course, and which you absolutely should, frankly, then you know, I might

01:34:18.520 --> 01:34:25.560
[Amit Varma]: sign up for that. All of that happens. So building that kind of community is important. My fifth out

01:34:25.560 --> 01:34:31.160
[Amit Varma]: of the six commandments, as it were, is don't pigeonhole yourself. Too often, you think, oh,

01:34:31.160 --> 01:34:35.240
[Amit Varma]: I want to be a writer, I want to do this. And this is what I want. But the point is, if you're a

01:34:35.240 --> 01:34:40.440
[Amit Varma]: creative person, there are multiple things that you can do. So don't pigeonhole yourself. Maybe

01:34:40.440 --> 01:34:45.160
[Amit Varma]: it's writing, maybe it's podcasts, conversations like this. Like if you're someone listening to

01:34:45.160 --> 01:34:49.000
[Amit Varma]: this right now and thinking that, oh, I've heard so many of Amit's episodes, and I love his

01:34:49.000 --> 01:34:54.680
[Amit Varma]: conversations, what the hell stops you from having conversations like this? What stops you? Nothing

01:34:54.680 --> 01:34:59.640
[Amit Varma]: stops you. You could start at home. Like, you know, before my father passed a year or so back,

01:34:59.640 --> 01:35:04.120
[Amit Varma]: I sat down with, you know, a recording device. And we just had a conversation and asked him about his

01:35:04.120 --> 01:35:09.240
[Amit Varma]: life and did that. And you can do that at home now with your parents. You know, maybe you can

01:35:09.240 --> 01:35:13.160
[Amit Varma]: have a conversation with your spouse and ask her and you ask him, and you might discover things

01:35:13.160 --> 01:35:17.560
[Amit Varma]: that you hadn't realized. Like one of my guests, I won't name him, mutual friend of ours, did a

01:35:17.560 --> 01:35:24.840
[Amit Varma]: four-hour episode with me. And after it was done, his wife got mad at him and said that you told

01:35:24.840 --> 01:35:29.320
[Amit Varma]: Amit so many things you have never told me. And they've been married for some 35 years.

01:35:29.960 --> 01:35:36.600
[Amit Varma]: So, you know, try having conversations, it can work. And my fifth of my commandments is

01:35:36.600 --> 01:35:42.440
[Amit Varma]: don't worry about metrics. You know, here again, we have to get past that whole anxiety of what

01:35:42.440 --> 01:35:49.080
[Amit Varma]: other people think of us. And the problem is that I think creators tend to what, and this is also

01:35:49.080 --> 01:35:53.080
[Amit Varma]: said about futurists and science fiction writers, but it's true of creators, we tend to overestimate

01:35:53.080 --> 01:35:57.880
[Amit Varma]: the short term and underestimate the long term. So in the sense, I'll start a podcast and I'll

01:35:57.880 --> 01:36:03.080
[Amit Varma]: think, arre ban jayenge superstar, itne log sunenge and all of that and that never happens,

01:36:03.080 --> 01:36:07.560
[Amit Varma]: right? It takes time. You know, it takes time to grow organically, but also it takes time for you

01:36:07.560 --> 01:36:11.800
[Amit Varma]: to become good. Because whenever you start at something, as you and I know, whenever you start

01:36:11.800 --> 01:36:16.440
[Amit Varma]: at something you suck at it, you know, how do you become better, you become better by doing it again

01:36:16.440 --> 01:36:20.840
[Amit Varma]: and again and again and again, if validation is going to be the sole motivation for doing it again

01:36:20.840 --> 01:36:26.760
[Amit Varma]: and again, you will just stop. And then you will never get good. And it will be an opportunity

01:36:26.760 --> 01:36:32.120
[Amit Varma]: lost. And you could say it will be the unseen. So you just have to. So therefore, when you start

01:36:32.120 --> 01:36:36.520
[Amit Varma]: off doing something in the creator economy, start off with something you love, which you would do

01:36:36.520 --> 01:36:42.200
[Amit Varma]: anyway, right? So the motivation is intrinsic, it comes from within, and then you become better. And

01:36:42.200 --> 01:36:47.800
[Amit Varma]: then the growth is really exponential. It's kind of like, I mean, maybe you'd be better placed to

01:36:47.800 --> 01:36:52.600
[Amit Varma]: comment on whether compound interest is a bit like that. But you know, it takes time, don't

01:36:52.600 --> 01:36:58.280
[Amit Varma]: underestimate what the long term can do. And my final commandment is that, and we've discussed an

01:36:58.280 --> 01:37:04.680
[Amit Varma]: aspect of this before, that be authentic to yourself, right? 7 billion people on this planet,

01:37:04.680 --> 01:37:10.440
[Amit Varma]: you know, what makes you unique, Deepak? It's Deepak. There's nothing else, you know, and I

01:37:10.440 --> 01:37:17.160
[Amit Varma]: would say at a broad level, we are all basically the same with minor differences in hardwiring and

01:37:17.160 --> 01:37:21.640
[Amit Varma]: circumstances, but basically the same, but what sets you apart, the only thing that sets you apart

01:37:21.640 --> 01:37:25.240
[Amit Varma]: is yourself and you don't need to do anything else. You want to start a podcast, you don't

01:37:25.240 --> 01:37:30.200
[Amit Varma]: need to do voice modulation, you don't need to do any of that crap. So you know, if you want to be a

01:37:30.200 --> 01:37:36.040
[Amit Varma]: creator, therefore, in a nutshell, I would say that don't overthink it. Jump into it. There's

01:37:36.040 --> 01:37:40.920
[Amit Varma]: a trade off between getting it done and getting it right. You know, and the only way to get it right

01:37:40.920 --> 01:37:45.240
[Amit Varma]: is by getting it done. Just get it done, do it again and again, you'll eventually get it right.

01:37:45.240 --> 01:37:50.040
[Amit Varma]: So just jump into it, do something you love. Don't worry about validation at first,

01:37:50.040 --> 01:37:55.320
[Amit Varma]: recognize that you probably suck, and just do it again and again. So you become better

01:37:55.320 --> 01:38:00.680
[Guest]: and just enjoy the process. Yeah, this is this is so rich. I mean,

01:38:00.680 --> 01:38:06.040
[Guest]: there's so many things to take out from here. But I think you've succinctly put it in. It's that

01:38:06.040 --> 01:38:12.440
[Guest]: it's a phase of the economy that is that has empowered people, ordinary people, you and me

01:38:12.440 --> 01:38:18.280
[Guest]: and a bunch of other people who earlier thought they didn't have any way to express their voice

01:38:18.280 --> 01:38:23.800
[Guest]: to monetize their or make it a living. Because doing what you love is one thing, but doing what

01:38:23.800 --> 01:38:29.000
[Guest]: you love and earning money from it that makes a living possible is a part of the world that's

01:38:29.000 --> 01:38:36.520
[Guest]: only happened now. And I mean, I really think so many of these things resound with me completely,

01:38:36.520 --> 01:38:40.760
[Guest]: especially about short term versus long term. Now I've been blogging for since what,

01:38:40.760 --> 01:38:46.840
[Guest]: 2004 to now, in Capital Mind itself. And people come back to me and show me,

01:38:47.480 --> 01:38:52.040
[Guest]: send me stuff that I've written 2007. So I'm like, I don't even remember I've written this

01:38:52.040 --> 01:38:56.040
[Guest]: stuff. And I've written something about guzzles. And so I look at that. And I'm like, Oh, my God,

01:38:56.040 --> 01:39:01.720
[Guest]: this there is, you know, it's interesting that someone else is reading this stuff has given me,

01:39:01.720 --> 01:39:07.160
[Guest]: but the magnification, like you said, compound interest, it is that something you've written

01:39:07.160 --> 01:39:15.000
[Guest]: at a point in the past, survives enough to compound to everything else you've written

01:39:15.000 --> 01:39:20.200
[Guest]: 10 years later, or 15 years later. So one of the things that people often, I think,

01:39:20.200 --> 01:39:26.280
[Guest]: ignore is that this power of compounding does not come from doing for a purpose. That means,

01:39:26.280 --> 01:39:31.720
[Guest]: if I had written that article on guzzles, to get 100,000 views, I didn't get 100,000 views at the

01:39:31.720 --> 01:39:39.720
[Guest]: time. But when I write points to that article again today, after 10 or 12 years, when a similar

01:39:39.720 --> 01:39:45.000
[Guest]: situation arises in the market again, people look back at it and say, wow, and you know,

01:39:45.000 --> 01:39:52.040
[Guest]: then it gets the 100,000 views that it would have otherwise not gotten at all at the time. So I

01:39:52.040 --> 01:39:58.760
[Guest]: think, you know, that this doing what you love, and then doing it for the purpose of getting it

01:39:58.760 --> 01:40:06.120
[Guest]: right, getting it better, has enormous potential. And we've never seen I mean, I look at this and

01:40:06.120 --> 01:40:12.200
[Guest]: say, you know what, we were talking about a few listed companies recently. They're trying to get

01:40:12.200 --> 01:40:19.000
[Guest]: to smaller towns using influencers. This is insane. Because if you think of the traditional

01:40:19.000 --> 01:40:24.520
[Guest]: concept, they would be like, oh, get a wholesaler, hire a bunch of distributors in each village,

01:40:24.520 --> 01:40:29.720
[Guest]: the wholesaler, we parcel the inventory to the inventor, wholesaler then transfers it to the

01:40:29.720 --> 01:40:34.200
[Guest]: and then each of the distributors have to order and they have to put some money down to get their

01:40:34.200 --> 01:40:40.840
[Guest]: inventory going and they transition it to the shop. As an example, what they're doing right

01:40:40.840 --> 01:40:46.920
[Guest]: now is saying, listen, what we'll do is we'll figure out whatever they want to buy. But how we

01:40:46.920 --> 01:40:53.640
[Guest]: get to them is not by us putting paper ads and all that stuff. We're going to get people on YouTube

01:40:53.640 --> 01:40:58.200
[Guest]: who use our products and demonstrate how these products are used now whether they're headphones

01:40:58.200 --> 01:41:04.280
[Guest]: or lipstick or whatever it is, it's not relevant. But this is an audience you would just not go

01:41:04.280 --> 01:41:11.560
[Guest]: after as a large FMCG company or a large company. You know what, how many people use lipstick in

01:41:11.560 --> 01:41:16.200
[Guest]: these? So if they want to buy it, they just have to wait, because my supply chain is not going to

01:41:16.200 --> 01:41:21.160
[Guest]: be strong enough. The difference now is suddenly everything is changing that ecosystem where you're

01:41:21.160 --> 01:41:26.040
[Guest]: saying, listen, you want that lipstick, we'll deliver it to your house. Because somewhere along

01:41:26.040 --> 01:41:30.280
[Guest]: the line, the whole logistics frameworks in India have gotten sorted out. So if you order from a

01:41:30.280 --> 01:41:35.960
[Guest]: small village in Kerala, anything can get you, get that product over to you in two months directly

01:41:35.960 --> 01:41:42.120
[Guest]: to your house. How do you even figure out which product to buy is you're now on YouTube. So you're

01:41:42.120 --> 01:41:47.160
[Guest]: going to use authentic people to figure out the, when I say authentic, it's like, I don't have to

01:41:47.160 --> 01:41:54.120
[Guest]: hire an Aamir Khan all the time. If I find another person who speaks my language, who looks like me,

01:41:54.120 --> 01:41:59.560
[Guest]: and is a person that I associate with, and they like this product, I would rather, you know,

01:41:59.560 --> 01:42:05.000
[Guest]: I would I would actually give them as much credence as me looking at a film star in into

01:42:05.000 --> 01:42:12.920
[Guest]: buying a product. So the it empowers the creators who can then therefore find a revenue stream by,

01:42:12.920 --> 01:42:19.800
[Guest]: you know, doing this. But it also empowers brands, which otherwise would have I mean, today, I keep

01:42:19.800 --> 01:42:25.880
[Guest]: in the in the financial world, they keep telling us their brand is a moat. It's this moat that says,

01:42:25.880 --> 01:42:31.080
[Guest]: well, you know what, if it's Nestle KitKat, then Nestle is Nestle and therefore it can't be broken.

01:42:31.880 --> 01:42:36.440
[Guest]: Why is Nestle KitKat KitKat? Because they've done these ads on TV and people have used it and

01:42:36.440 --> 01:42:43.160
[Guest]: but the product is just a wafer covered with chocolate. I can get better chocolate.

01:42:43.160 --> 01:42:49.400
[Guest]: I can get better wafer. I can get a similar crunchy sounding feel with a better actual physical

01:42:49.400 --> 01:42:54.200
[Guest]: product. The problem isn't that I have a better product, it was that I don't have the distribution

01:42:54.200 --> 01:43:01.160
[Guest]: or the reach. Now you do. So if you build a product like that, you could get it to people

01:43:01.160 --> 01:43:07.560
[Guest]: in a way that Nestle is going to be totally blindsided to, because their way of responding is

01:43:07.560 --> 01:43:13.400
[Guest]: go to the IPL and put more ads, because that's how people are going to find my product. The other

01:43:13.400 --> 01:43:21.240
[Guest]: person is going to be like, you know what, I am going to do a review of each IPL game on my YouTube

01:43:21.240 --> 01:43:26.840
[Guest]: channel. And you know what, I'll talk about this new fancy KitKat competitor that is out there.

01:43:27.560 --> 01:43:35.320
[Guest]: And both things have the same reach, except the TV guy, TV ad fellow is is paying 100x

01:43:35.320 --> 01:43:39.720
[Guest]: for the same kind of reach as the influencer is who's just talking about IPL. It's just

01:43:39.720 --> 01:43:45.880
[Guest]: incredible that this economy exists today, and that everybody can harness it. Today,

01:43:45.880 --> 01:43:53.000
[Guest]: if one person talks about a product that I have built, it gives me more revenue than if I had put

01:43:53.000 --> 01:43:59.480
[Guest]: an ad that said come buy my product. It's because people don't want to listen to come buy my product.

01:43:59.480 --> 01:44:07.080
[Guest]: They want to listen to go buy his product. So that, I mean, this change, and I think the economic

01:44:07.080 --> 01:44:12.280
[Guest]: change of the whole thing has so many ramifications. More and more people do this, and you have another

01:44:12.280 --> 01:44:17.720
[Guest]: layer, which is the creator economy is great from an, you know, from an independence perspective.

01:44:18.440 --> 01:44:24.120
[Guest]: But there is still not enough of a financial structure around. And I say this in my book,

01:44:24.120 --> 01:44:29.960
[Guest]: actually talks about it, is you have to think of these things, because earlier, the governments of

01:44:29.960 --> 01:44:35.080
[Guest]: the day or the companies of employers of the day would think about it for you. They would set up

01:44:35.080 --> 01:44:39.880
[Guest]: your pension plan, your EPF. Now, what is the EPF? Part of your income gets automatically saved

01:44:39.880 --> 01:44:43.960
[Guest]: somewhere. After 50 years, when you retire, you suddenly say, hey, what do I do? I don't have an

01:44:43.960 --> 01:44:48.840
[Guest]: income anymore. Employer gratuitously says, listen, I've been putting 10% of your money in this thing.

01:44:48.840 --> 01:44:54.200
[Guest]: And here's a big lump sum, go go spend it now. And you could look at them and says, thank you, you're

01:44:54.200 --> 01:44:59.800
[Guest]: my saviour. This is the traditional way of thinking about it. But over time, people got more and more

01:44:59.800 --> 01:45:05.480
[Guest]: intelligent people said, okay, the government said we can't fund our pension pensions endlessly.

01:45:05.480 --> 01:45:10.920
[Guest]: You guys have to start thinking about your own retirement. Employers were forced more and more.

01:45:10.920 --> 01:45:14.680
[Guest]: So right now, for instance, traditional employment, you have to put 10% of your income,

01:45:14.680 --> 01:45:20.920
[Guest]: and the employer puts another 10% of your income, so 20% of your income goes to this fund, which you

01:45:20.920 --> 01:45:26.760
[Guest]: can't touch until you retire or until you go out of a job. What is the equivalent for a creator?

01:45:26.760 --> 01:45:34.920
[Guest]: Unless they plan it themselves, the creators, while they get the freedom, it isn't entirely

01:45:34.920 --> 01:45:42.120
[Guest]: easy for them to build themselves a smarter financial retirement. Because like all jobs,

01:45:42.120 --> 01:45:48.760
[Guest]: every creator, like all restaurants, perhaps, every creator will have a shelf life of some sort.

01:45:48.760 --> 01:45:56.760
[Guest]: That shelf life, maybe because of topicality, I am famous for talking about something and that

01:45:56.760 --> 01:46:01.000
[Guest]: something itself got violated. I faced that myself, there was a language called Delphi,

01:46:01.000 --> 01:46:05.960
[Guest]: I used to be so fond of it as a programming language that we set up an India Delphi users

01:46:05.960 --> 01:46:11.080
[Guest]: group and we did things I went to Borland in the US to Borland was the company that kind of that

01:46:11.080 --> 01:46:15.480
[Guest]: kind of that owned Delphi at the time. I presented in international conferences, you search for

01:46:15.480 --> 01:46:20.280
[Guest]: Delphi in India, you would get Deepak Chinoy and my company Agni and all that stuff, except Delphi

01:46:20.280 --> 01:46:26.280
[Guest]: died. Delphi died, not because it was not a good product, it was just that the powerful competitors

01:46:26.280 --> 01:46:34.760
[Guest]: had more marketing resources and better. In fact, the guy who built Delphi went on to go to Microsoft

01:46:34.760 --> 01:46:39.800
[Guest]: and build even greater stuff over there, including the next bit of technologies that came out of

01:46:39.800 --> 01:46:47.240
[Guest]: Microsoft, which have dominated it for the last 20 years. However, what happened there was my

01:46:47.240 --> 01:46:53.640
[Guest]: creator influence. If I just sat the Delphi thing, I would have died. I would have had a good life

01:46:53.640 --> 01:46:59.400
[Guest]: when I did but the shelf life. So what happens to the creators when their shelf life changes,

01:46:59.400 --> 01:47:06.680
[Guest]: and the guy who used to do or the girl who used to do a video every single day at 9pm in the night

01:47:06.680 --> 01:47:11.480
[Guest]: has a child and the 9pm is not possible. I mean, I can tell you from being a parent,

01:47:11.480 --> 01:47:19.720
[Guest]: trying to commit to a 9pm lifestyle when you have a young child is altogether, at least in my case,

01:47:19.720 --> 01:47:26.440
[Guest]: it was impossible to predict. I mean, maybe it's different for different people, but my children

01:47:26.440 --> 01:47:35.400
[Guest]: taught me that the value of knowing when one can actually sleep, if it were traded as an NFT,

01:47:35.400 --> 01:47:41.720
[Guest]: it would be one of the most valuable things in the world right now. So to be able to accurately

01:47:41.720 --> 01:47:46.520
[Guest]: predict that, when you have a baby, it's different. So what happens then? Does your income

01:47:46.520 --> 01:47:51.560
[Guest]: stream fall because the YouTube algorithm says, this person is no longer producing a 9pm video

01:47:51.560 --> 01:47:55.160
[Guest]: every month, I'm going to downgrade their lifestyle or whatever it is. I think the

01:47:55.160 --> 01:48:01.560
[Guest]: financial aspect of these extremes does need to be considered, apart from the social impact as

01:48:01.560 --> 01:48:09.160
[Guest]: well. Because suddenly it's like the Amway problem. In Amway, once you become an Amway

01:48:09.160 --> 01:48:14.920
[Guest]: distributor, suddenly all your friends start looking to you like customers. So you go to

01:48:14.920 --> 01:48:19.400
[Guest]: their houses and you say, why aren't you using Amway toothpaste? I'll sell it to you. Suddenly

01:48:19.400 --> 01:48:23.320
[Guest]: nobody wants to invite you to their house anymore because all you're talking about is Amway. Does

01:48:23.320 --> 01:48:29.160
[Guest]: it happen in social media and creators? Maybe, I don't know. I'm just thinking that. Of course,

01:48:29.160 --> 01:48:32.280
[Guest]: most of the time when I go out, I end up talking finance because that's what people want to talk

01:48:32.280 --> 01:48:37.880
[Guest]: to me about. But I have more to say than finance, most of the time, though most of it is bad jokes,

01:48:37.880 --> 01:48:44.760
[Guest]: so people would rather talk to me about finance. However, the interesting part of this is that,

01:48:44.760 --> 01:48:49.800
[Guest]: where was I going with this? Yes, the issue that happens with a lot of the creator economies,

01:48:49.800 --> 01:48:55.320
[Guest]: sometimes they feel that the backbones of the regular economy, which got built over time,

01:48:55.320 --> 01:48:59.640
[Guest]: like the financial concept, the fact that Saturday and Sunday are a holiday, there's

01:48:59.640 --> 01:49:02.760
[Guest]: a reason Saturday and Sunday are a holiday for many people, it's just because they needed to

01:49:02.760 --> 01:49:07.640
[Guest]: get away, they needed to unwind. How do you unwind off being a creator? Because you're

01:49:07.640 --> 01:49:13.000
[Guest]: always creating and you can always create because your mind will never rust. Therefore,

01:49:13.720 --> 01:49:19.800
[Guest]: you could technically work seven hours a day, seven days a week, because you can. Now,

01:49:19.800 --> 01:49:27.240
[Guest]: these constructs in the creator economy become what? Is it important? Is it like,

01:49:27.240 --> 01:49:31.000
[Guest]: no, the world has changed, you have to work 24, I mean, you have to work seven days a week,

01:49:31.000 --> 01:49:36.040
[Guest]: no matter what? Or is it like, is it true freedom saying, listen, it doesn't matter,

01:49:36.040 --> 01:49:42.680
[Guest]: you can work one day a week, you don't have to conform to the norms as they are. But at the

01:49:42.680 --> 01:49:48.120
[Guest]: same time, the norms are important, because if you choose to work seven days a week, that is

01:49:48.120 --> 01:49:50.360
[Guest]: also a problem, because it will hurt you in the longer run.

01:49:51.640 --> 01:49:56.040
[Amit Varma]: So great questions, great thoughts. Let me take a stab at kind of sharing my thoughts on it.

01:49:56.040 --> 01:50:01.240
[Amit Varma]: But first, you know, that KitKat example, where I just want to point out that one thing advertisers

01:50:01.240 --> 01:50:05.880
[Amit Varma]: don't realize, possibly because people and ad agencies are our age and all that, is that many

01:50:05.880 --> 01:50:11.000
[Amit Varma]: young people don't even know, for them, KitKat is not a special thing. That brand resonance isn't

01:50:11.000 --> 01:50:15.800
[Amit Varma]: there for them. That brand resonance is for an older generation. What I think people tend to

01:50:15.800 --> 01:50:22.120
[Amit Varma]: miss is that look 60, 65, 70%, I don't know the exact number of India is born after liberalization.

01:50:22.120 --> 01:50:27.880
[Amit Varma]: Right? So you and I have a sort of a shared reality, a shared basis for thinking about

01:50:27.880 --> 01:50:32.120
[Amit Varma]: things that they may not share. There might be young people today for whom KitKat is nothing.

01:50:32.120 --> 01:50:36.840
[Amit Varma]: There are certainly young people today on social media, for whom Amitabh Bachchan is just a guy

01:50:36.840 --> 01:50:41.880
[Amit Varma]: who puts this weird numbers on his tweets, right? And that's what they know of the guy. And for

01:50:41.880 --> 01:50:46.920
[Amit Varma]: them, he's famous for being famous, not for Diwaar or Sholay. Right? So we have to, you know, and

01:50:46.920 --> 01:50:52.360
[Amit Varma]: different people think of the world in different ways. And that mainstream, there's no mainstream.

01:50:52.360 --> 01:50:58.520
[Amit Varma]: Like, you know, this was a thought sparked by an interview of Steve Van Zandt, the guitarist who

01:50:58.520 --> 01:51:03.240
[Amit Varma]: once said that rock was mainstream, really, between around the time of the Beatles and when

01:51:03.240 --> 01:51:08.840
[Amit Varma]: Dylan went electric to Nirvana. And after that, there is no mainstream anymore. Everybody isn't

01:51:08.840 --> 01:51:12.680
[Amit Varma]: listening to the same thing. Look, another thing that's changed. Back in the 90s, we all listened

01:51:12.680 --> 01:51:18.040
[Amit Varma]: to the same thing. Right? Back in the 90s, we got our news from the same three or four places,

01:51:18.040 --> 01:51:23.880
[Amit Varma]: there was a consensus on the truth. All of that is completely dissipated. And net-net,

01:51:23.880 --> 01:51:29.480
[Amit Varma]: it's a great thing. Obviously, there are problems like polarization, the world of fake news,

01:51:29.480 --> 01:51:36.040
[Amit Varma]: everything has become a narrative battle, whatever, big subject. But, you know, coming back

01:51:36.040 --> 01:51:43.240
[Amit Varma]: to this whole sort of issue of how do creators think about thinking, this is a difficult problem.

01:51:43.240 --> 01:51:47.880
[Amit Varma]: You know why? Because, and this is a problem that will be overcome when the ecosystem changes.

01:51:47.880 --> 01:51:52.760
[Amit Varma]: So let me explain what I mean by that. Today, we are in a situation where a creator has to

01:51:52.760 --> 01:51:58.360
[Amit Varma]: simultaneously be an entrepreneur. Right? So your one skill might be you're a creator,

01:51:58.360 --> 01:52:02.760
[Amit Varma]: the other skill that you have to develop is you're an entrepreneur of your own brand.

01:52:02.760 --> 01:52:08.440
[Amit Varma]: And then you kind of have to figure it out. Now, this, you know, and there are many human failings

01:52:08.440 --> 01:52:12.280
[Amit Varma]: that come into play. Like when you were speaking, you were talking from the money aspect, and we'll

01:52:12.280 --> 01:52:17.560
[Amit Varma]: talk more about your book soon. And these things will come up. But what is the reason that people

01:52:17.560 --> 01:52:22.280
[Amit Varma]: don't make wise financial decisions for the future? It's because there is number one, of course,

01:52:22.280 --> 01:52:25.880
[Amit Varma]: there is a fact that most people just don't understand money. It's not intuitive, you know,

01:52:25.880 --> 01:52:31.960
[Amit Varma]: big numbers are too much. But there is also this illusion of immortality, where you don't in your

01:52:31.960 --> 01:52:36.520
[Amit Varma]: mind, you don't come to terms with the fact that one day you might be weak and frail, and your

01:52:36.520 --> 01:52:41.080
[Amit Varma]: memory might be passing, and you may not be what you are today. And your capacity to earn has gone

01:52:41.080 --> 01:52:47.400
[Amit Varma]: down. Or you don't come to terms with your own mortality, for example. And the notion that like

01:52:47.400 --> 01:52:50.520
[Amit Varma]: so many people don't take life insurance, because in a sense, they think they're going to live

01:52:50.520 --> 01:52:55.400
[Amit Varma]: forever. And in your book, you, you know, argue at length that why you should depending on, you

01:52:55.400 --> 01:53:02.440
[Amit Varma]: know, who you are and what your circumstances are. And there is also sort of this sense of continuity,

01:53:02.440 --> 01:53:07.720
[Amit Varma]: like in my poker days, I would constantly remind myself and tell others that just because you're

01:53:07.720 --> 01:53:12.680
[Amit Varma]: making a lot of money now, so you've got a lifestyle with it, don't assume that the flow

01:53:12.680 --> 01:53:18.280
[Amit Varma]: of money will continue. You know, so then you get used to a lifestyle, you continue that lifestyle.

01:53:18.840 --> 01:53:23.720
[Amit Varma]: And then one day, the flow ends, and you can't adjust and it becomes a problem. And you're right,

01:53:23.720 --> 01:53:28.440
[Amit Varma]: creators do need to watch out for that. And because creators are not just at the mercy of

01:53:29.320 --> 01:53:34.200
[Amit Varma]: changing fads, or what they do no longer being so relevant, they also have the mercy of algorithms

01:53:34.200 --> 01:53:39.320
[Amit Varma]: by social media giants, that if suddenly an algorithm changes in some subtle way that

01:53:39.320 --> 01:53:45.000
[Amit Varma]: downgrades your content, then that kind of becomes an issue. So I think this is a short term problem

01:53:45.000 --> 01:53:50.120
[Amit Varma]: that creators need to think as entrepreneurs. But I think in the long run, an ecosystem will come

01:53:50.120 --> 01:53:56.600
[Amit Varma]: about around this, where you will have intermediaries who will, you know, say that,

01:53:56.600 --> 01:54:00.680
[Amit Varma]: okay, you're a creator, you don't have time to spend on marketing, or you don't have time to,

01:54:00.680 --> 01:54:05.080
[Amit Varma]: you know, get brands who might want to advertise with you, you know, we'll take care of all that

01:54:05.080 --> 01:54:11.400
[Amit Varma]: for you and all of that. And that ecosystem is going to kind of emerge. And you know, that's

01:54:12.120 --> 01:54:17.320
[Amit Varma]: sort of bound to happen. So I'm not kind of so worried about that. But just to go back to and

01:54:17.320 --> 01:54:21.480
[Amit Varma]: again, what you said about you have to do switch off, you look at someone like one of the most

01:54:21.480 --> 01:54:26.360
[Amit Varma]: successful podcasters is this guy called Dan Carlin, who does a show called hardcore history,

01:54:26.360 --> 01:54:31.480
[Amit Varma]: right? Like, first of all, it breaks every notion of what you might think about podcasts. Like,

01:54:31.480 --> 01:54:36.200
[Amit Varma]: he did a series called a blueprint for Armageddon about World War One, which was 25 hours,

01:54:36.200 --> 01:54:41.560
[Amit Varma]: five episodes of five hours each. And it's just him talking, no music, no sound effects, nothing,

01:54:41.560 --> 01:54:48.040
[Amit Varma]: it's just him talking for 25 hours. And I remember the first time I went for a walk. And I was

01:54:48.040 --> 01:54:52.920
[Amit Varma]: listening at a higher speed, obviously. And I started listening to one episode, not realizing

01:54:52.920 --> 01:54:58.600
[Amit Varma]: the impact it will have on me. And obviously, it did wonders for my fitness, because that particular

01:54:58.600 --> 01:55:03.160
[Amit Varma]: day, especially I just kept walking, I couldn't stop. I remember standing outside in the twilight

01:55:03.160 --> 01:55:07.960
[Amit Varma]: as the sun is setting and is growing dark around me, just listening to this guy talking. And it's

01:55:07.960 --> 01:55:13.400
[Amit Varma]: magical. And it is not presentation mode, where it's, you know, this happened after that. And on

01:55:13.400 --> 01:55:18.520
[Amit Varma]: so and so date, this happened. It's very informal, it's rambling, he's thinking about something else.

01:55:18.520 --> 01:55:23.240
[Amit Varma]: There's one really moving section, where this bunch of soldiers go into a battle and they all

01:55:23.240 --> 01:55:28.120
[Amit Varma]: die. But the day before they go into battle, they write letters to their wives and girlfriends,

01:55:28.120 --> 01:55:33.880
[Amit Varma]: and he's reading them out. Right? So it's incredible. You're standing in the twilight

01:55:33.880 --> 01:55:38.040
[Amit Varma]: under your building, the sun is setting, and you're listening to this and you're transported.

01:55:38.040 --> 01:55:44.360
[Amit Varma]: And this is history, but it's real again. Right? It is people who died, but it is people who are

01:55:44.360 --> 01:55:48.840
[Amit Varma]: in your head. It's beautiful, the power of podcasting. And the reason I mentioned him is,

01:55:48.840 --> 01:55:53.240
[Amit Varma]: he doesn't do this every day. He'll bring out one series a year or one series every one and a half

01:55:53.240 --> 01:55:57.240
[Amit Varma]: years or whatever. And everybody binges and they just go mad. And you can't do this. If you're

01:55:57.240 --> 01:56:03.560
[Amit Varma]: doing a 25 hour series. You can't do it weekly. You'll do it once a year. And he publishes all

01:56:03.560 --> 01:56:07.720
[Amit Varma]: his resources and everything will be on his blog that these are the 80 books I read for this and

01:56:07.720 --> 01:56:12.760
[Amit Varma]: everyone. So then people can go down rabbit holes and all of that. So what you're creating,

01:56:12.760 --> 01:56:16.440
[Amit Varma]: the experience that you're creating, you can define for yourself. You don't have to think

01:56:16.440 --> 01:56:20.360
[Amit Varma]: within fixed boundaries. You know, imagine him in the 90s, going to radio station or going to

01:56:20.360 --> 01:56:24.440
[Amit Varma]: whoever and saying, I'll talk for 25 hours and they're like, fuck off, man. And you know, another

01:56:24.440 --> 01:56:28.840
[Amit Varma]: example of that, which my friend Chuck Gopal introduced me to in the episode I did with him,

01:56:28.840 --> 01:56:35.880
[Amit Varma]: is this lady called Miss Excel, right? Now, Miss Excel is this Instagrammer who has knowledge of

01:56:35.880 --> 01:56:44.920
[Amit Varma]: Excel and a passion for EDM music, a passion for EDM and for dancing. She combined them, right?

01:56:44.920 --> 01:56:50.040
[Amit Varma]: She was so she started bringing out these Instagram videos, where she's dancing to EDM.

01:56:50.040 --> 01:56:54.760
[Amit Varma]: And on the top of the screen, there's an Excel problem being solved and you're shown how to

01:56:54.760 --> 01:57:00.680
[Amit Varma]: do something. And people loved it. And she met all the rules. If she goes to a TV channel,

01:57:00.680 --> 01:57:04.920
[Amit Varma]: and she says, I'll do this, they laugh her out of the room. But from my point of view,

01:57:04.920 --> 01:57:09.320
[Amit Varma]: she met every parameter a creator needs to meet. It's authentic. She really cares about all three

01:57:09.320 --> 01:57:14.360
[Amit Varma]: of these things. It's intimate. She is being who she is, and you appreciate that, right?

01:57:14.360 --> 01:57:20.360
[Amit Varma]: And so on, meets every parameter. And you know, for a while, she was making $100,000 a day selling

01:57:20.360 --> 01:57:25.640
[Amit Varma]: courses in Excel. Right? So here's someone who's made millions, definitely the richest Excel

01:57:25.640 --> 01:57:31.560
[Amit Varma]: teacher in the world. A young woman dancing to EDM or doing other things to music and is delightful.

01:57:32.440 --> 01:57:36.520
[Amit Varma]: Because she knows her shit. She really does know Excel. She's qualified to teach that's evident.

01:57:37.080 --> 01:57:43.560
[Amit Varma]: But it's just so light and it's beautiful and it's wonderful. Right? And so it's for creators,

01:57:43.560 --> 01:57:49.480
[Amit Varma]: it's unknown unknowns. And this is such a, you know, a fascinating time to be living in.

01:57:49.480 --> 01:57:55.240
[Amit Varma]: Because one, I think creators will begin to explore all of these. Two, an ecosystem,

01:57:55.240 --> 01:58:02.760
[Amit Varma]: a support ecosystem will obviously develop around them. And, you know, and the other thing is that

01:58:02.760 --> 01:58:07.000
[Amit Varma]: back in the day, it was worse for creators, because either you make it to that top 0.5%,

01:58:07.000 --> 01:58:11.480
[Amit Varma]: which makes all the money, or you get nothing. It's a labor of love. You know, like I say,

01:58:11.480 --> 01:58:16.680
[Amit Varma]: the cafes of Versova where I live, are filled with actors who struggled for the last 30 years.

01:58:16.680 --> 01:58:21.400
[Amit Varma]: It's sad, right? Everybody doesn't make it the top. But here in the creator economy,

01:58:21.400 --> 01:58:24.520
[Amit Varma]: there are all kinds of niches, which don't even interact with each other.

01:58:24.520 --> 01:58:29.000
[Amit Varma]: Where a superstar in one niche may pass a superstar in another niche on the street,

01:58:29.000 --> 01:58:32.600
[Amit Varma]: and they may not recognize each other and their fans may not know each other, but they're big

01:58:32.600 --> 01:58:39.400
[Amit Varma]: stars. You know, so it's, so in that sense, there are more opportunities, there are more and you

01:58:39.400 --> 01:58:44.200
[Amit Varma]: know, I just feel that, I mean, obviously, the role of luck is huge in life, but it's a little

01:58:44.200 --> 01:58:48.360
[Amit Varma]: less in this, your probability of making it if you're true to yourself, and you, you know,

01:58:48.360 --> 01:58:52.280
[Amit Varma]: continue working on your craft and do work that you enjoy doing, the probability of your making

01:58:52.280 --> 01:58:57.240
[Guest]: it is a bit much greater. This, you know, this is fascinating. From a perspective,

01:58:57.240 --> 01:59:05.640
[Guest]: also, I keep thinking about this. How come India is defined by the lack of enough niches? I mean,

01:59:05.640 --> 01:59:11.640
[Guest]: it's not defined by it, but it seems to have come across when everything about India is so big,

01:59:11.640 --> 01:59:16.840
[Guest]: that every niche is huge, is probably a country of its own. So, you end up with, you know, so,

01:59:17.560 --> 01:59:23.480
[Guest]: like, you know, how come cricket is our number one sport? In the South, volleyball isn't

01:59:23.480 --> 01:59:28.120
[Guest]: insanely popular. I mean, there's a volleyball league also that's going on. Perhaps it's only

01:59:28.120 --> 01:59:32.840
[Guest]: time that, you know, the other sports come in. And, you know, a country like Canada is like

01:59:32.840 --> 01:59:39.400
[Guest]: three sports. I mean, three large sports. India is maybe once in a while we get a tennis player

01:59:39.400 --> 01:59:43.720
[Guest]: or a badminton player and we, you know, or a set of badminton players. But otherwise,

01:59:43.720 --> 01:59:50.280
[Guest]: this isn't that much in India that's, you know, talked about. So, the creator economy, I think,

01:59:50.280 --> 01:59:55.160
[Guest]: for one, is what will change it. Because all the mainstream channels are like, listen,

01:59:55.160 --> 02:00:00.760
[Guest]: we want to get to 90% of the population or 80% of the population. I don't care if 10%

02:00:00.760 --> 02:00:05.400
[Guest]: of India's population is as much as France. They're like, no, no, we don't, we don't give

02:00:05.400 --> 02:00:11.000
[Guest]: a damn. That does not matter to us. What matters to us is that I want, I want to get to 80% of

02:00:11.000 --> 02:00:18.760
[Guest]: India. So, you know, this was for me fascinating because, again, it goes back to college when I

02:00:18.760 --> 02:00:24.280
[Guest]: discovered this. Till I was in college, all I was listening to was English music and Hindi music,

02:00:24.280 --> 02:00:29.560
[Guest]: for the most part. And English music was largely pop, some rock, some friends introduced me to

02:00:29.560 --> 02:00:35.480
[Guest]: metal, which I pretended to understand, but didn't. And then I would, I went to college. And

02:00:35.480 --> 02:00:43.640
[Guest]: then I discovered this thing called A.R. Rahman and Tamil and Telugu music, and even a bunch of

02:00:43.640 --> 02:00:51.400
[Guest]: other genres as well, which I had no idea. Now, I did not know, for instance, that the audiography

02:00:51.400 --> 02:00:58.760
[Guest]: of the beat and the thing of Tamil music was insanely good. I mean, way better than anything

02:00:58.760 --> 02:01:04.840
[Guest]: I'd heard in Bollywood music, at least so far. And I was like, wow, this is amazing. The fact

02:01:04.840 --> 02:01:09.480
[Guest]: that I was exposed to it at that time, told me that there was more, you know, much more out there

02:01:09.480 --> 02:01:15.080
[Guest]: than I had ever seen. I saw what rock really was. Till that time, Pink Floyd was, I think,

02:01:15.080 --> 02:01:19.480
[Guest]: that another brick in the wall. But then you heard the whole albums, and then you said, okay,

02:01:19.480 --> 02:01:25.000
[Guest]: this is a different beast. Each one is a each set of albums, or each album is a different thought

02:01:25.000 --> 02:01:32.120
[Guest]: process altogether. So, the discovery of these things, changed perception, at least in my own

02:01:32.120 --> 02:01:38.360
[Guest]: head. And I think that's happening now. It's like you're starting to, hang on, is this something

02:01:38.360 --> 02:01:43.960
[Guest]: that I can think about? Right now, I can think of about at least 20 or 30 topics that I've discovered

02:01:45.320 --> 02:01:51.160
[Guest]: almost entirely because someone has taken the time, including, let's say, in your interviews

02:01:51.160 --> 02:01:58.120
[Guest]: and podcasts, you might have not wanted the podcast to go there. But it turns out that it is

02:01:58.120 --> 02:02:02.600
[Guest]: because the person on the other side or the conversation that you have brought about this

02:02:02.600 --> 02:02:10.840
[Guest]: intensely interesting piece of information, that is a rabbit hole by itself. And as a listener,

02:02:10.840 --> 02:02:15.480
[Guest]: while you may not have gone down that rabbit hole, it takes me down that rabbit hole in the sense,

02:02:15.480 --> 02:02:20.920
[Guest]: it says, okay, well, I can do this. Sometimes, you know, it's bits and pieces of different things as

02:02:20.920 --> 02:02:28.040
[Guest]: well. So, one of the things that fascinated me a lot, or continues to fascinate me is energy,

02:02:28.040 --> 02:02:33.240
[Guest]: you know, as a as a whole, and how we consume it and how I keep thinking about this and saying,

02:02:33.240 --> 02:02:39.320
[Guest]: you know what, we've, we've started to move and this is my engineer, me speaking, we started to

02:02:39.320 --> 02:02:45.800
[Guest]: move slowly from what used to be an alternating current, current based setup, which is largely

02:02:45.800 --> 02:02:52.280
[Guest]: your earlier while our lights, your fans and stuff, to LED lights and LED TV and LED charger,

02:02:52.280 --> 02:02:58.360
[Guest]: I mean, and digital chargers and TVs, and so on, all of which actually require DC power.

02:02:58.920 --> 02:03:06.680
[Guest]: So, you send AC through the wire, and then use a DC converter to charge your and you want much

02:03:06.680 --> 02:03:12.440
[Guest]: lower voltage for it, you don't need the 220 volts, more and more devices go down this this hole.

02:03:12.440 --> 02:03:18.360
[Guest]: But, you know, it I realized this, it's not like the mainstream media is making all this stuff up,

02:03:18.360 --> 02:03:23.160
[Guest]: it's somewhere somebody started to talk about something and something. So, it's the picture

02:03:23.160 --> 02:03:28.680
[Guest]: started to build in my mind that today, you could have a house built entirely out of DC power,

02:03:28.680 --> 02:03:35.880
[Guest]: almost, other than maybe your fridge, you could go off grid, which means you have a solar power

02:03:35.880 --> 02:03:40.760
[Guest]: thing. So, solar power, it's stored in batteries as DC, you have to actually convert it to AC to

02:03:40.760 --> 02:03:46.920
[Guest]: be able to use it. But if you kept it as DC and power your devices directly, you might not need

02:03:46.920 --> 02:03:51.800
[Guest]: as much power as you think you do, because the size and scale of the batteries required to run

02:03:51.800 --> 02:03:56.600
[Guest]: some convert something to AC is much higher than if you were to directly use the DC.

02:03:56.600 --> 02:04:00.200
[Guest]: This is interesting, because you could go off grid almost entirely.

02:04:01.800 --> 02:04:07.000
[Guest]: Then what happens to the grid? They spend so much money and time building saying,

02:04:07.000 --> 02:04:11.800
[Guest]: oh, we have electrified our villages. And you go to the next village and say, screw you guys,

02:04:11.800 --> 02:04:16.120
[Guest]: we're already electrified. Because we have the solar power, we have the batteries,

02:04:16.120 --> 02:04:19.240
[Guest]: and we've been running this for the last decade. And everybody's looking at each other and saying,

02:04:19.240 --> 02:04:23.880
[Guest]: but we never drew our lines. What happens to all the money that we spent drawing lines to

02:04:23.880 --> 02:04:30.200
[Guest]: this stupid village because we thought it's not electrified? Worse, what if people in the city

02:04:30.200 --> 02:04:36.040
[Guest]: started to do this for themselves and said, forget it, we're not using the main grid anymore.

02:04:36.040 --> 02:04:42.200
[Guest]: All these discoms and the, you know, the distribution companies, what happens to them?

02:04:42.200 --> 02:04:47.320
[Guest]: And this is not me speaking. I mean, this is me speaking right now. But it's a confluence of ideas

02:04:47.320 --> 02:04:51.880
[Guest]: I've started to look around and saying, okay, this guy is asking that question. I'm just putting the

02:04:51.880 --> 02:04:58.520
[Guest]: points together. I don't think I would have had this as an original thought, just by myself.

02:04:58.520 --> 02:05:03.560
[Guest]: It's got to have been all the influences that I've got, maybe bits and pieces over the years,

02:05:03.560 --> 02:05:07.560
[Guest]: that that jigsaw puzzle starts to come into place. And suddenly I find there's a gaping hole over

02:05:07.560 --> 02:05:13.640
[Guest]: there. It's like, I'll give you the, you know, for instance, you can't stop running a power plant,

02:05:13.640 --> 02:05:21.400
[Guest]: which is made of coal or natural gas. It's a lot of effort. If solar power were to take over,

02:05:21.400 --> 02:05:26.600
[Guest]: in a way, power is consumed as soon as it's generated. We don't have the battery capacity

02:05:26.600 --> 02:05:30.680
[Guest]: to store power at that level. So every time you generate the power, it's the same time that it is

02:05:30.680 --> 02:05:39.240
[Guest]: consumed. If solar power works in the day, my availability of my power in the day is 50 gigawatts,

02:05:39.240 --> 02:05:45.400
[Guest]: but in the night it's 20. So to make up for the night, if my power requirements are 30 gigawatts,

02:05:45.400 --> 02:05:50.920
[Guest]: for the night, I need that extra 10 gigawatts to come from somewhere, you know, so not from solar.

02:05:52.120 --> 02:05:56.760
[Guest]: Can I run power plants only at night? The answer is, are you freaking kidding me? You can't.

02:05:56.760 --> 02:06:01.560
[Guest]: The natural gas power plant will have to be run for most of the day. Otherwise,

02:06:01.560 --> 02:06:07.160
[Guest]: you have to change that technology. Suddenly you have a problem because if you keep giving

02:06:07.160 --> 02:06:13.720
[Guest]: impetus to solar power, in the day your power costs will be so low that certain power companies

02:06:13.720 --> 02:06:18.840
[Guest]: will go bankrupt. And in the night, power costs will be so high because solar power isn't there.

02:06:18.840 --> 02:06:22.600
[Guest]: You don't know how to marry these two in any meaningful way unless you actually store power.

02:06:22.600 --> 02:06:27.080
[Guest]: And storing power is a nuclear physicist level problem right now in the sense of

02:06:27.080 --> 02:06:32.040
[Guest]: storing power at that magnitude. It's an interesting problem to have. And the reason

02:06:32.040 --> 02:06:38.440
[Guest]: that I have it as a thought process also is simply because there are so many of these things I have

02:06:38.440 --> 02:06:43.000
[Guest]: seen, these pieces that I've seen, and some of them are comedy. Some of them have probably

02:06:43.000 --> 02:06:48.360
[Guest]: mentioned this in some comic, you know, there are these people who kind of do physics, like you said,

02:06:48.360 --> 02:06:52.920
[Guest]: Miss Excel, there's Miss Macroeconomics in a way, who come and do these complex macroeconomics

02:06:52.920 --> 02:06:57.240
[Guest]: topics. And then they put this into like this really funny video, that after you finish the

02:06:57.240 --> 02:07:02.920
[Guest]: video and saying, I had a good laugh, but this is a real problem. I find it fascinating that the

02:07:02.920 --> 02:07:09.240
[Guest]: creative creator economy opens our eyes into these, these, you know, these crazy levels of things,

02:07:09.960 --> 02:07:16.920
[Guest]: which for a mainstream media to have actually addressed would be get 15 people who are PhDs,

02:07:16.920 --> 02:07:22.280
[Guest]: get each of their opinions on the problem. So you would not go to random person on internet who

02:07:22.280 --> 02:07:28.920
[Guest]: perhaps has about 5% of an idea on this. And this is the interesting part, and I think you and I

02:07:29.720 --> 02:07:37.480
[Guest]: gel on this. There is no longer a call to authority that works on the internet, which means

02:07:37.480 --> 02:07:46.120
[Guest]: you could be a nobody, a Joe Rogan, and comment on something that you don't have a degree in,

02:07:46.120 --> 02:07:51.800
[Guest]: simply because you have enough of a context to make a voice. And people will not grudge you that,

02:07:51.800 --> 02:07:56.200
[Guest]: of course, some people will grudge you that forever, but not enough people and people will

02:07:56.200 --> 02:08:01.960
[Guest]: give you a chance. Whereas in the olden world, you wouldn't even get the podium to stand and speak on.

02:08:01.960 --> 02:08:08.440
[Guest]: What changes because this, this is this thing is remarkable from a perspective of, you know,

02:08:08.440 --> 02:08:12.520
[Guest]: equality, equality, democratizing, also a lot of noise, because now everybody's an expert on

02:08:13.400 --> 02:08:19.960
[Guest]: protein covered with something that spike protein. Yeah, that's the word. Everybody knows what spike

02:08:19.960 --> 02:08:24.840
[Guest]: protein is and how it works, which is not necessarily a good thing. But at some level,

02:08:24.840 --> 02:08:32.040
[Guest]: at some level, this democracy is is helpful, because if it, it changes, if it helps change

02:08:32.040 --> 02:08:37.160
[Guest]: the world in a little way, that little way will magnify to give compounding effects in the future.

02:08:38.920 --> 02:08:43.640
[Amit Varma]: So I want to touch on various aspects of this, like, in our last episode, I think we discussed

02:08:43.640 --> 02:08:49.080
[Amit Varma]: nuclear power a little bit, which I think is the one big solution, which makes much of this more.

02:08:49.080 --> 02:08:52.760
[Amit Varma]: But apart from that, I loved your framework. I love the phrase, I've written it down,

02:08:52.760 --> 02:08:57.320
[Amit Varma]: what happens to the grid, because I think as a framework, it works across so many things,

02:08:57.320 --> 02:09:03.240
[Amit Varma]: and it works on in the creator economy, right? Now, what you were earlier saying about niches

02:09:03.240 --> 02:09:07.320
[Amit Varma]: not being recognized, you know, so in the 90s, what used to happen, and I worked for a while,

02:09:07.320 --> 02:09:11.560
[Amit Varma]: they're in channel V and MTV, and so on. And in the 90s, there was this thing where

02:09:11.560 --> 02:09:16.120
[Amit Varma]: multinationals would come to India, and they would think that India is Bollywood and cricket

02:09:16.120 --> 02:09:20.040
[Amit Varma]: to Joby can now you make your marketing your advertising around Bollywood and cricket,

02:09:20.040 --> 02:09:24.440
[Amit Varma]: and that's it. And that's all they knew. And then over a period of time, there was, you know,

02:09:24.440 --> 02:09:29.240
[Amit Varma]: some nuance kind of crept in. Now, what I have seen recently is a lot of new entrants into the

02:09:29.240 --> 02:09:34.840
[Amit Varma]: space came with this whole mindset. Like, you know, Audible started this podcasting this thing

02:09:34.840 --> 02:09:41.960
[Amit Varma]: called Audible Suno briefly, and Spotify came in here as well. And they came with the same mindset,

02:09:41.960 --> 02:09:46.920
[Amit Varma]: even Netflix has that, that Bollywood is everything. So Netflix is not coming here and

02:09:46.920 --> 02:09:50.520
[Amit Varma]: saying, Okay, you know, let's look at the whole creator ecosystem. They're saying let's go to

02:09:50.520 --> 02:09:56.120
[Amit Varma]: Karan Johar, or let's go to big Bollywood names. And that's it. You know, when Audible Suno came,

02:09:56.120 --> 02:10:00.520
[Amit Varma]: I pitched a couple of shows to them at the time and the scene and the unseen even then was,

02:10:00.520 --> 02:10:05.080
[Amit Varma]: you know, doing pretty well. But the person I met there had been hired from Zee. And forget me,

02:10:05.080 --> 02:10:12.360
[Amit Varma]: she hadn't heard of Joe Rogan. Right. And she said, I don't listen to podcasts.

02:10:12.360 --> 02:10:18.680
[Amit Varma]: And they commissioned a bunch of filmy shows and they commissioned a bunch of

02:10:18.680 --> 02:10:23.960
[Amit Varma]: shit which was based around celebrities. Now the point is those big names will get you initial

02:10:23.960 --> 02:10:28.680
[Amit Varma]: numbers, but they won't get you the depth of engagement, because they are not because the

02:10:28.680 --> 02:10:33.800
[Amit Varma]: content is shallow, right? They won't give you that intimate economy field, that intimate creator

02:10:33.800 --> 02:10:39.000
[Amit Varma]: ecosystem field. The smart way for these big companies to think about it would be to say,

02:10:39.000 --> 02:10:44.040
[Amit Varma]: what can we do to enable an ecosystem, where the best creators rise to the top,

02:10:44.040 --> 02:10:49.240
[Amit Varma]: where we can look for authentic voices, like this, in a sense is a kind of thinking,

02:10:49.240 --> 02:10:53.560
[Amit Varma]: which is skeuomorphic. Have you heard the term? Skeuomorphic. Skeuomorphic. So in design,

02:10:53.560 --> 02:11:00.200
[Amit Varma]: skeuomorphic is used as you are using a design from one paradigm in a separate paradigm to make

02:11:00.200 --> 02:11:05.960
[Amit Varma]: people comfortable with it. For example, when Apple had their ebooks app, in I think the late

02:11:05.960 --> 02:11:11.320
[Amit Varma]: aughties, you know, it looked like a bookshelf on the screen. Right? So people who want to read

02:11:11.320 --> 02:11:17.240
[Amit Varma]: books, you're giving them an artifact from the past and making that the visual representation.

02:11:17.240 --> 02:11:22.360
[Amit Varma]: So that's kind of how it looks like, like there are some music mixing softwares,

02:11:22.360 --> 02:11:25.800
[Amit Varma]: where you will actually the software will have these knobs, which you can turn.

02:11:25.800 --> 02:11:26.600
[Unknown]: Yeah, right.

02:11:26.600 --> 02:11:31.480
[Amit Varma]: And you don't actually need that. But it's just to make people comfortable with because they're

02:11:31.480 --> 02:11:37.640
[Amit Varma]: used to it. Now, I think that marketers in the mainstream media, increasingly think of the not

02:11:37.640 --> 02:11:42.600
[Amit Varma]: increasingly the forever thought of the world in this skeuomorphic ways, where if there is something

02:11:42.600 --> 02:11:50.120
[Amit Varma]: that comes up that they don't understand, they want to fit in, into their pre existing conceptions

02:11:50.120 --> 02:11:55.320
[Amit Varma]: of what is kind of going on there going on in the scene. And I think this is you know,

02:11:55.320 --> 02:11:59.720
[Amit Varma]: and I think this doesn't matter. Like I'm a creator, it doesn't bother me, you know,

02:11:59.720 --> 02:12:04.280
[Amit Varma]: you know, it doesn't bother me at all. I had pitched stuff to Spotify as well. They also,

02:12:04.280 --> 02:12:07.160
[Amit Varma]: they were just more into celeb names and all that. I keep saying Audible,

02:12:07.160 --> 02:12:12.760
[Amit Varma]: Suno was about Bollywood, Spotify is about Bandra. It's just, but it, you know,

02:12:12.760 --> 02:12:16.440
[Amit Varma]: so they can do whatever content that they want, and eventually, you know,

02:12:17.720 --> 02:12:22.760
[Amit Varma]: shit settles down. But the point is, thankfully, the creator economy has gotten to the point

02:12:22.760 --> 02:12:27.320
[Amit Varma]: where we don't need these people anymore. Right? And creators everywhere get this.

02:12:27.320 --> 02:12:31.640
[Amit Varma]: And there's kind of a period of time and some of them will figure it out, right? Like, and some of

02:12:31.640 --> 02:12:36.040
[Amit Varma]: them won't. So Kodak didn't figure it out, for example, and they're not there. Netflix figured

02:12:36.040 --> 02:12:41.960
[Amit Varma]: it out. They started as DVD rentals. Right? And but they figured it out. So some people will figure

02:12:41.960 --> 02:12:47.640
[Amit Varma]: it out. Some people won't and it doesn't really bother me. And as far as you know, what you

02:12:47.640 --> 02:12:51.880
[Amit Varma]: mentioned about, you know, you mentioned Joe Rogan. Now, the thing with Rogan here is this,

02:12:51.880 --> 02:12:57.400
[Amit Varma]: that number one, I don't even know why he signed the Spotify deal. He's already, you know,

02:12:57.400 --> 02:13:02.360
[Amit Varma]: he transcended that space. You know, whatever one thinks of him, you know, I could give him a few

02:13:02.360 --> 02:13:07.800
[Amit Varma]: tips on craft, but whatever one thinks of him, he transcended that space and did some things really

02:13:07.800 --> 02:13:13.160
[Amit Varma]: well. And he didn't need to do that. But the important thing here is this in terms of principle

02:13:13.160 --> 02:13:17.320
[Amit Varma]: and why I agree with you that the increased democratization is a good thing. And that

02:13:17.320 --> 02:13:21.160
[Amit Varma]: people like him are uncancellable. That today, you may disagree with Joe Rogan and say,

02:13:21.160 --> 02:13:25.960
[Amit Varma]: Rogan and say that, oh, he's siding with the anti-vaxxers or he's got this idiot called Malone

02:13:25.960 --> 02:13:30.920
[Amit Varma]: on a show who's talking nonsense. And, you know, de-platform him. Today, you may say that. Today,

02:13:30.920 --> 02:13:37.960
[Amit Varma]: you may disagree with Rogan. But tomorrow, somebody you agree with, the same principle

02:13:37.960 --> 02:13:43.160
[Amit Varma]: will apply. Right? You know, what will the tech giants go by? The tech giants will either go by

02:13:43.160 --> 02:13:47.320
[Amit Varma]: the prevailing politics of the day as they might be within the company, or by the government of

02:13:47.320 --> 02:13:52.280
[Amit Varma]: the day and what the state in each country tells them to do. You know, so today, if you're a liberal

02:13:52.280 --> 02:13:57.560
[Amit Varma]: in India, saying that, oh, he's an anti-vaxxer, and he's this and shut him up. Tomorrow, Adityanath

02:13:57.560 --> 02:14:03.480
[Amit Varma]: will apply the same principle to shut your ass down. Right? So what you got to do is you got to

02:14:03.480 --> 02:14:08.600
[Amit Varma]: stand up for principles. And the principle there is free speech and the principle there is whatever

02:14:08.600 --> 02:14:13.400
[Amit Varma]: and in this whole fracas, by the way, I think everyone behaved appropriately. You know, Neil

02:14:13.400 --> 02:14:18.200
[Amit Varma]: Young and Joni Mitchell, both of whose music I love and listen to much more than to Rogan,

02:14:18.760 --> 02:14:22.360
[Amit Varma]: were entitled to make a stand and take their music out, you know, more power to them standing

02:14:22.360 --> 02:14:27.640
[Amit Varma]: up for principles. Spotify also was entitled to say that, no, we'll keep this guy on our platform,

02:14:27.640 --> 02:14:32.520
[Amit Varma]: you know, though, I think they should have been more firm about it and reiterated the principle

02:14:33.080 --> 02:14:39.480
[Amit Varma]: behind the whole thing. And so yeah, it's kind of an interesting sort of case. But I just don't

02:14:39.480 --> 02:14:44.280
[Guest]: know why he signed with Spotify. In fact, one thing that I do want to say over here is he had

02:14:44.280 --> 02:14:50.360
[Guest]: about 200 million downloads a month before he started. Yeah, Spotify and Spotify now has 400

02:14:50.360 --> 02:14:56.360
[Guest]: million dollars of downloads a month, which I think is a is weird because he's half of Spotify

02:14:56.360 --> 02:15:04.680
[Guest]: in terms of downloads or is it but the point isn't that the point is, you can't cancel Joe Rogan.

02:15:04.680 --> 02:15:09.720
[Guest]: Because earlier, you could shut a person down, you could shut a person down by going to his

02:15:09.720 --> 02:15:14.520
[Guest]: employer and saying shut him down. He should not be allowed to say what he wants to say.

02:15:15.240 --> 02:15:20.040
[Guest]: You can't do that with Joe Rogan anymore. If you take him out of Spotify, they will still be a

02:15:20.040 --> 02:15:26.040
[Guest]: Joe Rogan that is intensely popular, and so popular that you would now no longer have anywhere

02:15:26.040 --> 02:15:29.560
[Guest]: else to go, you literally have to go to the internet to shut them down. You have to go to

02:15:29.560 --> 02:15:34.760
[Guest]: Google and say when people search for him, stop showing his show, at which point they will be

02:15:34.760 --> 02:15:39.640
[Guest]: an competitor to Google will show them and people will still find this is insane. Because I mean,

02:15:39.640 --> 02:15:44.840
[Guest]: I'd learned this in Dream 11. Dream 11 app apparently was not available on the App Store

02:15:44.840 --> 02:15:51.480
[Guest]: because it was akin to whatever gambling or whatever it was. So people found a way to install

02:15:51.480 --> 02:15:56.920
[Guest]: it on their Android phones. I'm like, you know, you couldn't say this to a person saying if you're

02:15:56.920 --> 02:16:03.800
[Guest]: if I'm not on the App Store, am I finished? The answer is no. With appropriate popularity,

02:16:03.800 --> 02:16:09.560
[Guest]: you can get people to bypass what the traditional way was to access your application,

02:16:09.560 --> 02:16:14.760
[Guest]: which is go to the App Store and search for it. To I have an app over here, please download it

02:16:14.760 --> 02:16:20.200
[Guest]: to this setting in your phone, allow external apps to be run and then let run this separately.

02:16:20.200 --> 02:16:24.920
[Guest]: Enough people ran it simply because it was an app that was immensely popular.

02:16:24.920 --> 02:16:30.280
[Guest]: You can't you couldn't cancel the app, it had enough money behind it. But now you can't cancel

02:16:30.280 --> 02:16:36.680
[Guest]: a voice because the voice will find a way to get to you. Regardless, I mean, you could cancel it by

02:16:36.680 --> 02:16:41.640
[Guest]: you know, putting the person in jail. Of course, that that can happen. But I'm just saying that

02:16:41.640 --> 02:16:47.000
[Guest]: this concept of a popular notion of saying 50% of the people are for something and 50% are against,

02:16:47.000 --> 02:16:54.120
[Guest]: but the against people are louder. And therefore, we, they should be allowed to shut this person

02:16:54.120 --> 02:16:59.320
[Guest]: down. I don't think that happens anymore. It's very clear, which is very huge. I don't think

02:16:59.320 --> 02:17:06.280
[Guest]: anybody could shut down Amit Verma for meeting, I don't know, a person who had an alternative view

02:17:06.280 --> 02:17:12.440
[Guest]: about science, religion, technology, whatever, or who came and said, of course, you can cancel

02:17:12.440 --> 02:17:17.000
[Guest]: the grid, all the discoms ought to be bankrupt. Can the discoms go to the government and say,

02:17:17.000 --> 02:17:20.600
[Guest]: shut Amit Verma down? I don't think they can. I don't think they should be allowed to.

02:17:20.600 --> 02:17:26.360
[Guest]: And it's more power to the creator economy because if Amit Verma was on a Wall Street Journal,

02:17:26.360 --> 02:17:28.280
[Guest]: that Wall Street Journal could have stopped your column.

02:17:29.240 --> 02:17:33.800
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, no, a number of points. And by the way, the Ministry of Ayush once complained to Times

02:17:33.800 --> 02:17:38.040
[Amit Varma]: of India about a column I wrote, where I really shat on the Ministry of Ayush,

02:17:38.040 --> 02:17:43.160
[Amit Varma]: and they demanded an apology. And my literate DOI called me and she was quite amused and she said,

02:17:43.160 --> 02:17:46.600
[Amit Varma]: what do you want to do? And I said, I can double down, no way I'm ever apologizing. And of course,

02:17:46.600 --> 02:17:52.520
[Amit Varma]: I didn't and I wasn't cancelled. But there's a disturbing nuance here, which is that yes,

02:17:52.520 --> 02:17:57.960
[Amit Varma]: Joe Rogan is too big to be cancelled. But he's too big. That's why, you know, if you're much

02:17:57.960 --> 02:18:02.600
[Amit Varma]: smaller, if you're somebody starting out, if you need to do 200 videos before you become good and

02:18:02.600 --> 02:18:07.880
[Amit Varma]: you reach that level, and early on, you don't agree with whatever the consensus is, whether

02:18:07.880 --> 02:18:12.520
[Amit Varma]: it's right wing or left wing or whatever, and you're shut down, you know, for that reason,

02:18:12.520 --> 02:18:17.880
[Amit Varma]: then or you censor yourself and you just stop for that reason, because the environment is too noisy.

02:18:17.880 --> 02:18:22.360
[Amit Varma]: That becomes a problem. I mean, I don't even, you know, that 50-50 formulation you made,

02:18:22.360 --> 02:18:28.440
[Amit Varma]: I don't agree with it. I think only three or 4% of the people are strident and loud and go into

02:18:28.440 --> 02:18:33.000
[Amit Varma]: this. You have a vocal minority, which is really small and a silent majority, which either doesn't

02:18:33.000 --> 02:18:39.720
[Amit Varma]: give a shit, or they're like, you know, let 1000 flowers blossom. But a silent minority is kind of

02:18:39.720 --> 02:18:43.960
[Amit Varma]: an illustration of this is Dave Chappelle, where, you know, there was such an outcry when his last

02:18:43.960 --> 02:18:48.280
[Amit Varma]: special came out, but you go to Rotten Tomatoes and you see the rating, you know, and there is

02:18:48.280 --> 02:18:55.000
[Amit Varma]: no doubt it was last I checked 97.5% or whatever, adored by the vast masses of people. Now a few

02:18:55.000 --> 02:19:00.360
[Amit Varma]: random people will do their thing and that's okay. The worry is that these manic silent,

02:19:00.360 --> 02:19:06.360
[Amit Varma]: these manic vocal minorities might sometimes, you know, have, yeah, you know, people will just say,

02:19:06.360 --> 02:19:10.680
[Guest]: you know, why get into this, you know? Yeah, especially I mean, if you like, for instance,

02:19:10.680 --> 02:19:16.120
[Guest]: if Neil Young, for instance, who's, who's universally liked, I think, takes a stand,

02:19:16.120 --> 02:19:20.200
[Guest]: it almost makes you feel that Joe Rogan must be doing something really stupid.

02:19:20.200 --> 02:19:23.880
[Amit Varma]: You know, the interesting thing there is that two artists I greatly admire,

02:19:23.880 --> 02:19:28.120
[Amit Varma]: to my great dismay, took a stand last year, which I didn't agree with, which is Eric Clapton and Van

02:19:28.120 --> 02:19:32.680
[Amit Varma]: Morrison, and I adore Van Morrison. You know, a lot of some of his music is like the soundtrack

02:19:32.680 --> 02:19:37.960
[Amit Varma]: to my growing up years. And they came out as hardcore anti-maskers and anti-vaxxers and all

02:19:37.960 --> 02:19:44.200
[Amit Varma]: that. And it's so sort of, but that consolidated my case for separating the art from the artist.

02:19:45.240 --> 02:19:51.000
[Amit Varma]: I love their music. But now the guy is behaving like a, you know, whatever, and they're wrong,

02:19:51.000 --> 02:19:56.920
[Amit Varma]: but it is what it is. Right? So it's not as if all the artists are necessarily on one side on this.

02:19:56.920 --> 02:20:03.960
[Amit Varma]: I mean, a Neil Young versus Eric Clapton mud fight or something would kind of be fun. But,

02:20:03.960 --> 02:20:09.400
[Amit Varma]: but yeah, on the whole, you want diverse voices to flourish. But then the worry there is the tyranny

02:20:09.400 --> 02:20:13.800
[Amit Varma]: of the social media algorithms, because the fact of the matter, and that's a whole separate problem

02:20:13.800 --> 02:20:19.000
[Amit Varma]: we could talk for five hours about, is that you have these social media behemoths like your

02:20:19.000 --> 02:20:24.360
[Amit Varma]: Facebook and your Twitter and your Google, which have way too much power, which have way too much

02:20:24.360 --> 02:20:32.040
[Amit Varma]: power. So what you want to democratize, also, is that kind of access where artists aren't

02:20:32.040 --> 02:20:37.560
[Amit Varma]: necessarily dependent on them, that if they run afoul of the YouTube algorithm, for whatever reason,

02:20:37.560 --> 02:20:43.320
[Amit Varma]: they're kind of cut out of it, right? Now, what I have built is that whatever audience like my

02:20:43.320 --> 02:20:49.000
[Amit Varma]: thing comes on all podcast apps, I'm not dependent on algorithms for discovery. The audience I have

02:20:49.000 --> 02:20:54.200
[Amit Varma]: this the audience I have, and it spreads by word of mouth and is grown organically. So I'm lucky

02:20:54.200 --> 02:20:59.320
[Amit Varma]: enough to get to that stage where, you know, that is there. But if you're just starting out,

02:20:59.320 --> 02:21:04.200
[Amit Varma]: you know, and the algorithms are doing whatever the hell they're doing, then what do you do on

02:21:04.200 --> 02:21:09.880
[Amit Varma]: Facebook, for example, I just have a, it's like very personal, Twitter is where I broadcast,

02:21:09.880 --> 02:21:14.760
[Amit Varma]: Facebook is just kind of family and friends and all of that. But there every time, you know,

02:21:14.760 --> 02:21:19.320
[Amit Varma]: just as I post a link to my podcast on Twitter, I post them on Facebook, and nobody notices because

02:21:19.320 --> 02:21:24.280
[Amit Varma]: their algo downgrades links, if you put a link, it will not show up on somebody's timeline. So

02:21:24.280 --> 02:21:28.520
[Amit Varma]: yeah, if you put a photo, it will, but only if you don't post a link with it. So what many people

02:21:28.520 --> 02:21:32.680
[Amit Varma]: will do is they'll post a photo, and they'll say link in the first comment and they'll put the link

02:21:32.680 --> 02:21:37.240
[Amit Varma]: there. And I don't give a damn, I just whatever I post on Twitter, I posted there, I know there'll

02:21:37.240 --> 02:21:42.360
[Amit Varma]: be like four likes, and I don't I don't kind of care about that. But that shows you that,

02:21:42.360 --> 02:21:47.800
[Amit Varma]: you know, that artists should not have to think about algorithms and have to cater to that. And

02:21:47.800 --> 02:21:54.440
[Amit Varma]: there'll be YouTube courses, which will teach you how to sort of, you know, sort of weave your

02:21:54.440 --> 02:21:58.680
[Amit Varma]: content and all the things that you do in the headline that you give, and the image that you

02:21:58.680 --> 02:22:03.880
[Amit Varma]: use so that, you know, and the frequency with which you post. And I, you know, and I'm probably

02:22:03.880 --> 02:22:09.640
[Amit Varma]: a bit extreme in this kind of idealism, but I just want to do my whatever I do, without thinking of

02:22:09.640 --> 02:22:13.720
[Amit Varma]: any of these things, that, you know, if I'm recording a conversation, I want to record the

02:22:13.720 --> 02:22:19.160
[Amit Varma]: conversation I most enjoy having, and not think how to market it, and how will an algo push it

02:22:19.160 --> 02:22:25.240
[Guest]: and all that. But that's a bit of an interesting that you say that, because one of the things that

02:22:25.240 --> 02:22:28.920
[Guest]: people told me when I started off writing at Capital Mind was that Deepak, you have to focus

02:22:28.920 --> 02:22:35.000
[Guest]: on SEO. So being lazy as I was, I said, I have two things to do, might I have a limited amount

02:22:35.000 --> 02:22:40.840
[Guest]: of time, one, I can learn more about finance and write it, or I can learn about SEO. I chose to

02:22:40.840 --> 02:22:45.480
[Guest]: learn about finance and write it. And of course, that was interesting that I went, what happened

02:22:45.480 --> 02:22:50.520
[Guest]: to this SEO stuff was quite interesting. So in the process of doing this, people had figured out

02:22:50.520 --> 02:22:54.840
[Guest]: Google's algorithms around text. So they said, you know what, this is what you should write,

02:22:54.840 --> 02:22:59.560
[Guest]: the headline should have these keywords and something, search for the keyword before you

02:22:59.560 --> 02:23:05.480
[Guest]: write the content. And I'm like, yeah, yeah, I will, I need to figure out what I want to write

02:23:05.480 --> 02:23:10.520
[Guest]: about. And I want to write about that. And this may be an esoteric, very boring topic, like

02:23:10.520 --> 02:23:15.880
[Guest]: how does RBI pump money into the economy, which is a great headline to have because you read that

02:23:15.880 --> 02:23:19.720
[Guest]: and then you read the content and you're like, oh my god, this is really boring. So how do I make

02:23:19.720 --> 02:23:25.000
[Guest]: it exciting. So I'm going to use my Abeyars and I'm going to use my other ways to keep the audience

02:23:25.880 --> 02:23:30.120
[Guest]: at least hooked up to a point where I can say you've read enough to answer a few questions

02:23:30.120 --> 02:23:36.600
[Guest]: if you're asked about it at parties. But beyond this, I am not willing to do an SEO work that

02:23:36.600 --> 02:23:42.280
[Guest]: says, you know what, put the word RBI 17 times so that when people search for RBI, Google says your

02:23:42.280 --> 02:23:49.400
[Guest]: RBI. So I was doing this normally. But then somewhere along and I think 2010 or 2011,

02:23:49.400 --> 02:23:55.080
[Guest]: Google changed its algorithm. It suddenly decided that people who are tricking its algorithm into

02:23:55.080 --> 02:24:01.240
[Guest]: bringing their pages to the forefront are going to get penalized. And people suddenly lost a

02:24:01.240 --> 02:24:05.560
[Guest]: very large amount of traffic and I would get people in the finance area, which is a bunch of

02:24:05.560 --> 02:24:10.280
[Guest]: people in the same area that I was complaining saying, listen, we've lost all I'm not getting

02:24:10.280 --> 02:24:15.640
[Guest]: enough. It's I'm looking my hits and I'm like, they're the same or they're growing. And it turns

02:24:15.640 --> 02:24:21.800
[Guest]: out that because I was not using any of these SEO techniques, I saw nothing change in that algorithm.

02:24:21.800 --> 02:24:26.680
[Guest]: And therefore I was not a slave to it. Of course, I may I will still be a slave to it in some way.

02:24:26.680 --> 02:24:31.640
[Guest]: But I was getting the compounding effect that because now when people start searching for the

02:24:31.640 --> 02:24:36.360
[Guest]: same content, I didn't have as much competition, I was getting highlighted a lot more. I think

02:24:36.360 --> 02:24:41.000
[Guest]: this is going to happen with the algos that you mentioned on YouTube and Facebook also.

02:24:41.560 --> 02:24:46.120
[Guest]: Facebook, of course, there is an evil nature to it, which is that they tell you that listen,

02:24:46.120 --> 02:24:51.160
[Guest]: you're no longer going to be organic because you aren't paying us. So if you paid us,

02:24:51.160 --> 02:24:55.400
[Guest]: then maybe we would show you some more we'd show you to a bunch of more of your friends.

02:24:55.400 --> 02:25:01.160
[Guest]: And you're like, dude, I built this community on Facebook. That means all these people follow me

02:25:01.160 --> 02:25:05.960
[Guest]: for me. And now you're telling me I need to pay to get to the same people, which sounds a little

02:25:05.960 --> 02:25:11.080
[Guest]: obscene. But that's fine. It's a platform by itself, you learn, you live to learn and so on.

02:25:11.080 --> 02:25:19.240
[Guest]: But over time, I think like what you've done is build a community on so many platforms,

02:25:19.240 --> 02:25:24.600
[Guest]: that if one platform through its weight around, you would not get impacted. Of course,

02:25:24.600 --> 02:25:28.920
[Guest]: they're eventually all slaves to at least a few of these at some point.

02:25:28.920 --> 02:25:33.560
[Amit Varma]: No, I think what I managed to do and what not everyone can do, and I kind of

02:25:34.120 --> 02:25:38.120
[Amit Varma]: lucked into it. And I'm probably the kind of person who I was like, I don't care about money,

02:25:38.120 --> 02:25:41.800
[Amit Varma]: I don't care, I'll just do what I do. And whatever following that I have,

02:25:42.760 --> 02:25:47.560
[Amit Varma]: has nothing to do with an algorithm. The discovery is not algorithm, the discovery is always word of

02:25:47.560 --> 02:25:52.680
[Amit Varma]: mouth, or some friend said, hey, this episode is great, and you listen to it, and it becomes a

02:25:52.680 --> 02:25:57.720
[Amit Varma]: habit and all of that. And so therefore, I'm freed of the algorithm. Now the point is, if I was a

02:25:57.720 --> 02:26:02.280
[Amit Varma]: really savvy marketing person, if I understood all of this, could I get more people to listen,

02:26:02.280 --> 02:26:07.160
[Amit Varma]: perhaps, but then the point is that part of my mental bandwidth would go there. And I just want

02:26:07.160 --> 02:26:13.080
[Amit Varma]: 100% of my mental bandwidth to go into this. You know, if I'm going to talk to you, and I have say

02:26:13.080 --> 02:26:17.560
[Amit Varma]: 20 hours, I want to spend 20 hours in prepping for talking to you and then have the hopefully

02:26:17.560 --> 02:26:22.840
[Amit Varma]: five hour plus conversation which this can become. I don't want to spend 10 hours out of that

02:26:22.840 --> 02:26:32.040
[Amit Varma]: thinking is algorithm. I don't want to do that. Whatever shit Yeah, because I think then,

02:26:32.040 --> 02:26:37.240
[Amit Varma]: you know, it's that's an endless game you are playing because any algorithm can be gamed.

02:26:37.240 --> 02:26:42.600
[Amit Varma]: But as people figure out the way to game it, the algorithm will change. And that's an endless race

02:26:42.600 --> 02:26:47.480
[Amit Varma]: you can get into. And I'm like, No, man, like I idealistically say a good product is a best

02:26:47.480 --> 02:26:53.080
[Amit Varma]: marketing. Just do something that makes people you know, recommend what you're doing to other people

02:26:53.080 --> 02:26:58.760
[Amit Varma]: that makes people you know, make you a habit and and so enter their comfort zones. And but,

02:26:59.400 --> 02:27:03.880
[Amit Varma]: you know, it's easy for me to say that having reached a stage where but if you're starting out

02:27:03.880 --> 02:27:09.720
[Amit Varma]: today, then it's so confusing for a young creator and my advice would still remain that just do what

02:27:09.720 --> 02:27:13.960
[Amit Varma]: you love and do it often and don't care too much about validation and eventually shit works out.

02:27:13.960 --> 02:27:18.040
[Amit Varma]: And a lot of work is good and worth doing for its own sake.

02:27:19.480 --> 02:27:25.320
[Guest]: In fact, that is the most difficult thing you can ever teach somebody is like do it now. They

02:27:25.320 --> 02:27:31.880
[Guest]: will not come now. Yeah, they will come later. And the problem is build it and they will come

02:27:31.880 --> 02:27:37.080
[Guest]: almost says as soon as I finish building it, they will start coming. Whereas I'm saying just keep

02:27:37.080 --> 02:27:43.960
[Guest]: building it. And they will keep coming. Eventually, it's not it's it's a difficult conversation to have

02:27:43.960 --> 02:27:51.480
[Guest]: because you're talking delayed gratification of someone's work. Because when I work, I get a salary

02:27:51.480 --> 02:27:56.200
[Guest]: at the end of the month. It's instant gratification in that context, right. But when I'm building a

02:27:56.200 --> 02:28:01.560
[Guest]: business, I'm going to struggle, struggle, struggle for three years. And somebody told me this, you

02:28:01.560 --> 02:28:07.560
[Guest]: know, this is saying that for the first three years, don't ask me about profit or what I get out

02:28:07.560 --> 02:28:13.560
[Guest]: of the business. After three years, ask only what I get out of the business. That means your first

02:28:13.560 --> 02:28:19.320
[Guest]: three years are built in only building a flywheel that generates revenue. After three years, you can

02:28:19.320 --> 02:28:25.800
[Guest]: optimize it and build whatever. So maybe it may take five years in this case. But in a day when

02:28:25.800 --> 02:28:30.920
[Guest]: you're watching content that's only three days old, five years sounds like yeah, what is wrong

