[Amit Varma]: the expert. And, and I'm fascinated by and I'm trying to learn about it. And that, of course,

02:31:14.680 --> 02:31:21.400
[Amit Varma]: is your brilliant book Money Wise, which, you know, tells people how to approach their money,

02:31:21.400 --> 02:31:26.760
[Amit Varma]: and just demystifies that completely and breaks it down. Before we get to the book itself,

02:31:26.760 --> 02:31:31.160
[Amit Varma]: tell me about where did the idea of the book come from? Like, when did you think of the book? And

02:31:31.160 --> 02:31:36.440
[Amit Varma]: when you thought of the book? Like, were there any models that you looked at any previous books,

02:31:36.440 --> 02:31:41.240
[Amit Varma]: which were on in the same territory? You know, what? How did that? How did the book evolve?

02:31:41.240 --> 02:31:46.920
[Guest]: So this is interesting, because the book itself has been thought process in the last maybe five

02:31:46.920 --> 02:31:52.360
[Guest]: to six years. In fact, the first time I started talking about a book of this sort, was to a

02:31:52.360 --> 02:31:59.400
[Guest]: publisher in 2014. Roughly, that's the first time I had a conversation. And then I wasn't very sure

02:31:59.400 --> 02:32:04.280
[Guest]: that I could do it at the time. And I didn't feel that I had enough to write about. And I wanted to

02:32:04.280 --> 02:32:10.360
[Guest]: write about a slightly different topic at the time. And it's chapter in this book, that I think

02:32:10.360 --> 02:32:14.360
[Guest]: deserves to be a book by itself. It's called Suckered. So the idea being, you know, all the

02:32:14.360 --> 02:32:18.520
[Guest]: scams that have happened and all that stuff, but there wasn't that much of meeting of minds there.

02:32:18.520 --> 02:32:24.040
[Guest]: And I didn't think I had enough, enough material. But you can always trust scams. So we've had about

02:32:24.040 --> 02:32:29.480
[Guest]: five or six since then. We then I said, Okay, maybe I should go on this on my own to try and

02:32:29.480 --> 02:32:36.280
[Guest]: at least write the book. And, but what actually happened was interesting. In the pandemic,

02:32:36.280 --> 02:32:42.200
[Guest]: I was at home, there was enough time because at your lockdown, so it's all you can do is

02:32:42.200 --> 02:32:46.360
[Guest]: you have a lot of thoughts, you can put this together. Chiki at Juggernaut, you know,

02:32:47.160 --> 02:32:53.160
[Guest]: we there was a common connection, she knew her and then, you know, which he introduced us and

02:32:53.160 --> 02:32:58.040
[Guest]: then we started talking and she looked at a piece couple of pieces of the writing. And she said,

02:32:58.040 --> 02:33:04.360
[Guest]: Okay, I'm this is a great idea to write a book on the Suckered topic. But just to start to get

02:33:04.360 --> 02:33:08.360
[Guest]: this together. And I said, Okay, let me get the material together. I started putting it together.

02:33:08.360 --> 02:33:13.720
[Guest]: She then said, the I mean, this was just about before the pandemic is when all our conversations

02:33:13.720 --> 02:33:18.200
[Guest]: started to happen. And then she said, Deepak, there's a problem in the pandemic here. You're

02:33:18.200 --> 02:33:24.280
[Guest]: seeing people want to invest, but they don't have the ability to why don't you write something that

02:33:24.280 --> 02:33:29.480
[Guest]: helps the person who doesn't really know about finance. And that's more challenging for me,

02:33:29.480 --> 02:33:34.280
[Guest]: because if you don't know anything about finance, I can't use half the jargon I use. So

02:33:34.280 --> 02:33:39.640
[Guest]: how do I make it sound interesting, and yet it should have enough information and enough depth

02:33:39.640 --> 02:33:43.560
[Guest]: for someone to be able to get out of this and say, Listen, I've got something that's good,

02:33:43.560 --> 02:33:49.240
[Guest]: good enough for me to at least start. It took a while because it I did the first round of writing,

02:33:49.240 --> 02:33:55.080
[Guest]: I had a bunch of articles of my own from the past, which was we have about 5000 articles on

02:33:55.080 --> 02:33:59.480
[Guest]: Capital Mind. So some of them are timeless, in the sense of having, you know, talked about a

02:33:59.480 --> 02:34:04.040
[Guest]: lot of this from the very basics. But more importantly, I had to write this in a in a

02:34:04.040 --> 02:34:10.840
[Guest]: way that was kind of structured to read as a book. So it was different chapters. So I started off

02:34:10.840 --> 02:34:16.520
[Guest]: with something and then I had to start off with the very basics, which was, which was more of the

02:34:16.520 --> 02:34:22.120
[Guest]: element of so you come to start thinking about stock markets, if I invest, I put my money in,

02:34:22.120 --> 02:34:27.720
[Guest]: and I instantly make some money that comes out of it. And sometimes I can put 100,000 rupees in and

02:34:27.720 --> 02:34:33.320
[Guest]: get 125,000 rupees, so I make 25. So that's the thought process that goes in. The problem is,

02:34:33.960 --> 02:34:37.960
[Guest]: we shouldn't think of finance that way. So I had a different thought process around it a lot of

02:34:37.960 --> 02:34:42.120
[Guest]: myths around these things, I had to break them down first saying this, and you can start investing

02:34:42.120 --> 02:34:47.720
[Guest]: whenever you want, you just have to be disciplined at the concept, you need to understand that there

02:34:47.720 --> 02:34:51.800
[Guest]: are different types of instruments, different type of vehicles and different types of approaches you

02:34:51.800 --> 02:34:56.520
[Guest]: can take to the market. But before you get there, but to stock market investing and all that you

02:34:56.520 --> 02:35:01.960
[Guest]: have to fix some hygiene elements first. Once you start to build that out into the flesh it out

02:35:01.960 --> 02:35:08.760
[Guest]: properly. In fact, once I did this Devangshu, you know, we both know we he actually took a look and

02:35:08.760 --> 02:35:15.400
[Guest]: then removed all the stuff that wasn't the book. So effectively, it's like, you know, you how do

02:35:15.400 --> 02:35:20.040
[Guest]: you make a elephant sculpture, you find a piece of rock and remove the stuff that isn't the elephant.

02:35:20.040 --> 02:35:26.280
[Guest]: So DD actually helped kind of break it all down. But in the process, I found that I repeat the same

02:35:26.280 --> 02:35:32.680
[Guest]: joke at least two times in the book, because I'd written the two parts at different points. I've

02:35:32.680 --> 02:35:38.920
[Guest]: forgotten I'd written that, you know, so you all the stuff I kind of went away. But also, you know,

02:35:38.920 --> 02:35:43.720
[Guest]: then later, of course, they cleaned up, they brought in an editor who would help with the

02:35:43.720 --> 02:35:49.080
[Guest]: with the documents, cleaning up and so on. And then, you know, we released it in November,

02:35:49.080 --> 02:35:55.320
[Guest]: I think they released in November of last year. It took a while to get this into shape. However,

02:35:55.320 --> 02:36:03.320
[Guest]: the I had to spend more time editing it. And I don't edit my articles that much. When I write

02:36:03.320 --> 02:36:07.480
[Guest]: them, they stay written for the most part, even with the spelling mistakes, I don't really go

02:36:07.480 --> 02:36:13.880
[Guest]: back and read unless there's a factual error somewhere. So it took me a lot of effort. I hate

02:36:13.880 --> 02:36:18.120
[Guest]: listening to my own voice. So I don't listen to my own podcasts. And I hate reading my own

02:36:18.120 --> 02:36:22.120
[Guest]: articles, because somehow I find it very difficult for me to read at the same time, just when I've

02:36:22.120 --> 02:36:26.360
[Guest]: written it. I read it about, you know, one year later, then I'm fine. I say, Oh, okay, this is a

02:36:26.360 --> 02:36:31.640
[Guest]: great, this is an interesting thought process that I had at that time, and so on. So this part,

02:36:31.640 --> 02:36:36.360
[Guest]: this time was different, you had to write and read it again, as if you're reading it afresh.

02:36:36.360 --> 02:36:41.480
[Guest]: And you've actually been an inspiration in that because you wrote a book like way back, right. So

02:36:42.280 --> 02:36:48.120
[Guest]: I saw that and I said, Okay, I don't think I'm cut out for fiction. Maybe I am, but it's not

02:36:48.120 --> 02:36:53.800
[Guest]: what I am doing right now. So it's I'm more keen to write books on finance. I also think you have

02:36:53.800 --> 02:36:58.920
[Guest]: many books left in you, looking at just that. So just your poker experience, and I know the

02:36:58.920 --> 02:37:04.680
[Guest]: discipline and you know, so a large part of this also came in from the fact that we know a lot of

02:37:04.680 --> 02:37:10.040
[Guest]: people who've written books, it isn't very different from how they write in some of the,

02:37:10.040 --> 02:37:16.200
[Guest]: you know, email groups that we're on or something like that. But the point is to put a lot of what's

02:37:16.200 --> 02:37:21.720
[Guest]: in your head into a structured way into into the writing. And we know Naren, for instance,

02:37:21.720 --> 02:37:27.400
[Guest]: who I think if you just collect all the stuff he's sent over the years on WhatsApp and a bunch

02:37:27.400 --> 02:37:32.280
[Guest]: of things, could be a fantastic book called Naren is typing, which is what happens when he's typing

02:37:32.280 --> 02:37:37.960
[Guest]: on WhatsApp. I mean, so writing a book, I think is not so much about the writing, it's just about

02:37:37.960 --> 02:37:43.800
[Guest]: the rigor and the discipline. So my inspiration has been, of course, you know, number of writers

02:37:43.800 --> 02:37:50.120
[Guest]: and it isn't the charm of having written a book to the name that it's a nice feeling. And it's not

02:37:50.120 --> 02:37:57.160
[Guest]: the economics because the economics never works out for a book writer, in the sense that there

02:37:57.160 --> 02:38:02.840
[Guest]: are very few people who have become rich writing books, very, very few. And if you start off saying

02:38:02.840 --> 02:38:07.400
[Guest]: I'll become rich using books, you should write a cookbook and try to compete with Tarla Dalal,

02:38:07.400 --> 02:38:13.160
[Guest]: because that's pretty much as transactional as the value gets from a book or write something

02:38:13.160 --> 02:38:17.960
[Guest]: religious that becomes really famous, but don't write like these. I mean, writing about investing

02:38:17.960 --> 02:38:23.000
[Guest]: is great, but with the objective of making money is a very bad idea. I think, you know,

02:38:23.000 --> 02:38:27.640
[Amit Varma]: and two recent web series got this spectacularly wrong, where in Gehraiya, you have this one

