[Amit Varma]: been nice. But anyway, and Naren Shannoy, you're referring to, of course, I did, you know, my 250th

02:38:50.840 --> 02:38:55.880
[Amit Varma]: episode with him. And we had even started a Facebook group called we want Naren Shannoy to

02:38:55.880 --> 02:39:01.160
[Amit Varma]: write a book. And, and yeah, and the last hour of that four hour episode I did with him was just him

02:39:01.160 --> 02:39:08.040
[Amit Varma]: telling stories, one after the other. And it was, it was quite beautiful. So, you know, in another

02:39:08.040 --> 02:39:13.880
[Amit Varma]: part of your biography involves you for a very brief time teaching, where you would teach Java,

02:39:13.880 --> 02:39:20.280
[Amit Varma]: I think for 800 rupees a week or something like that, right? And here you are sort of writing and

02:39:20.280 --> 02:39:26.040
[Amit Varma]: rewriting your book. Now, both of these are really good ways also of sharpening your thinking and

02:39:26.040 --> 02:39:30.120
[Amit Varma]: learning. Like when you have to teach something, you have to answer the really the basic questions

02:39:30.120 --> 02:39:33.880
[Amit Varma]: and you got to know the subject really well. Similarly, when you're writing about something,

02:39:33.880 --> 02:39:37.320
[Amit Varma]: you know, you can write a blog post or an article and put it out there. But if you're writing a book

02:39:37.320 --> 02:39:41.480
[Amit Varma]: and you're editing it, you got to, you know, make sure everything is in its place. And that also

02:39:41.480 --> 02:39:45.960
[Amit Varma]: forces you to kind of examine your thoughts and all of that. So well, as you know, the subject,

02:39:45.960 --> 02:39:51.400
[Amit Varma]: do you feel that your thinking was, you know, clarified further by the act of teaching it or

02:39:51.400 --> 02:39:57.640
[Guest]: writing about it, which are similarly deepening? Yeah. Oh, yeah. I mean, anything. I think I keep

02:39:57.640 --> 02:40:01.720
[Guest]: having this conversation even with people with all my colleagues at Capital Mind itself is

02:40:02.360 --> 02:40:06.520
[Guest]: when you have an idea, write about it. Because if you start writing about it, you start getting

02:40:06.520 --> 02:40:10.680
[Guest]: conceptual clarity. And if you don't get the conceptual clarity, there's something wrong

02:40:10.680 --> 02:40:15.640
[Guest]: enough wrong into the idea because it may be as simple as saying, I think there's an opportunity

02:40:15.640 --> 02:40:22.040
[Guest]: here because and then that because the way you answer that because shows me how much conviction

02:40:22.040 --> 02:40:27.480
[Guest]: you have in the idea, and will show you how much conviction you had in the idea. But also,

02:40:27.480 --> 02:40:32.520
[Guest]: about whether you know all the specific aspects around it. So for one, for one, for instance,

02:40:33.160 --> 02:40:39.640
[Guest]: our problem in this field is that there are way too many, way too many things that can happen.

02:40:39.640 --> 02:40:46.360
[Guest]: Like today, for instance, who would have guessed that today was the day where Russia walks into

02:40:46.360 --> 02:40:53.480
[Guest]: Ukraine? Your the stock market is down x percent and all that stuff worldwide. Does this really

02:40:53.480 --> 02:41:00.120
[Guest]: matter to you as a long term investor and whether it's a temporary blip or a permanent one is not

02:41:00.120 --> 02:41:04.200
[Guest]: something we can answer and you know, or do anything about. When you're trying to write

02:41:04.200 --> 02:41:08.840
[Guest]: about something like this, if you've never experienced this before, you will not be able

02:41:08.840 --> 02:41:12.920
[Guest]: to write about it. If you experience this only once, you'll take the wrong conclusions out of it.

02:41:12.920 --> 02:41:18.440
[Guest]: If you experience it one too many times, you'll end up being quite cynical about the whole world.

02:41:18.440 --> 02:41:22.920
[Guest]: And you'll probably end up writing the wrong thing. So to get perspective, you have to

02:41:22.920 --> 02:41:27.160
[Guest]: basically start thinking from the in the shoes of a person who's never seen this before,

02:41:27.160 --> 02:41:31.080
[Guest]: who's seen this once before, and who's seen this all the many different times,

02:41:31.080 --> 02:41:36.600
[Guest]: and try to address each of their fears and concerns in a different way. This can only come

02:41:37.320 --> 02:41:42.280
[Guest]: from learning. So for instance, when I first started to write about stuff in, I would analyze

02:41:42.280 --> 02:41:50.280
[Guest]: history. And in history, the problem in history is you get very dry accounts. Stock prices,

02:41:50.280 --> 02:41:54.520
[Guest]: for instance, they don't tell you anything, something is dropped to 20%. But if you read

02:41:54.520 --> 02:41:59.320
[Guest]: a book about that day, it will tell you the emotions of the people that were involved,

02:41:59.320 --> 02:42:04.920
[Guest]: where how on what happened during that day. So there was a day in October 1987, when the US

02:42:04.920 --> 02:42:09.880
[Guest]: stock market fell 22%, which is a ridiculously high amount, high amount for the stock to fall.

02:42:09.880 --> 02:42:16.360
[Guest]: Imagine one fifth of your wealth is gone in like a five hour trading day. How would you feel? Now,

02:42:16.360 --> 02:42:22.680
[Guest]: it, this is like, you know, Eddie Izzard says, Pol Pot killed 1.5 million people. And we can't

02:42:22.680 --> 02:42:26.760
[Guest]: get our heads around that number. And we're like, how do you do it? I mean, your, your,

02:42:26.760 --> 02:42:30.840
[Guest]: your schedule must look like wake up in the morning, have breakfast, death, death, death.

02:42:30.840 --> 02:42:36.600
[Guest]: So he said this, and he was right, because we can't get our heads around these kind of numbers

02:42:36.600 --> 02:42:42.920
[Guest]: in any meaningful way. 22% in a day when your average movement is 0.5, and 1%, and one and a

02:42:42.920 --> 02:42:47.480
[Guest]: half percent a day, you so you have no idea what it feels like. So you have to go through those

02:42:47.480 --> 02:42:53.320
[Guest]: accounts. And then you have to write about it in a format that doesn't make you look like you're

02:42:53.320 --> 02:42:57.880
[Guest]: giving a sermon, because most likely you're wrong if you're trying to give a sermon. And therefore,

02:42:57.880 --> 02:43:02.440
[Guest]: you shouldn't go around saying that this is exactly the right way to go. Secondly, you should

02:43:02.440 --> 02:43:09.800
[Guest]: also appear or at least have the knowledge enough to be able to tell people exactly what you're

02:43:09.800 --> 02:43:13.400
[Guest]: thinking about. So for instance, if the markets were to go down, and you're writing a book about

02:43:13.400 --> 02:43:19.640
[Guest]: what you should do, my always my answer to this is don't react in panic, don't buy in a panic,

02:43:19.640 --> 02:43:24.840
[Guest]: don't sell in a panic, because both have downsides. Now, why is buying in a panic bad,

02:43:24.840 --> 02:43:28.920
[Guest]: because the market has fallen x percent, you must be feeling like it's better. But there are,

02:43:28.920 --> 02:43:35.240
[Guest]: you know, a stock that falls 90% is just a stock that first falls 80%. You buy it, and then it

02:43:35.240 --> 02:43:44.680
[Guest]: falls by half. So you have no idea where the, you know, how deep the knife will gash in. So don't

02:43:44.680 --> 02:43:51.560
[Guest]: try to cash catch a falling knife. This is, unfortunately, an element of experience. But

02:43:51.560 --> 02:43:58.280
[Guest]: it's also an element of how you can bring this imagery across to the reader without boring the

02:43:58.280 --> 02:44:04.360
[Guest]: daylight sort of horror. So, you know, that I think is where you have to write to get clarity

02:44:04.360 --> 02:44:10.280
[Guest]: for yourself. Most of the time, I erase maybe 20 to 25% of what I write saying this is not making

02:44:10.280 --> 02:44:17.240
[Guest]: sense. But without that erasing, I would not be able to write, which means I've gone down a rabbit

02:44:17.240 --> 02:44:21.560
[Guest]: hole. And I'm saying no, no, this whole thing is wrong. I want to come back a little bit,

02:44:21.560 --> 02:44:27.480
[Guest]: back it up and then start writing again. That is clarity. So unless you get that conceptual

02:44:27.480 --> 02:44:32.120
[Guest]: clarity or not, but there's some topics where you have conceptual clarity, because you just

02:44:32.120 --> 02:44:40.200
[Guest]: know. And then there you can be more, you know, the amount it helps you is relatively lesser

02:44:40.200 --> 02:44:44.840
[Guest]: compared to the amount it might have helped you in a subject where you have a lot of experience,

02:44:44.840 --> 02:44:49.640
[Guest]: but you're trying to string these thoughts together. The process of writing sometimes

02:44:49.640 --> 02:44:57.080
[Guest]: tells you more about what you don't know than about what you know. And hopefully,

02:44:57.080 --> 02:45:02.200
[Guest]: and I've seen this in a few authors very prominently, but hopefully it builds humility

02:45:02.200 --> 02:45:08.040
[Guest]: inside of you. That says, listen, I'm giving all this Gyan, but I don't think I'm the expert at

02:45:08.040 --> 02:45:16.520
[Guest]: this. And perhaps it's just me. But I think the one thing that, you know, in the finance world,

02:45:16.520 --> 02:45:20.520
[Guest]: the only thing that really works in the long term is that if you're humble enough to accept

02:45:20.520 --> 02:45:25.480
[Guest]: that you don't know what you don't know, or that you know that you don't know a lot of stuff.

02:45:25.480 --> 02:45:30.280
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, I mean, one of my favorite books of the last decade is Super Forecasting by Philip

02:45:30.280 --> 02:45:36.120
[Amit Varma]: Tetlock, where he kind of talks a lot about this. And what you sort of realize there is that most

02:45:36.120 --> 02:45:40.600
[Amit Varma]: people who pretend to be, most people who claim to be experts or who are known as experts, they

02:45:40.600 --> 02:45:44.680
[Amit Varma]: are known that way, because they'll be public intellectuals, they'll come on television,

02:45:44.680 --> 02:45:51.640
[Amit Varma]: they'll come wherever, and they are incentivized to exude certainty. And they will be wrong a lot

02:45:51.640 --> 02:45:55.720
[Amit Varma]: of the time. And it doesn't matter once you're, you know, classified as an expert, that's who you

02:45:55.720 --> 02:46:00.840
[Amit Varma]: are. But they're incentivized to exude certainty, and they often get a lot wrong. And what Tetlock

02:46:00.840 --> 02:46:05.560
[Amit Varma]: found is that most of the time you pit experts against the kind of forecasters he calls super

02:46:05.560 --> 02:46:10.360
[Amit Varma]: forecasters who get much more right, the experts do really badly, sometimes even worse than average,

02:46:10.360 --> 02:46:15.000
[Amit Varma]: because they're holding on to their certainties. And the classic quality of these so called super

02:46:15.000 --> 02:46:20.520
[Amit Varma]: forecasters is that humility, that they are open, and they're not hedgehogs, but foxes,

02:46:20.520 --> 02:46:26.200
[Amit Varma]: in Isaiah Berlin's, you know, terminology, where they're not wedded to one theme or one big idea,

02:46:26.200 --> 02:46:30.920
[Amit Varma]: or whatever. They are constantly updating their priors, thinking probabilistically,

02:46:30.920 --> 02:46:35.640
[Amit Varma]: all of that. You know, one thing that strikes me, and when I think about it, the reason that

02:46:35.640 --> 02:46:40.520
[Amit Varma]: I just don't think about finances, I just don't, right, I've always avoided it like a reflex

02:46:40.520 --> 02:46:45.800
[Amit Varma]: action, you know, do something else immediately, when the thought comes to mind, is that human

02:46:45.800 --> 02:46:52.280
[Amit Varma]: beings are hardwired to not understand big numbers. We evolved in small tribes, where,

02:46:52.280 --> 02:46:57.320
[Amit Varma]: you know, everything is small numbers, right? I think there's something called Dunbar's law,

02:46:57.320 --> 02:47:02.920
[Amit Varma]: which means that, which basically says that you can't remember the names of more than 150 people,

02:47:02.920 --> 02:47:06.760
[Amit Varma]: in the sense that those are the people you relate to as actual people, because that's

02:47:06.760 --> 02:47:11.880
[Amit Varma]: the kind of tribe size when we evolved. And if you go beyond that, it becomes an abstraction.

02:47:11.880 --> 02:47:18.600
[Amit Varma]: So I can, you know, if there are 10 oranges, I can comprehend those 10 oranges. But if you tell me

02:47:18.600 --> 02:47:23.960
[Amit Varma]: 1.5 billion or 1.2 trillion, I don't actually know the difference between them. I mean, of course,

02:47:23.960 --> 02:47:28.040
[Amit Varma]: I do in terms of zeros, and I've been educated, but there's no way to get my mind around it.

02:47:28.040 --> 02:47:33.480
[Amit Varma]: So this is one hardwiring that wherever big numbers come in, I, you know, we rebel against it.

02:47:33.480 --> 02:47:39.880
[Amit Varma]: And the other way is that we are also perhaps hardwired to ignore mortality, because how do

02:47:39.880 --> 02:47:44.760
[Amit Varma]: we live if we think about mortality, or if we accept the fact that life is meaningless,

02:47:44.760 --> 02:47:50.680
[Amit Varma]: and we're going to die, right? So, and we get past it in various different ways, various false

02:47:50.680 --> 02:47:56.200
[Amit Varma]: constellations, like religion, and so on. But this also means that we live with this sort of

02:47:56.200 --> 02:48:01.480
[Amit Varma]: effective illusion of immortality, where we assume that if things are going well today,

02:48:01.480 --> 02:48:07.000
[Amit Varma]: they will go well tomorrow, we don't need to plan, it's okay. And of course, we know that is wrong.

02:48:07.000 --> 02:48:11.480
[Amit Varma]: You know, like one thing that's stuck a chord with me was, at the start of your book, you write

02:48:11.480 --> 02:48:15.160
[Amit Varma]: about how when your father died, the papers were all over the place and all that. Now,

02:48:15.160 --> 02:48:20.680
[Amit Varma]: my father died last year, and he left just no account of where anything was. So we could figure

02:48:20.680 --> 02:48:26.040
[Amit Varma]: out one bank account of his, where the total money was less than a year of pension. So clearly,

02:48:26.040 --> 02:48:31.720
[Amit Varma]: that's not the only thing we can't figure out anything else, you know, and it's just a complete

02:48:31.720 --> 02:48:37.240
[Amit Varma]: mess. And in his own lifetime, obviously, I can imagine why he would not think about it. And you

02:48:37.240 --> 02:48:43.240
[Amit Varma]: believe that, you know, all of that. So question, therefore, from two angles, one is that in your

02:48:43.240 --> 02:48:50.360
[Amit Varma]: own life, how did you come to sort of take an interest in this and be able to understand big

02:48:50.360 --> 02:48:55.240
[Amit Varma]: numbers, because I don't believe that this truly comes naturally to anything you have to anyone,

02:48:55.240 --> 02:49:01.480
[Amit Varma]: you kind of have to train yourself to go against your wiring and sort of get to a way of understanding

02:49:01.480 --> 02:49:09.000
[Amit Varma]: big numbers. And the second one is this bizarre, and we also, I guess, hardwired to be delusional

02:49:09.000 --> 02:49:15.240
[Amit Varma]: in different ways, this bizarre tendency of people who do not understand the stock market in any way

02:49:15.240 --> 02:49:20.360
[Amit Varma]: whatsoever, thinking that they know the formula and putting their money, like the reason I haven't

02:49:20.360 --> 02:49:25.240
[Amit Varma]: invested so far, though I will invest with you now. But the reason I haven't invested so far

02:49:25.240 --> 02:49:31.320
[Amit Varma]: is that I realized that I don't really understand the markets in the kind of way that would justify

02:49:31.320 --> 02:49:37.080
[Amit Varma]: my putting my money on it. It doesn't make sense. And yet so many people get overconfident. And,

02:49:37.080 --> 02:49:41.080
[Amit Varma]: you know, you you have a chapter in your book called suckered, like you said,

02:49:41.080 --> 02:49:45.720
[Amit Varma]: and most people are self suckered. So two questions, one, the personal element into,

02:49:45.720 --> 02:49:51.400
[Guest]: you know, how and yeah, so let me get to this the first part first, how do I handle high?

02:49:51.400 --> 02:49:55.640
[Guest]: So actually, it's a problem, because the first time you deal with large numbers, you kind of

02:49:55.640 --> 02:50:00.760
[Guest]: think of this as Oh, my God, this number is too big or this large. And the issue with that is that

02:50:00.760 --> 02:50:06.520
[Guest]: quickly passes, because eventually, it's just a number at some level. But you see, there are some

02:50:06.520 --> 02:50:10.760
[Guest]: numbers which are hardwired in our own head, for instance, the time I used to buy a stock,

02:50:10.760 --> 02:50:15.880
[Guest]: it will always be 10,000 rupees of that stock, I would never buy more than 10,000 rupees. And now,

02:50:16.680 --> 02:50:21.640
[Guest]: that was the same 15 years ago. And if you ask me to buy something today, my instant reflex is to

02:50:21.640 --> 02:50:27.080
[Guest]: buy 10,000 rupees worth of stock. Of course, now I don't trade anymore. But this is nonsense,

02:50:27.080 --> 02:50:30.920
[Guest]: because it should always be a percentage of your network. And you have to start thinking

02:50:30.920 --> 02:50:36.760
[Guest]: of those larger numbers. And in the first place, the problem that I was having was that at some

02:50:36.760 --> 02:50:41.960
[Guest]: point, it's just mathematics, because it just applies to larger numbers. But I was trying to

02:50:41.960 --> 02:50:48.360
[Guest]: deal with the behavioral aspect of saying, if I have 25 lakh rupees in something, and if I lose

02:50:48.360 --> 02:50:54.600
[Guest]: only 2%, that's 50,000 rupees, and then I was equating that 50,000 rupees into what I could

02:50:54.600 --> 02:51:03.240
[Guest]: could buy for me. 50,000 rupees is, you know, five cell phones that nowadays come by or two,

02:51:03.880 --> 02:51:09.480
[Guest]: you know, 50 inch TVs, I don't know, it could be any of these arguments. And then you were trying

02:51:09.480 --> 02:51:14.600
[Guest]: to think of things in absolutes, which is a horrible way to think because that means if I

02:51:14.600 --> 02:51:20.440
[Guest]: did the same thing with a 5 lakh rupee portfolio, I would be comfortable losing one cell phone worth,

02:51:20.440 --> 02:51:26.120
[Guest]: but not five cell phone worths. Is that is that how I'm thinking about this? But I mean,

02:51:26.120 --> 02:51:31.000
[Guest]: at some point in time, I realized that I have to make that switch between small and big. It took

02:51:31.000 --> 02:51:36.120
[Guest]: some time. But what helped really was the study of macroeconomics. When you start studying

02:51:36.120 --> 02:51:40.680
[Guest]: macroeconomics and RBI and inflation and all that stuff, all these numbers are so big,

02:51:40.680 --> 02:51:47.400
[Guest]: you can't imagine them. Like, I mean, I can imagine, for instance, owning at some level,

02:51:47.400 --> 02:51:53.400
[Guest]: up to say 20 crore rupees. Beyond 20 crores, I don't even know what I mean, I know, of course,

02:51:53.400 --> 02:51:59.560
[Guest]: I will not refuse that kind of money if it comes to me. But beyond that, having that much more of

02:51:59.560 --> 02:52:05.480
[Guest]: personal wealth is possibly going to be just, you know, an extra, it's useful, because money is a

02:52:05.480 --> 02:52:10.520
[Guest]: motivator, it drives you and all that stuff. But I know inherently that beyond that number, it's

02:52:10.520 --> 02:52:16.440
[Guest]: not it's not going to meaningfully change my life from what it will up till that first 20 crores.

02:52:16.440 --> 02:52:22.680
[Guest]: When you get to 100, you're like, okay, now you're talking 5000 crores, suddenly, let's say,

02:52:22.680 --> 02:52:27.560
[Guest]: and I'm like, okay, I have no idea what to do with 5000. I don't even know where to begin to say

02:52:27.560 --> 02:52:33.800
[Guest]: what, as in, those numbers start sounding big. 5000 was probably the lowest number you will

02:52:33.800 --> 02:52:38.840
[Guest]: start looking at when you're looking at macroeconomics. So foreign investors told $2

02:52:38.840 --> 02:52:44.280
[Guest]: billion today or $1 billion today, that's 1 billion is 7500 crores, it's a big number,

02:52:44.280 --> 02:52:48.280
[Guest]: it's a large, larger than what you can ever, so you stop thinking absolutes, because you're saying

02:52:49.000 --> 02:52:55.960
[Guest]: $1 billion is less than their worst day, which is $5 billion, let us say. So it's not that bad a

02:52:55.960 --> 02:53:03.480
[Guest]: deal. So but it's still bad. When RBI talks about certain numbers, like money supply, it's 800,000

02:53:03.480 --> 02:53:08.760
[Guest]: crores. This is such a big number that I mean, I don't even know what to say in terms of absolutes

02:53:08.760 --> 02:53:15.240
[Guest]: when I how many cars can it buy, it will be like x number. But in terms of India's total economy,

02:53:15.240 --> 02:53:22.360
[Guest]: it is roughly 4% of all the value produced in India in the year, which technically means that

02:53:22.360 --> 02:53:27.720
[Guest]: it's not a very big number for India as a whole. So having that much money is a big number compared

02:53:27.720 --> 02:53:33.480
[Guest]: to its own past, but it's not a massive number compared to what India's entire GDP or is what

02:53:33.480 --> 02:53:39.240
[Guest]: they call this. That's where I think I got into this concept of saying numbers are just numbers

02:53:39.240 --> 02:53:44.680
[Guest]: and you know, eventually, but you have to look at numbers with certain comparisons. So what I

02:53:44.680 --> 02:53:50.520
[Guest]: call a big number for India is small for the US. India in total trades about 60,000 crores or

02:53:50.520 --> 02:53:55.880
[Guest]: 70,000 crores per day, which is about $10 billion. That is equivalent to what one stock in the US

02:53:55.880 --> 02:54:02.600
[Guest]: trades per day. So relative terms, we are tiny, even though this number of 70,000 crores is so

02:54:02.600 --> 02:54:09.640
[Guest]: large that I can't even imagine what that 70,000 crores would look like. I just know that from a

02:54:09.640 --> 02:54:14.760
[Guest]: comparative perspective, it's not a very huge number compared to the US. So there's a reason

02:54:14.760 --> 02:54:19.160
[Guest]: you have to start thinking this way is that when especially what we're doing right now is managing

02:54:19.160 --> 02:54:26.440
[Guest]: money. So we manage roughly between 650 and 700 crores. This number can scare the daylights out

02:54:26.440 --> 02:54:33.560
[Guest]: of you if you start thinking absolutes. But as you start getting relatives in place, my job is

02:54:33.560 --> 02:54:38.120
[Guest]: primarily to ensure that this money can grow over a period of time. So whether I was growing 6

02:54:38.120 --> 02:54:44.120
[Guest]: crores or 650 crores should not be any different, except my motivations to do both are slightly

02:54:44.120 --> 02:54:49.560
[Guest]: different. In 6 crores, you can buy a lot of really tiny companies. In 670, you can't because

02:54:49.560 --> 02:54:55.560
[Guest]: the tiny companies will be volatile and you won't be able to exit your portfolio position

02:54:55.560 --> 02:55:02.200
[Guest]: quite as easily and so on. So apart from that, the size number itself shouldn't scare the daylights

02:55:02.200 --> 02:55:07.400
[Guest]: out of you. Perhaps this is a function of experience. But it's also a function of exposure.

02:55:07.400 --> 02:55:12.520
[Guest]: I was just lucky enough to be exposed to these numbers within my job, though I set up the

02:55:12.520 --> 02:55:17.320
[Guest]: company and did this whole thing in terms of you know, setting up and getting you know,

02:55:17.320 --> 02:55:24.120
[Guest]: things involved. But if it scares you, you will fall victim to the fear of large numbers.

02:55:24.120 --> 02:55:28.120
[Guest]: And in your own case, so for instance, if you were to say, if I were to tell you,

02:55:28.840 --> 02:55:32.760
[Guest]: Amit, you're going to need about at least 10 crores to be able to build a lifestyle for yourself

02:55:32.760 --> 02:55:39.960
[Guest]: to retirement. That fear, 10 crores, what is Deepak talking about is, is a little bit associated by

02:55:39.960 --> 02:55:45.480
[Guest]: if you're 30 years old, to build a 10 crore rupee portfolio will just take 20 years of investing

02:55:45.480 --> 02:55:50.520
[Guest]: maybe 25,000 rupees a month. And then you're like, why didn't you say that? Because I'm thinking 10

02:55:50.520 --> 02:55:56.680
[Guest]: crores is impossible, but 25,000 rupees a month is possible. It's just the way you frame the

02:55:56.680 --> 02:56:01.640
[Guest]: argument, you know. So instead of telling a person that all your relatives will die before you,

02:56:01.640 --> 02:56:06.680
[Guest]: you tell him that he will outlive all his relatives. It's just a different way to state

02:56:06.680 --> 02:56:12.200
[Guest]: the same thing, just more acceptable. So the law of large numbers is just that make it sound not

02:56:12.200 --> 02:56:18.040
[Amit Varma]: as large as it was. That's a remarkable analogy, all your relatives will die before you. And

02:56:18.040 --> 02:56:23.080
[Amit Varma]: that no, and I completely get where you're coming from. Because in poker also, you know,

02:56:23.080 --> 02:56:28.760
[Amit Varma]: any good player, you could be playing low stakes, like 50 100, where you're sitting with maybe 20k

02:56:28.760 --> 02:56:32.440
[Amit Varma]: on the table, or you could be playing 500,000, where you're sitting with two lakhs on the table.

02:56:32.440 --> 02:56:36.040
[Amit Varma]: But the point is, once you're sitting there, you're just thinking of the odds, you're thinking

02:56:36.040 --> 02:56:39.800
[Amit Varma]: of big blinds, you're thinking of the odds in a particular hand, you're thinking of equities,

02:56:39.800 --> 02:56:44.760
[Amit Varma]: you're not thinking of them as absolute numbers, because that makes absolutely no sense.

02:56:44.760 --> 02:56:49.800
[Amit Varma]: But one area where I wish that where I think more poker players should think of absolute numbers is,

02:56:49.800 --> 02:56:54.920
[Amit Varma]: you know, we'd have these long sessions play 1516 hours, and, you know, winnings would go up to,

02:56:54.920 --> 02:57:00.520
[Amit Varma]: you know, a couple of lakhs up or down in a session. And sometimes we'd have to go for

02:57:00.520 --> 02:57:05.000
[Amit Varma]: breakfast and we'd all just droop to the Marriott. And the logic was, and it became very regular

02:57:05.000 --> 02:57:09.560
[Amit Varma]: after a point. And the logic was that what is breakfast at the Marriott? It's like a couple

02:57:09.560 --> 02:57:14.600
[Amit Varma]: of big blinds. It's like you posted a straddle and somebody raised and you folded, you know,

02:57:14.600 --> 02:57:18.600
[Amit Varma]: so when you look at it from that perspective, everything seemed trivial. And one mistake I see

02:57:18.600 --> 02:57:24.360
[Amit Varma]: many poker players still making, I mean, I retired in 2015. But one mistake I see many people making

02:57:24.360 --> 02:57:29.880
[Amit Varma]: is living that kind of lifestyle where you are not giving the taking the absolute seriously enough,

02:57:29.880 --> 02:57:36.680
[Amit Varma]: right? And you're taking that poker mindset to everything else, which doesn't always work.

02:57:36.680 --> 02:57:43.160
[Amit Varma]: And this one similarity, in fact, between writing well and investing well, and I want to make it

02:57:43.160 --> 02:57:49.160
[Amit Varma]: here. Like when I speak to my writing students, you know, and I'll tell them about like, one of

02:57:49.160 --> 02:57:54.120
[Amit Varma]: the points that I drive home is that what is a piece of writing? A piece of writing is a series

02:57:54.120 --> 02:57:59.560
[Amit Varma]: of choices that you have made. You know, how long are your sentences? What words are you using?

02:57:59.560 --> 02:58:03.320
[Amit Varma]: Where are the parabrakes? What is the rhythm? Every piece of writing is a series of choices

02:58:03.320 --> 02:58:08.520
[Amit Varma]: you have made. Those choices individually and together affect the reader in a certain way,

02:58:08.520 --> 02:58:12.120
[Amit Varma]: and you want to affect the reader. Now the point is, you could say that I don't care,

02:58:12.120 --> 02:58:15.400
[Amit Varma]: I'll just let it flow. I won't be too mindful, I don't want to work too hard.

02:58:15.400 --> 02:58:19.800
[Amit Varma]: But that doesn't change the fact that those choices are there. You know, just as when I

02:58:19.800 --> 02:58:24.200
[Amit Varma]: talk about making sure that a piece sounds well, that there is there is a coherent rhythm to it,

02:58:24.200 --> 02:58:28.520
[Amit Varma]: you could choose to ignore that and say, I don't want to think about that. But then the point is,

02:58:28.520 --> 02:58:33.000
[Amit Varma]: there is still a rhythm that is there by default, except it's a random one that you haven't put.

02:58:33.560 --> 02:58:39.640
[Amit Varma]: Similarly, you might be a person who says that I don't invest. But the point is that if you have

02:58:39.640 --> 02:58:43.640
[Amit Varma]: money, you have already invested. If it is in your savings account, you've invested in that,

02:58:44.360 --> 02:58:48.360
[Amit Varma]: right? And you feel like you've done nothing and the money is coming to your bank.

02:58:48.360 --> 02:58:53.560
[Amit Varma]: But the point is, it is a choice that you have made by default. In a sense,

02:58:53.560 --> 02:58:57.640
[Amit Varma]: not doing something is doing something and doing something bad in this case. And therefore,

02:58:57.640 --> 02:59:03.720
[Amit Varma]: just as a writer owes it to herself to write the most effective piece she can without compromising

02:59:03.720 --> 02:59:11.080
[Amit Varma]: on her content. Similarly, all of us with money owe it to ourselves to sort of try and figure out

02:59:11.080 --> 02:59:16.280
[Amit Varma]: the basics of investing because it is after all our money. You know, if you're just putting it

02:59:16.280 --> 02:59:20.120
[Amit Varma]: in a savings account, or you're not investing it optimally, what are you doing? You're burning your

02:59:20.120 --> 02:59:25.320
[Amit Varma]: money. That's effectively what you're doing. You're just completely burning it. Is this a

02:59:25.320 --> 02:59:30.360
[Amit Varma]: difficult point to get across to people? Because I know, like on the one hand, there is that thing

02:59:30.360 --> 02:59:34.840
[Amit Varma]: of don't invest if you don't know the markets well enough, because people get suckered by

02:59:34.840 --> 02:59:41.320
[Amit Varma]: themselves. On the other hand, there is also this drive that my money is basically bleeding away,

02:59:41.320 --> 02:59:46.120
[Amit Varma]: I need to do something about it. And then that comes with the added question of where is my

02:59:46.120 --> 02:59:51.080
[Amit Varma]: bandwidth? I'm earning a living doing whatever I'm doing. Where is my additional bandwidth to

02:59:51.080 --> 02:59:56.440
[Amit Varma]: then think about this? So you know, when you have conversations with people and indeed during your

02:59:56.440 --> 03:00:01.400
[Amit Varma]: own journey, maybe speaking to your own family, your own sort of beginnings as an investor,

03:00:01.400 --> 03:00:05.640
[Guest]: you know, just take me through your thoughts. Oh, yeah, this is so this, this has so many facets

03:00:05.640 --> 03:00:10.760
[Guest]: to it. I'll give you one thing that I told someone who was doing running a startup in this space

03:00:10.760 --> 03:00:17.160
[Guest]: about 10 years ago. They were running a startup around investing in mutual funds. And my statement

03:00:17.160 --> 03:00:25.000
[Guest]: to them was when you get a 10 to 20% increment every year from your job, and that is a time when

03:00:25.000 --> 03:00:30.680
[Guest]: there was 9% inflation, so 10 to 20% was a given. When you have that much coming in from your job

03:00:30.680 --> 03:00:37.720
[Guest]: itself, why does investing matter to this person? Because if I am making 10% more by just working

03:00:37.720 --> 03:00:43.800
[Guest]: harder at my job or not even working, just having a pulse, then should investing matter at all

03:00:43.800 --> 03:00:50.680
[Guest]: because making the market will give you 10 to 12% or 15% a year, they will not excite you at the

03:00:50.680 --> 03:00:55.480
[Guest]: absolute number will not excite you unless your corpus is really big. You're starting out investing

03:00:55.480 --> 03:01:00.840
[Guest]: your chances are you look at a 50,000 number that's been invested as okay, give me 10%. What's

03:01:00.840 --> 03:01:07.160
[Guest]: the number? It's 55,000 rupees, it's just 5000 rupees more. And instead, I have now earned maybe

03:01:07.160 --> 03:01:14.040
[Guest]: 20,000 rupees more a month from my primary job, those absolute numbers, you know, that's where

03:01:14.040 --> 03:01:20.200
[Guest]: the problem comes. And a lot of people don't invest because they don't see this, they think

03:01:20.200 --> 03:01:26.360
[Guest]: of it as a useless waste of time. And the aspect that you have to worry about here is that investing

03:01:26.360 --> 03:01:34.840
[Guest]: is purely behavior. That means a lot of money is made on behavior, and less is made on the skill

03:01:34.840 --> 03:01:39.960
[Guest]: of identifying great investments, which means like you said, it's our job to find the greatest

03:01:39.960 --> 03:01:46.360
[Guest]: investment or the find a way to, but I think our job is actually not to find the best investment,

03:01:46.360 --> 03:01:54.280
[Guest]: our job is primarily to find a way that ensures that the stuff that I should plan for is being

03:01:54.280 --> 03:01:58.440
[Guest]: planned for. So when I say that, I mean, for instance, I tell everybody you need a six month

03:01:58.440 --> 03:02:04.040
[Guest]: emergency fund, you need a life insurance if you have dependents. So to give you an example,

03:02:04.040 --> 03:02:09.480
[Guest]: if you don't have any dependents, nobody depends on you for income, you don't need life insurance.

03:02:09.480 --> 03:02:13.160
[Guest]: Anytime you have any amount of money you're paying for life insurance is a waste of money.

03:02:13.160 --> 03:02:18.120
[Guest]: But if you do have dependents, at least have insurance for the time that they're dependent

03:02:18.120 --> 03:02:24.360
[Guest]: on you. So if my children are, let's say, my youngest is 10 years old. So I probably need

03:02:24.360 --> 03:02:31.000
[Guest]: another eight to 10 years of insurance to ensure that if something happens to me today, that he can

03:02:31.000 --> 03:02:36.360
[Guest]: be taken care of. So there is that that one has to kind of, you know, so you say that a spouse has

03:02:36.360 --> 03:02:42.600
[Guest]: to be taken care of, or anybody else that has is dependent on you. That is when you need life

03:02:42.600 --> 03:02:47.160
[Guest]: insurance. But when you do need it, take care of it first. So you do the hygiene part, six months

03:02:47.160 --> 03:02:52.520
[Guest]: of an emergency buffer, life insurance, health insurance, that we owe it to ourselves. The next

03:02:52.520 --> 03:02:57.080
[Guest]: thing you do to ourselves, there'll be a some point in our life, and maybe the creator economy

03:02:57.080 --> 03:03:01.080
[Guest]: ensures there will never be that point in our lives, where we will stop working and stop making

03:03:01.080 --> 03:03:06.040
[Guest]: money. This point of stop working and stop making money may be voluntary, saying I don't want to

03:03:06.040 --> 03:03:11.160
[Guest]: work anymore for money, I'm going to do charity based work. My savings should take care of my

03:03:11.160 --> 03:03:15.400
[Guest]: expenses. This is called retirement. And whether it happens when you're 60, or it happens when you're

03:03:15.400 --> 03:03:21.960
[Guest]: 35 is left to how much corpus you have, how much you spend per month. To understand how much money

03:03:21.960 --> 03:03:28.360
[Guest]: you're going to need is our job. So we're going to need to know that in order to if people got

03:03:28.360 --> 03:03:33.960
[Guest]: this in place, then whether they put their money into an FD, or whether they put it into the most

03:03:33.960 --> 03:03:39.720
[Guest]: complicated, complicated, you know, complex product, structured product that invest half

03:03:39.720 --> 03:03:45.400
[Guest]: in India, half in the US, it is not relevant, because you know exactly where you need to be,

03:03:45.400 --> 03:03:50.040
[Guest]: and you've chosen a path to get there. You could tell me, Deepak, listen, I don't get the stock

03:03:50.040 --> 03:03:57.400
[Guest]: market business. Okay, my FDs give me 5% a year. After tax, I make 3.5%. How much time is it going

03:03:57.400 --> 03:04:01.720
[Guest]: to how much money do I am I going to need to put per month to get to my investing goal, which is

03:04:01.720 --> 03:04:07.320
[Guest]: let's say 15 years from now, which is a retirement corpus of X crores. And in I can tell you this,

03:04:07.320 --> 03:04:11.960
[Guest]: that I might tell you like, take the risky road, and you can put 75,000 rupees a month,

03:04:12.680 --> 03:04:17.400
[Guest]: take the non risky road, and you can put 125,000 rupees a month, both of which will get you there.

03:04:18.280 --> 03:04:22.520
[Guest]: You can look at me and say, Deepak, I don't want the risky road, I'll find a way to make that extra

03:04:22.520 --> 03:04:28.360
[Guest]: 50,000 rupees a month to be able to pay for the non risky road. Fine, it's great. It doesn't need

03:04:28.360 --> 03:04:34.280
[Guest]: to be optimal. It doesn't need to be that you get the most maximum optimal return possible.

03:04:34.280 --> 03:04:39.720
[Guest]: More important is the fact that you're comfortable with whatever risk and elements again, remember

03:04:39.720 --> 03:04:45.960
[Guest]: in the market, no, this is the problem is that when the when you make 10 rupees, if I told you

03:04:45.960 --> 03:04:53.480
[Guest]: that, you know, you are as happy as having eaten one lollipop, the losing of 10 rupees is the

03:04:53.480 --> 03:05:00.200
[Guest]: feeling of having lost to a drop to lollipops before you could eat them. So the amount you

03:05:00.200 --> 03:05:05.560
[Guest]: unhappiness of you face when you lose money is far more than the amount of because inherently,

03:05:05.560 --> 03:05:10.680
[Guest]: when markets go up, we think it's our right, that, you know, we're entitled to this

03:05:12.600 --> 03:05:18.760
[Guest]: 5%, 10%. We normalize it. Yes, it's like, you know what, I'm smart, I did, you know,

03:05:18.760 --> 03:05:23.160
[Guest]: engineering in X college, and therefore, I deserve this money. But when it goes down,

03:05:23.160 --> 03:05:27.960
[Guest]: we're like, oh, shit, I deserve more, but I got far lesser. So I'm actually going to be

03:05:27.960 --> 03:05:34.520
[Guest]: more miserable than I am and it went up. So this misery causes is a is a cause of concern,

03:05:34.520 --> 03:05:42.120
[Guest]: because every piece of misery you add to your life is just one more heart attack waiting to happen

03:05:42.120 --> 03:05:51.560
[Guest]: 25-30 years down the line. So you want to optimize for lack of misery, not for maximum returns.

03:05:51.560 --> 03:05:57.960
[Guest]: This is an aspect that not many people understand in the beginning. And some people will never

03:05:57.960 --> 03:06:00.840
[Guest]: understand. So they will, for instance, they will go into the stock market and say we want the

03:06:00.840 --> 03:06:04.840
[Guest]: maximum return, they will lose money, they will get out and say I will never invest in stocks

03:06:04.840 --> 03:06:09.000
[Guest]: again, and then buy real estate. And it doesn't matter that the real estate gives them less

03:06:09.000 --> 03:06:13.480
[Guest]: returns than a fixed deposit. They will just say I can't deal with the stock market was never my

03:06:13.480 --> 03:06:18.040
[Guest]: thing. And I'm happier doing whatever I'm doing. Rather than going down the route of saying,

03:06:18.040 --> 03:06:23.320
[Guest]: listen, I, I just was miserable taking this kind of risk in the market. I'm just going to put

03:06:23.320 --> 03:06:28.280
[Guest]: lesser money into the stock market, more money into something that is fixed income. And therefore

03:06:28.280 --> 03:06:33.800
[Guest]: my combined misery on the both, if I look at them together, is a lot more easy for me to handle.

03:06:34.840 --> 03:06:39.160
[Guest]: And I wish I could answer that other and also the other part of the first question that you asked,

03:06:39.160 --> 03:06:44.840
[Guest]: which is why do so many people feel that they can make out like bandits in the stock market?

03:06:44.840 --> 03:06:49.480
[Guest]: I think it's the same reason why everybody feels they can win against a casino. And though the

03:06:49.480 --> 03:06:54.920
[Guest]: stock market is not a casino, it's not a zero sum game. And I think I've mentioned this on your on

03:06:54.920 --> 03:06:59.480
[Guest]: our earlier podcast, but I'll repeat that. So the reason the stock market is not a zero sum game is

03:06:59.480 --> 03:07:05.400
[Guest]: if there's a stock stock that makes 10 rupees of profits, and you buy it at 100, you're paying 10

03:07:05.400 --> 03:07:12.040
[Guest]: times earnings, you sell it to me at 150, you've made some money, the company has now made 15

03:07:12.040 --> 03:07:18.040
[Guest]: rupees of profits. I'm also paying 10 times earnings, you also paid 10 times earnings when

03:07:18.040 --> 03:07:24.360
[Guest]: you started now you've made 150, your 100 has become 150, you've made 50 rupees, I have bought

03:07:24.360 --> 03:07:31.080
[Guest]: it at 150, it grows its earnings to 200, I sell it to somebody else at 200, who has lost? Nobody

03:07:31.080 --> 03:07:37.160
[Guest]: has. The stock market is not a zero sum game. Therefore, it's better than gambling or better

03:07:37.160 --> 03:07:42.280
[Guest]: than casino, which is another feeling why people feel that they can go in and say, listen, if I

03:07:42.280 --> 03:07:49.000
[Guest]: bought the right companies, I would make money. Now add this to the casino ish concept of the

03:07:49.000 --> 03:07:54.600
[Guest]: markets trades every day, you get a price every day, you get a report card every day, when you

03:07:54.600 --> 03:07:59.640
[Guest]: get a report card every day, some days you won and some days you lost. The guys who win every day

03:07:59.640 --> 03:08:07.640
[Guest]: show off on Twitter, saying I won, the guys who lose, talk about politics and other stuff. So,

03:08:08.280 --> 03:08:15.000
[Guest]: you get a bunch of different sorts of people, but you're getting the information of people winning,

03:08:15.560 --> 03:08:20.040
[Guest]: which is exactly the way the casinos highlight, they want to highlight the winners all the time

03:08:20.040 --> 03:08:26.520
[Guest]: and the losers are like, huh, the same, the same behavior that triggers those dopamine effects,

03:08:26.520 --> 03:08:32.760
[Guest]: affects a person who is walking into the market for the first time. So, they feel that they can,

03:08:32.760 --> 03:08:39.160
[Guest]: and in all honesty, anybody can become rich in the stock market. It's like that ratatouille

03:08:39.160 --> 03:08:45.880
[Guest]: statement of anyone can cook. It does not take a special kind of skill that can be learned,

03:08:46.600 --> 03:08:52.680
[Guest]: or a special kind of inheritance that can be genetically modified in order to make great

03:08:52.680 --> 03:08:57.080
[Guest]: money from the stock market. A lot of the stock market is just behavior. It's about greed and

03:08:57.080 --> 03:09:03.720
[Guest]: fear. It's about panic and sustenance. And it's more important about the analogy of writing that

03:09:03.720 --> 03:09:10.840
[Guest]: you just said. The statement that you made in the beginning was that you have to build, instill in

03:09:10.840 --> 03:09:18.760
[Guest]: yourself a sense of rigor and discipline. 90% of the returns you'll make will come from that rigor

03:09:18.760 --> 03:09:24.840
[Guest]: and discipline. It's only 10% will come from your brilliance in discovering which new stock was fancy.

03:09:25.480 --> 03:09:30.920
[Guest]: I'll give you an example of why. You say you bought a stock at 100 rupees and it went to 200.

03:09:31.880 --> 03:09:37.560
[Guest]: And you said, dude, that's a 100% return. I'm going to take it out. In all your life,

03:09:37.560 --> 03:09:44.120
[Guest]: you're going to invest in maybe 1000 or 2000 stocks. Only about 10 or 20 will give you phenomenal

03:09:44.120 --> 03:09:49.960
[Guest]: returns. I'm talking really phenomenal, like 100x returns. If you get out of those stocks,

03:09:49.960 --> 03:09:56.520
[Guest]: when they give you a 1x or a 2x return, you're effectively losing the possibility that they can

03:09:56.520 --> 03:10:03.160
[Guest]: give you a 100x or 200x return. And over time, those losers which you were anyway going to invest

03:10:03.160 --> 03:10:07.560
[Guest]: in and lose money in, they're going to keep losing you money, but you've stopped yourself

03:10:07.560 --> 03:10:12.920
[Guest]: from winning the big wins. The whole concept was behavioral because you thought I'll take

03:10:12.920 --> 03:10:17.960
[Guest]: the profits when they're there. That behavior is what made you lose this money. In fact,

03:10:17.960 --> 03:10:22.440
[Guest]: this is where it slightly differs from poker because in poker, there's literally an upper

03:10:22.440 --> 03:10:27.400
[Guest]: limit to what you can win in a pot. There's an upper limit for the pot. There isn't such an

03:10:27.400 --> 03:10:32.600
[Guest]: upper limit for the for the stock market. In a sense, you can stay invested for a really long

03:10:32.600 --> 03:10:39.160
[Guest]: time without having to make a decision to get out. So this is where that discipline and rigor

03:10:39.160 --> 03:10:43.640
[Guest]: comes into play. And I think the same discipline and rigor comes in poker, because you need to know

03:10:43.640 --> 03:10:50.520
[Guest]: when you're out. You can't keep buying pots and losing and saying that dude, my next pot will be

03:10:50.520 --> 03:10:56.200
[Guest]: the victory. That's a sure shot way of like, losing everything you have is the same way in

03:10:56.200 --> 03:11:01.880
[Guest]: stock markets is where you have to know when to stop, you know, your losses. And you have to know

03:11:01.880 --> 03:11:07.720
[Guest]: when to keep staying with your gains. And most of the time, this is a fight with your own behavior.

03:11:07.720 --> 03:11:13.080
[Guest]: That's why the stock market investors that make the most amount of money are usually dead.

03:11:14.760 --> 03:11:20.920
[Guest]: Because they didn't act on the various panics and manias that happened in the middle.

03:11:20.920 --> 03:11:26.280
[Guest]: And suddenly their kin discovered that, oh, you know what my father and somebody came on TV and

03:11:26.280 --> 03:11:33.720
[Guest]: said this, my father bought a bunch of MRF shares. I think I have like 200 of them. What can I do

03:11:33.720 --> 03:11:40.600
[Guest]: with them? Now MRF at the time his father bought it was about maybe 500 rupees per share. So 200

03:11:40.600 --> 03:11:47.000
[Guest]: rupees adds up to a lakh. So this guy is thinking maybe it's worth two lakhs now. MRF was at 68,000

03:11:47.000 --> 03:11:52.040
[Guest]: rupees per share when he made the statement. So he was actually worth nearly one and a half crores.

03:11:52.600 --> 03:11:57.080
[Guest]: So he had no idea he could have made that much. And I'm telling you, if he knew he had that many

03:11:57.080 --> 03:12:01.880
[Guest]: shares, he would have sold it the minute that one lakh had become two lakhs. It was the sleeping

03:12:01.880 --> 03:12:06.680
[Guest]: that earned him the money, but he did it involuntarily. Very few of us are able to do it

03:12:06.680 --> 03:12:11.480
[Guest]: voluntarily. I hope I'm one of them, though I have proved myself wrong many times that I'm

03:12:11.480 --> 03:12:17.800
[Guest]: not one of them in many ways. But I would say this, because anyone can make money in the stock

03:12:17.800 --> 03:12:25.640
[Guest]: markets, everyone wants to get in on the pie when the markets are going up. And of these people who

03:12:25.640 --> 03:12:33.800
[Guest]: get in, 80% of them lose their cool when the markets correct very naturally in a correction

03:12:33.800 --> 03:12:38.040
[Guest]: that is brought about by factors way beyond their control, like Putin is having a bad day because

03:12:38.040 --> 03:12:42.920
[Guest]: he woke up on the wrong side of the bed. And therefore, you've lost 10% of your money just

03:12:42.920 --> 03:12:47.720
[Guest]: in one day. This is not acceptable to a lot of people and they walk away saying this is just a

03:12:47.720 --> 03:12:54.760
[Guest]: scam. But it isn't. It involves discipline. How do you kind of tell them that? So therefore,

03:12:54.760 --> 03:13:01.400
[Guest]: there will always be a bunch of new, well, I shouldn't call them bakras, but unfortunately,

03:13:02.520 --> 03:13:09.640
[Guest]: that's the only term that kind of fits that come in. Some people stay and become sage old wolves,

03:13:09.640 --> 03:13:18.920
[Guest]: if you may. The other just go and find less useful pastures to venture into than compared

03:13:18.920 --> 03:13:21.960
[Guest]: to the stock market. That's all. That's how unfortunately the market is.

03:13:21.960 --> 03:13:28.360
[Amit Varma]: Yeah. And there's a term for this in poker also, where, you know, typically what you should do

03:13:28.360 --> 03:13:34.280
[Amit Varma]: is that if you're losing, cut your losses at some point. And if you're winning, you know,

03:13:34.280 --> 03:13:38.840
[Amit Varma]: if you feel you have an edge in the game, go with it, don't cash out. And the phrase is that people

03:13:38.840 --> 03:13:44.440
[Amit Varma]: who for example, you know, somebody sat down with 50k, he takes it to 80k and he gets up.

03:13:44.440 --> 03:13:49.400
[Amit Varma]: But if he loses a 50, he'll put in another 50, another 50, another 50, lose maybe 3 lakhs at

03:13:49.400 --> 03:13:53.960
[Amit Varma]: the end of the day. And the phrase is eats like a bird and shits like an elephant. Right? So if you

03:13:53.960 --> 03:13:58.600
[Amit Varma]: keep eating like a bird and shitting like an elephant, it's not good for you. And that point

03:13:58.600 --> 03:14:02.440
[Amit Varma]: about loss aversion is also interesting. And I've seen that in poker also where, you know, losing a

03:14:02.440 --> 03:14:07.080
[Amit Varma]: lakh on a given day will hurt way more than winning a couple. Though the interesting thing is that a

03:14:07.080 --> 03:14:12.840
[Amit Varma]: lot of experiments in behavioral psychology are now they found are not replicable. So a lot of

03:14:12.840 --> 03:14:17.400
[Amit Varma]: these concepts are actually suspect, I think loss aversion is one of them. But it seems to make

03:14:17.400 --> 03:14:23.400
[Amit Varma]: intuitive sense to us, at least it certainly goes with, you know, your typical Indian conservative

03:14:23.400 --> 03:14:28.360
[Amit Varma]: sort of approach to things. Let's kind of, you know, in your starting chapter, where you talk

03:14:28.360 --> 03:14:34.360
[Amit Varma]: about start in the beginning, what you share a number of lessons. And I want to go through these

03:14:34.360 --> 03:14:40.200
[Amit Varma]: lessons, because I think that they are foundational to you know, how one approaches money. And you've

03:14:40.200 --> 03:14:45.080
[Amit Varma]: already actually, in a sense, mentioned a couple of them. But the first one is something deeply

03:14:45.080 --> 03:14:51.240
[Amit Varma]: unintuitive, where you say let the money compound, right? And our minds don't really, you know,

03:14:51.240 --> 03:14:55.560
[Amit Varma]: understand compound interest, you have to force yourself to understand what the hell it is,

03:14:55.560 --> 03:14:59.800
[Amit Varma]: do the numbers again and again, and then you begin to figure out. And the interesting thing is you

03:14:59.800 --> 03:15:04.440
[Amit Varma]: spoke about when your dad passed away 25 years ago, all his papers were in a mess, and there

03:15:04.440 --> 03:15:08.920
[Amit Varma]: was really nothing and his investments were crap, and everything went to hell. But there was one

03:15:08.920 --> 03:15:14.520
[Amit Varma]: aspect of it, which turned out to be incredibly profitable. And that was because of the compounding

03:15:14.520 --> 03:15:21.320
[Amit Varma]: effect over the years. So tell me a little bit about sort of this lesson and you know, how you'd

03:15:21.320 --> 03:15:25.400
[Guest]: like to speak about compound interest. Oh, this is actually I mean, it was fascinating to me

03:15:25.400 --> 03:15:32.200
[Guest]: because I was doing the numbers. So when my father passed away, there was a bunch of stocks that he

03:15:32.200 --> 03:15:38.200
[Guest]: had invested in that he had kept as a pledge to the bank for a loan that he had to take to top up

03:15:38.200 --> 03:15:44.040
[Guest]: the housing loan that he had taken, because the house wasn't delivered on time. So there was a

03:15:44.040 --> 03:15:49.240
[Guest]: bunch of stocks which he hadn't touched because so now the stocks have already gone up like 4x

03:15:49.240 --> 03:15:54.280
[Guest]: from when he had bought them. And I was surprised because the other stocks my dad would have bought

03:15:54.280 --> 03:15:58.920
[Guest]: and sold on a regular basis. So he might not have kept these shares that long. But these ones he

03:15:58.920 --> 03:16:04.040
[Guest]: just kept and it was kept pledged. It helped him because he couldn't sell those shares because

03:16:04.040 --> 03:16:10.360
[Guest]: they were pledged. So the bank effectively had the shares. And so he couldn't sell them. So some of

03:16:10.360 --> 03:16:15.160
[Guest]: these stocks were, for instance, he had applied in the IPO of some of these companies in 1985 and

03:16:15.160 --> 03:16:21.560
[Guest]: 1986. So by the time he passed away, they had already gone up four or five times. When we got

03:16:21.560 --> 03:16:27.800
[Guest]: it, the smartest thing that happened to us was that we were dumb enough to not know how to sell

03:16:27.800 --> 03:16:35.240
[Guest]: these shares. That we didn't even try to discover it. And my mother had, because of this, her

03:16:35.240 --> 03:16:39.880
[Guest]: feeling was inaction is better than action, let's just keep them. This is not much in terms of

03:16:39.880 --> 03:16:45.400
[Guest]: stocks, but there were 40 or 50 different companies, a bunch of physical shares, because they were all

03:16:45.400 --> 03:16:51.880
[Guest]: paper shares that came in. Only seven or eight survived, to be honest. The rest of the companies

03:16:51.880 --> 03:16:58.200
[Guest]: are zero, the rest of them for the most part. To this date, my mother cannot get over that,

03:16:58.200 --> 03:17:03.640
[Guest]: in the sense that she feels that how can we let go of 33 companies going bankrupt?

03:17:04.520 --> 03:17:08.520
[Guest]: You know, how could my father have not seen that these guys were in a sense,

03:17:08.520 --> 03:17:12.840
[Guest]: he didn't know what it was like. He invested in all these companies, he had no idea what this was,

03:17:12.840 --> 03:17:17.960
[Guest]: he just bought them. I'm like, mom, the seven companies or eight companies that survived

03:17:17.960 --> 03:17:26.200
[Guest]: have actually gone up 40x. And not 40x of what they were, 40x of what all the 40 companies were

03:17:26.200 --> 03:17:31.480
[Amit Varma]: worth. So the entire portfolio went up 40x because of this small percentage of companies.

03:17:31.480 --> 03:17:35.560
[Guest]: Which gives you the Pareto principle right there. For me, it was like,

03:17:35.560 --> 03:17:40.920
[Guest]: this is not Pareto principle, this is my dad principle. It's like, you know, for me,

03:17:41.560 --> 03:17:45.640
[Guest]: it was not more visible, the concept of compounding, but not just the concept of

03:17:45.640 --> 03:17:51.720
[Guest]: compounding. Now what is 40x? 40x sounds like a huge number, right? So if something doubles,

03:17:52.280 --> 03:17:59.240
[Guest]: and then doubles again, that's 4x. And then if it does that two more times, it's 16x.

03:18:00.280 --> 03:18:04.680
[Guest]: And if it does that one more time, it's 32x. So you're essentially doubling your money

03:18:04.680 --> 03:18:09.640
[Guest]: in so many times. Now let's say, for whatever reason, you're able to double your money every

03:18:09.640 --> 03:18:17.640
[Guest]: five years. Every five years, your money doubles. So in 25 years, you get 32x your money,

03:18:18.920 --> 03:18:23.960
[Guest]: if you're able to double your money every five years. Now this sounds like, come on, Deepak,

03:18:23.960 --> 03:18:29.720
[Guest]: doubling your money every five years is a ridiculously difficult thing to do. Agreed.

03:18:29.720 --> 03:18:37.480
[Guest]: But was it difficult at the time that I came through? India was running at about 7 to 8%

03:18:37.480 --> 03:18:44.680
[Guest]: inflation for the longest part. We were having 6 to 7% economic growth. So we're getting 15%

03:18:44.680 --> 03:18:50.680
[Guest]: growth, inflation plus real growth is your nominal growth. 15% growth in the economy was

03:18:50.680 --> 03:18:56.520
[Guest]: happening on a year-on-year basis almost every year, consistently over a period of time. So what

03:18:56.520 --> 03:19:01.960
[Guest]: I was getting was 15% a year. If you get 14 to 15% a year, your money doubles every five years.

03:19:03.800 --> 03:19:12.040
[Guest]: In fact, the number is about 14%, closer to 14%. So if you got the returns of the economy itself,

03:19:12.600 --> 03:19:18.040
[Guest]: you are able to double your money every five years, which means you would get 32x returns

03:19:18.040 --> 03:19:22.920
[Guest]: if you just had a pulse and stayed alive. You know, and as long as you didn't do something

03:19:22.920 --> 03:19:29.480
[Guest]: really stupid. So this 40x does not sound so incredibly huge in comparison, now that I put

03:19:29.480 --> 03:19:34.360
[Guest]: it in context. There's something more to it as well. So the important thing was to not sell

03:19:34.360 --> 03:19:39.320
[Guest]: and to not take it out and put it into a fixed deposit. And we did do that after a while because

03:19:40.200 --> 03:19:45.720
[Guest]: there was too much equity in comparison with everything else. But despite that, the portfolio

03:19:45.720 --> 03:19:54.680
[Guest]: went up quite considerably. Now the issue really was that we didn't give in to those behavioral

03:19:54.680 --> 03:20:00.920
[Guest]: emotions that resulted in this. The compounding could be achieved. That means you could allow

03:20:00.920 --> 03:20:06.600
[Guest]: something that becomes 2x to become 4x, 4x to become 8x. Sometimes it's not visible why this

03:20:06.600 --> 03:20:11.560
[Guest]: happens. So for instance, you might always look at me and say, Deepak, you bought this stock at

03:20:11.560 --> 03:20:17.080
[Guest]: 300 rupees. It's at 3000 now. If I buy it now, I've lost everything. I mean, all the gains have

03:20:17.080 --> 03:20:23.480
[Guest]: gone. But what are the chances that the 3000 becomes 30,000? It can become 30,000. And of

03:20:23.480 --> 03:20:28.520
[Guest]: course, it may not be 30,000, the stock may split and then but you may actually get 10x your returns

03:20:28.520 --> 03:20:34.760
[Guest]: even in a stock that has gone up a lot. And that is why our behavioral challenges for compounding

03:20:35.400 --> 03:20:40.760
[Guest]: come in. Compounding is very difficult to fathom because of this, you know, how many years it takes

03:20:40.760 --> 03:20:45.240
[Guest]: to double. Let me tell you going forward, the last past was the past. Now you can say that India is

03:20:45.240 --> 03:20:51.240
[Guest]: going to grow at 6% a year, we may have 5% inflation because so the economy gives us only 11%.

03:20:52.200 --> 03:20:56.280
[Guest]: So if you got 11% returns on your investments, what would the same thing look like? Now,

03:20:56.280 --> 03:21:02.040
[Guest]: if you're 35 years old, you have another 25 years left for retirement. If you get 11% a year,

03:21:02.040 --> 03:21:07.640
[Guest]: your money will double every six and a half years, let's say six years. So in a 25 year period,

03:21:07.640 --> 03:21:14.280
[Guest]: your money will grow go up 16 times at a, if you get just the same returns of the economy. Now,

03:21:14.280 --> 03:21:18.280
[Guest]: this is not the same thing as putting in a fixed deposit. But if you put it in a stock market,

03:21:18.280 --> 03:21:25.880
[Guest]: over a period of 25 years, you should get roughly that much. So getting a 16x return in a 25 year

03:21:25.880 --> 03:21:32.680
[Guest]: period is not should not be a big deal. But we don't get it. That means it literally says that

03:21:32.680 --> 03:21:38.200
[Guest]: a small amount of money invested every month can actually result in crores of a portfolio,

03:21:38.200 --> 03:21:45.000
[Guest]: simply because it stays invested that long. On the other side, it is the aspect of saying,

03:21:45.000 --> 03:21:50.040
[Guest]: if you micromanage your investments too much, you might end up taking those behavioral,

03:21:50.040 --> 03:21:54.680
[Guest]: doing those really behavioral bad things, which means you'll end up. So I would say,

03:21:55.240 --> 03:22:01.640
[Guest]: in a poker parlance, it's like, if you're having a great streak going, going on the way up,

03:22:01.640 --> 03:22:05.960
[Guest]: would you just walk away from it? It may be because you're playing with some really bad players.

03:22:07.080 --> 03:22:12.360
[Guest]: And you know more than them. It may be because you're just lucky and you're getting your hands

03:22:12.360 --> 03:22:18.680
[Guest]: in. But if you don't stick around at those times, you're probably going to only like you said,

03:22:18.680 --> 03:22:25.720
[Guest]: eat like a bird and poop like an elephant. In the end, the metric is always about your if your

03:22:25.720 --> 03:22:31.720
[Guest]: your if your odds are better. Warren Buffett apparently once talked to Peter Lynch and said

03:22:31.720 --> 03:22:35.640
[Guest]: he wanted to use a quote from one of his books and Peter Lynch had written in one of his books,

03:22:35.640 --> 03:22:43.720
[Guest]: which said, selling your winners and keeping your losers is like cutting off the flowers

03:22:43.720 --> 03:22:51.400
[Guest]: and watering the weeds. So that I think is true for everything. So compounding will only happen

03:22:51.400 --> 03:22:57.400
[Guest]: if you water the flowers, not, you know, try to take the flowers off. That's beautifully put. And

03:22:57.400 --> 03:23:00.840
[Amit Varma]: no, in the poker context, I think like, first of all, I would say that a streak is something that

03:23:00.840 --> 03:23:06.280
[Amit Varma]: you call a streak only in hindsight, right? And I think in any given moment, you evaluate the

03:23:06.280 --> 03:23:11.560
[Amit Varma]: expected value of that decision there. So if I'm sitting with a bunch of players where I know I

03:23:11.560 --> 03:23:16.680
[Amit Varma]: have an edge, then I'll continue playing whether I'm down or up. But if I feel I'm very tired,

03:23:16.680 --> 03:23:21.960
[Amit Varma]: and that affects my EV, I'll factor that in. But every decision has to be according to that

03:23:21.960 --> 03:23:25.960
[Amit Varma]: particular moment, which in a human way is hard, you could actually be down a lot because you're

03:23:25.960 --> 03:23:30.360
[Amit Varma]: running really bad, but playing really well. And then that affects your judgment. Or you could get

03:23:30.360 --> 03:23:35.320
[Amit Varma]: overconfident at a table where you are the fish on the table. But you know, that can affect your

03:23:35.320 --> 03:23:39.400
[Amit Varma]: judgment. And just going back to that, you know, that hypothetical example of there's a shared has

03:23:39.400 --> 03:23:44.760
[Amit Varma]: gone from 300 to 3000. And now this guy comes and says I missed all the this thing. And I'd again

03:23:44.760 --> 03:23:50.120
[Amit Varma]: say that, I think the human tendency is to see that journey that a stock has made from here to

03:23:50.120 --> 03:23:54.840
[Amit Varma]: there and say, oh, shit, I missed out on all this much. But I think at any moment in time,

03:23:54.840 --> 03:23:59.160
[Amit Varma]: what you decide to do is a judgment call that you're making at that point in time. So if it's

03:23:59.160 --> 03:24:04.840
[Amit Varma]: 3000, your your question is not what it was yesterday, except in the sense that if there is

03:24:04.840 --> 03:24:09.400
[Amit Varma]: a trend happening there, and that trend could factor into your decision, but your judgment is

03:24:09.400 --> 03:24:15.480
[Amit Varma]: is this a good buy right now or not? Right? And so, you know, and that's just a way that people

03:24:15.480 --> 03:24:19.800
[Amit Varma]: are not hardwired to think in a similar way, if you know, a stock falls, if it's 100, and it goes

03:24:19.800 --> 03:24:25.800
[Amit Varma]: to 80, you know, the correct decision to ask yourself is would I buy this for 80? Right?

03:24:25.800 --> 03:24:30.120
[Amit Varma]: Otherwise, otherwise, why hold it holding on to something is equal to buying it? If you wouldn't

03:24:30.120 --> 03:24:34.760
[Amit Varma]: buy it at that price? Why would you hold on to it, then let it go either it's worth 80 or it's not

03:24:34.760 --> 03:24:39.080
[Amit Varma]: whether you already have it or not, is irrelevant to that.

03:24:39.080 --> 03:24:43.160
[Guest]: This I think is where I think I would disagree over here. Because again, I know there's a

03:24:43.160 --> 03:24:49.960
[Guest]: behavioral aspect to having owned and not having owned it. But there are actually there is a

03:24:49.960 --> 03:24:55.960
[Guest]: concept called a hold, which is don't buy, don't sell, but hold. There's a reason you want to do

03:24:55.960 --> 03:25:02.040
[Guest]: this. Now, this is a difference between looking at an individual stock and looking at a portfolio.

03:25:02.040 --> 03:25:07.880
[Guest]: When you look at a portfolio, which is a bunch of different things, every action that you take

03:25:07.880 --> 03:25:12.120
[Guest]: at any given point in time introduces the need for another action to counterbalance something

03:25:12.120 --> 03:25:17.000
[Guest]: else. If I sell something, I want to buy something and so on. That is one reason why you might want

03:25:17.000 --> 03:25:24.120
[Guest]: to continue to hold. Second is that let us say there is a there is, I'll give you a real example

03:25:24.120 --> 03:25:28.280
[Guest]: of some stocks that happen. There are sometimes these international funds, these international

03:25:28.280 --> 03:25:34.840
[Guest]: funds want to exit. Now, you are looking at them exit and you're saying, listen, there are only

03:25:34.840 --> 03:25:38.920
[Guest]: two reasons why they can exit. One is they know that something is sinister underneath.

03:25:39.640 --> 03:25:45.000
[Guest]: And B is that they're actually exiting because maybe they need to move out of the stock and

03:25:45.000 --> 03:25:48.280
[Guest]: some into some other stock and they're just artificially depressing the price. You don't

03:25:48.280 --> 03:25:53.880
[Guest]: know which one is what. You have a certain position, that position is supposed to be

03:25:53.880 --> 03:25:58.680
[Guest]: is relatively small today. You could increase the position saying, listen, I know what's right with

03:25:58.680 --> 03:26:02.200
[Guest]: this company. I know everything's right with this company. And the minute you know that everything

03:26:02.200 --> 03:26:06.840
[Guest]: is right, you could increase that position. We don't know yet. On the other side, on the other

03:26:06.840 --> 03:26:10.680
[Guest]: hand, if the company is really bad, then you should be selling everything. But you don't know

03:26:10.680 --> 03:26:15.560
[Guest]: that yet as well. You might want to wait for that further information before taking that call.

03:26:15.560 --> 03:26:20.280
[Guest]: The only constraint is you have a portfolio, this is about 2% of that portfolio. Are you

03:26:20.280 --> 03:26:25.080
[Guest]: comfortable with it being 2%? Or do you want to take it down to 1% and make that decision at a

03:26:25.080 --> 03:26:30.680
[Guest]: later point in life? This is the portfolio level thinking that should drive whether you hold,

03:26:30.680 --> 03:26:36.360
[Guest]: buy or sell a stock. And many times these are not relevant to the individual stocks,

03:26:37.080 --> 03:26:41.320
[Guest]: gyrations or movements, but to your thinking of the portfolio as a whole.

03:26:41.320 --> 03:26:48.440
[Guest]: The other important point of this is why you need a hold sometimes is when a stock is purchased,

03:26:48.440 --> 03:26:53.960
[Guest]: you may be buying it over a long period of time. That means every month that you know,

03:26:53.960 --> 03:26:59.800
[Guest]: you get more money, I will add on to it over time. That means I may want to buy the stock,

03:26:59.800 --> 03:27:04.360
[Guest]: but not now because my money comes in the future, I'm only going to put in more money at that time,

03:27:04.360 --> 03:27:07.720
[Guest]: at which point you're not going to sell today, but you don't have more money to buy it,

03:27:07.720 --> 03:27:13.080
[Guest]: you would buy it if you had it. So yeah, I mean, you could make that argument that if I didn't want

03:27:13.080 --> 03:27:22.200
[Guest]: to buy it at all, I wouldn't. In most cases, I feel that catching falling knives requires a lot

03:27:22.200 --> 03:27:29.960
[Guest]: more experience, and a lot more knowledge. Because all companies tell you exactly what you want to

03:27:29.960 --> 03:27:35.160
[Guest]: hear. So if you like the company, they will tell you no, the next quarter will be good. Right? So

03:27:35.160 --> 03:27:42.600
[Guest]: the check is in the mail. It's always going to come to you like that. So if you're looking at

03:27:42.600 --> 03:27:48.200
[Guest]: the price and it's falling, most likely the reasons why that they're giving you for the

03:27:48.200 --> 03:27:54.760
[Guest]: underperformance is, it's likely to be, come on, are you out of your mind? Because if everybody

03:27:54.760 --> 03:27:58.920
[Guest]: believed that the price would not be down, there's another reason that the whole market could be down

03:27:58.920 --> 03:28:03.880
[Guest]: like you know, Russia. I mean, why does Russia attacking Ukraine affect one Indian guy selling

03:28:03.880 --> 03:28:11.000
[Guest]: toothpaste? I mean, are we not going to brush our teeth tomorrow? Because you know, but chances are

03:28:11.000 --> 03:28:16.280
[Guest]: that was just an excuse. And somebody had bought too much of toothpaste company and taken it to a

03:28:16.280 --> 03:28:20.920
[Guest]: high that was too high. And now they're just correcting back to a point where it trades like

03:28:20.920 --> 03:28:28.120
[Guest]: a toothpaste company, not like a company that mints gold. So today, you what the reason for

03:28:28.120 --> 03:28:33.720
[Guest]: its downfall may sound like Russia's attacking Ukraine, but it's actually you're paying a

03:28:33.720 --> 03:28:38.520
[Guest]: company that makes toothpaste as if it was making gold. Now we're going to evaluate like it's a

03:28:38.520 --> 03:28:43.160
[Guest]: company making toothpaste, at which point your decision making would change into okay, dude,

03:28:43.160 --> 03:28:47.960
[Guest]: I think I don't like this company making toothpaste valued at this rate. I'll wait

03:28:47.960 --> 03:28:52.920
[Guest]: till it comes to a valuation that reflects it's making toothpaste and then only buy.

03:28:53.720 --> 03:29:00.040
[Guest]: Great decision making requires a lot more depth of knowledge to think about it. Sometimes the

03:29:00.040 --> 03:29:05.720
[Guest]: best thing to do is just asset allocate and hold, which means I have so much money in equity,

03:29:05.720 --> 03:29:13.320
[Guest]: I have so much money in debt, I don't, I focus on that more than I focus on which exact company

03:29:13.320 --> 03:29:19.320
[Guest]: have I got more ownership in. And therefore, you know, kind of but like you said, the hands

03:29:19.320 --> 03:29:25.000
[Guest]: matter sometimes. And the more knowledgeable you are about the hands, the specific stocks,

03:29:25.000 --> 03:29:32.040
[Guest]: you can make much more informed decisions about them. Generally, you want to have the ability to

03:29:32.040 --> 03:29:36.840
[Guest]: identify bullshit. So in poker, I'm sure there are a lot of ways to identify whether a person

03:29:36.840 --> 03:29:42.840
[Guest]: is bluffing most famously in the I think Casino Royale, there was this guy's eye twitching and

03:29:42.840 --> 03:29:48.360
[Amit Varma]: those are very cinematic depictions in the real world where poker right now is that any good

03:29:48.360 --> 03:29:54.040
[Amit Varma]: player will mix it up to the extent that it's as close to game theory optimal as possible. So,

03:29:54.680 --> 03:29:58.440
[Amit Varma]: you know, like just to give you an example, let's say there is 200 rupees in the pot,

03:29:58.440 --> 03:30:04.440
[Amit Varma]: and I bet 100 rupees and now you have a decision on the river. So you are you have to call 100 to

03:30:04.440 --> 03:30:08.760
[Amit Varma]: win 300 because there's 300 in the pot, you're getting three to one odds, right? And therefore,

03:30:08.760 --> 03:30:15.400
[Amit Varma]: you should call if you know, 25% you know, depending on how often I bluff, if I if I'm

03:30:15.400 --> 03:30:20.040
[Amit Varma]: bluffing too much, you should absolutely call. But if I'm bluffing too little, you should fold.

03:30:20.040 --> 03:30:25.480
[Amit Varma]: And the idea there is that I construct my range in such a way that when I give you three to one odds,

03:30:25.480 --> 03:30:30.120
[Amit Varma]: 25% of my hands are bluffs and the rest are value hands. So it doesn't matter what you do.

03:30:31.000 --> 03:30:35.480
[Amit Varma]: It doesn't matter what you do. If you play perfectly, I break even. But if you call too

03:30:35.480 --> 03:30:39.320
[Amit Varma]: much or fold too much, I make money in the long run, you're looking at everything in the long

03:30:39.320 --> 03:30:44.920
[Amit Varma]: run. So it's a it's a whole different kind of game that whole Casino Royale romance that you'll see

03:30:44.920 --> 03:30:49.880
[Amit Varma]: somebody's nose twitch and all that and you'll get a tell and you'll do all that. No, like at any

03:30:49.880 --> 03:30:54.920
[Amit Varma]: decent level, it's like fairly mathematical and that doesn't really happen. But let's move on to

03:30:54.920 --> 03:31:00.360
[Amit Varma]: your second lesson now, which is in fact what you nicely segwayed into yourself. And your second

03:31:00.360 --> 03:31:06.600
[Amit Varma]: lesson there was money is made largely when you sleep. Right? And explain this a little bit because

03:31:06.600 --> 03:31:11.960
[Amit Varma]: again, I think romantic notions of stock market investing, just as in poker, are often very far

03:31:11.960 --> 03:31:15.640
[Amit Varma]: from the truth, where the notions are that you know, you've got your flickering screens in front

03:31:15.640 --> 03:31:20.600
[Amit Varma]: of you, you see something happen, Russia has invaded Ukraine, like so Russia, Ukraine is

03:31:20.600 --> 03:31:24.840
[Amit Varma]: very much the topic of the day. So you know, they look at like Russia, Ukraine,

03:31:24.840 --> 03:31:29.080
[Amit Varma]: this has happened, there's a strike going on in the salt mine, let's sell this. You know,

03:31:29.080 --> 03:31:34.920
[Amit Varma]: that's a romantic notion of whatever, but at the level of nitty gritties, it's not quite that

03:31:34.920 --> 03:31:40.040
[Amit Varma]: dramatic. So, you know, so tell me a little bit by what you mean when you say money is made largely

03:31:40.040 --> 03:31:45.960
[Guest]: when you sleep. So this actually comes down to that very point, because the attraction that

03:31:45.960 --> 03:31:52.280
[Guest]: your skill is in identifying those opportunities when they happen. It's less relevant than just

03:31:52.840 --> 03:31:57.080
[Guest]: having a simplistic whole story. I'll give you an example. I mean, a lot of people tell me this.

03:31:57.960 --> 03:32:03.400
[Guest]: Deepak, I have made 200% on the stock. And I'll say, hey, I have the same stock, I made only 10%.

03:32:05.400 --> 03:32:09.560
[Guest]: And then I asked them, how much have you invested in the stock? I put 10,000 rupees.

03:32:09.560 --> 03:32:17.320
[Guest]: 10,000 rupees. So I'll say I have put 5 lakh rupees, my 5 lakh rupees, I made 50,000 rupees,

03:32:17.320 --> 03:32:23.000
[Guest]: your 10,000 you made. So it's not like you didn't have 5 lakh rupees, you just chose to put 10,000.

03:32:23.000 --> 03:32:29.720
[Guest]: So how much money you put into the opportunity is another reason why you might make more or less

03:32:29.720 --> 03:32:34.440
[Guest]: on this. He might have 4 lakhs 90,000 rupees sitting in a fixed deposit, which didn't give

03:32:34.440 --> 03:32:40.200
[Guest]: him anything or give him three and a half percent post tax. So I am, I would say a large part of

03:32:41.160 --> 03:32:47.560
[Guest]: what money you make is how you allocate money to this. The more money you allocate to opportunities,

03:32:48.120 --> 03:32:53.880
[Guest]: and then the more your feeling of wanting to act as well. And if you start acting too often,

03:32:53.880 --> 03:33:01.000
[Guest]: the chances are that you are going to either exit an opportunity too soon, or and not allow it give

03:33:01.000 --> 03:33:07.240
[Guest]: time to breathe. Or in an even worse fashion, you're going to generate stress by owning that

03:33:07.240 --> 03:33:13.400
[Guest]: investment and looking at it on an everyday basis. If you take these two aspects, and then say what

03:33:13.400 --> 03:33:19.560
[Guest]: happens if you just hold the stocks. Now I did an experiment, I said, okay, 2006, I take all the

03:33:19.560 --> 03:33:25.400
[Guest]: stocks of the nifty. And I put an equal amount of money in every single one of them. 10 years later,

03:33:25.400 --> 03:33:31.160
[Guest]: what happens? So I find out that 10 years later, four stocks had fallen more than 95%.

03:33:32.040 --> 03:33:36.120
[Guest]: That means these were nifty stocks, the top 50 stocks of the Indian exchange,

03:33:36.120 --> 03:33:41.960
[Guest]: four of them have actually fallen 95% plus some was 98, some 96, Unitec and this.

03:33:42.920 --> 03:33:48.680
[Guest]: Around another 14 of them had negative absolute returns, which means whatever I'd invested in

03:33:48.680 --> 03:33:55.960
[Guest]: 2006, would actually be less in 2016 on an absolute basis. Another 14 or 15 of them roughly

03:33:56.520 --> 03:34:01.960
[Guest]: made positive returns, but less than inflation, which was roughly 7% average during this time.

03:34:02.680 --> 03:34:10.600
[Guest]: So you're saying 37 to 39 companies made less than inflation, and some of them lost severely

03:34:11.320 --> 03:34:16.600
[Guest]: out of 50. And yet, the whole amount of money, which is, let us say 10,000 rupees per stock

03:34:16.600 --> 03:34:24.040
[Guest]: into 55 lakh rupees, made an a total return of over 12% per year, not counting dividends

03:34:24.040 --> 03:34:29.240
[Guest]: in those 10 years, which means the 10 or 11 stocks that actually made money made it paid so much

03:34:29.240 --> 03:34:36.440
[Guest]: money that they were enough to kind of, what did I do differently? I didn't sell anything,

03:34:36.440 --> 03:34:40.200
[Guest]: not the winners, not the losers, I just left them, let them all be, I'm saying,

03:34:40.200 --> 03:34:45.960
[Guest]: what are the flowers and the thorns, it doesn't matter, because in the end, whatever's bad will

03:34:45.960 --> 03:34:52.520
[Guest]: just will die, but the stuff that remains will be enough to take you for a long time. That was what

03:34:52.520 --> 03:34:57.400
[Guest]: I meant when I say money is made when you sleep, because if your concept of action is that if I'm

03:34:57.400 --> 03:35:01.960
[Guest]: not sleeping, I need to be finding the bad stocks and selling them. My answer to that is it doesn't

03:35:01.960 --> 03:35:07.400
[Guest]: matter if you sell them all. And in the surreal garden of happiness, what appears to be a flower

03:35:07.400 --> 03:35:12.360
[Amit Varma]: today could be a thorn tomorrow and vice versa. So just hold the damn thing and see where it goes.

03:35:12.360 --> 03:35:17.160
[Guest]: Yeah, for the most part, if you've made your decisions, large and diversified,

03:35:17.800 --> 03:35:23.080
[Guest]: I built something called a random portfolio. So I said, at any point in time, choose a bunch of

03:35:23.080 --> 03:35:29.160
[Guest]: stocks, randomly 10, it's like monkeys picking stocks, is that monkey picking stocks better

03:35:29.160 --> 03:35:35.480
[Guest]: than the stock market? If consistently, monkeys picking stock become better than the stock

03:35:35.480 --> 03:35:41.800
[Guest]: market, better than the stock market, it's a bull market. If it is not possible, that means you're

03:35:41.800 --> 03:35:46.920
[Guest]: half and half, sometimes you beat sometimes you don't, then it's not a bull market. It could be

03:35:46.920 --> 03:35:50.120
[Guest]: a bear market, it could be a sideways market, but it's not a bull market, that means the stocks are

03:35:50.120 --> 03:35:56.040
[Guest]: not going up. In a bull market, no matter what you do, you will make money. It is like being blind,

03:35:56.040 --> 03:36:00.600
[Guest]: it's not your skill, it is the monkey. In a bear market, there is some skill involved, but

03:36:00.600 --> 03:36:06.200
[Guest]: the bear market players will only make money in a bull market. That means if the market stay

03:36:06.200 --> 03:36:10.200
[Guest]: bearish for a long time, it doesn't matter what skill you have, you will not make money.

03:36:10.200 --> 03:36:16.200
[Guest]: You need a bull market to make money. And if you survive long enough, you will see bull markets,

03:36:16.200 --> 03:36:23.800
[Guest]: because bull markets are a function of greed and fear, fear of missing out and the greed of making

03:36:23.800 --> 03:36:30.040
[Guest]: money. And that is so human, that no matter what happens at some point in time in five years,

03:36:30.040 --> 03:36:36.680
[Guest]: there will be a layer of greed that will drive the markets up. India's entire market history from

03:36:36.680 --> 03:36:47.000
[Guest]: 1992 to now, post liberalization, can be classified into four great years, 2004 to 2008, January

03:36:47.000 --> 03:36:55.320
[Guest]: roughly, and two great years between 2020 and 2022. That is it, that is our bull markets.

03:36:55.320 --> 03:36:59.400
[Guest]: In the middle, there was some bull, some bear, some bull, some bear. But these are the years

03:36:59.400 --> 03:37:03.320
[Guest]: where if you had stayed invested in the markets, and not done anything, you would have made out

03:37:03.320 --> 03:37:10.520
[Guest]: like a bandit. You miss these six years, and it would take a lot of skill to make money.

03:37:11.160 --> 03:37:15.960
[Amit Varma]: Do these years correlate with easy money coming in from the US, quantitative easing and so on?

03:37:15.960 --> 03:37:18.600
[Guest]: There was no quantitative easing in 2004, 2007, but

03:37:18.600 --> 03:37:21.720
[Amit Varma]: But you had low interest rates, you had low interest rates and all that, right?

03:37:21.720 --> 03:37:27.240
[Guest]: Actually, the US started raising interest rates in 2005. We don't miss that. So it was,

03:37:27.240 --> 03:37:33.240
[Guest]: it was not, the low interest rates started off in 2008. But it was easy money in the sense the

03:37:33.240 --> 03:37:36.200
[Guest]: money was coming in from the US, they were buying anything that was possible,

03:37:36.760 --> 03:37:40.760
[Guest]: because relatively, we were so small. 2020 also was a function of,

03:37:40.760 --> 03:37:45.640
[Guest]: but there has been quantitative easing in the West from 2008, 2018.

03:37:45.640 --> 03:37:47.320
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, it did affect us.

03:37:47.320 --> 03:37:52.440
[Guest]: At that time, the market was growing only at 10% a year. So, which is great, which is not that great.

03:37:52.440 --> 03:37:59.240
[Guest]: But I'm talking about the last 20 to 22, we grew more than 50% in the stock markets.

03:37:59.240 --> 03:38:06.040
[Guest]: Well, I'm, I don't have the exact numbers, but I'm just saying 2004 to 2008 was just phenomenal.

03:38:06.040 --> 03:38:15.080
[Guest]: I think the market doubled, went from 1300 in the nifty to 8000 in those four years,

03:38:15.080 --> 03:38:20.600
[Guest]: or sorry, 6000, 6500, 300 in those four years. So roughly 4x in four years.

03:38:20.600 --> 03:38:23.640
[Amit Varma]: So anybody who invested would have felt so skillful.

