[Amit Varma]: I don't know why you picked Croatia. But yeah, there you go. And, you know, think about allocation

03:48:19.960 --> 03:48:24.680
[Amit Varma]: and you know, plan for your necessities. And, you know, with the rest, enjoy your life,

03:48:24.680 --> 03:48:30.600
[Amit Varma]: as you put it, and build personal leverage, you have also said. So what do you mean by build

03:48:30.600 --> 03:48:35.880
[Amit Varma]: personal leverage? And how is it different from the kind of investing in yourself that we spoke about?

03:48:35.880 --> 03:48:40.920
[Guest]: Okay, so personal leverage is a complicated concept to understand, but think about it like this.

03:48:41.880 --> 03:48:48.840
[Guest]: Okay, when you invest, when you do something as a job for someone, they pay you a salary,

03:48:48.840 --> 03:48:57.240
[Guest]: and that is it. You stop working, the money stops flowing in. So it's like you're a hamster in a

03:48:57.240 --> 03:49:02.360
[Guest]: wheel that's giving you water, you're as long as you're running, the water's coming, the minute

03:49:02.360 --> 03:49:09.240
[Guest]: you stop, the water stops and you die of thirst. This is terrible, because the typical advice now

03:49:09.240 --> 03:49:13.960
[Guest]: is, we're getting a lot of water today, take that water and store it somewhere and let it keep

03:49:13.960 --> 03:49:17.960
[Guest]: growing. And eventually when you'll have you'll get tired enough and stop and the water stops,

03:49:17.960 --> 03:49:22.680
[Guest]: you have a storage of water somewhere else that you can use for your future needs. Fantastic,

03:49:22.680 --> 03:49:27.480
[Guest]: very great advice. But there's another way. And there's a better, this is a better way

03:49:27.480 --> 03:49:31.400
[Guest]: according to me. This is the idea of building personal leverage. Now, it comes back to the

03:49:31.400 --> 03:49:37.560
[Guest]: creator economy in ways that perhaps are interesting for this episode. But anything

03:49:37.560 --> 03:49:45.560
[Guest]: that you build that is an asset helps you in the long term. Now, what that does is,

03:49:45.560 --> 03:49:49.400
[Guest]: for instance, if you wrote a book, now, it's a very bad idea, because you won't get anything

03:49:49.400 --> 03:49:54.520
[Guest]: in royalties nowadays. But let's say it's a wild chance, there's an optionality of it being a

03:49:54.520 --> 03:50:00.360
[Guest]: bestseller, that optionality is one in 500. You make a YouTube channel, it can get get you some

03:50:00.360 --> 03:50:06.280
[Guest]: income, but it'll get you that income 10 years down the line. This at some level is a flywheel

03:50:06.280 --> 03:50:13.000
[Guest]: that can operate by itself. Well, not entirely by itself, but some part of it can operate without

03:50:13.000 --> 03:50:18.920
[Guest]: you needing to work for it at a certain stage. Start a business, employ people to do the work

03:50:18.920 --> 03:50:24.600
[Guest]: you do, you can reap the benefits while paying them a salary, get a house. Now, I don't recommend

03:50:24.600 --> 03:50:29.800
[Guest]: this because in India, it's a terrible idea because the returns are not great. But or build

03:50:29.800 --> 03:50:34.120
[Guest]: a stock portfolio, the stock portfolio pays you dividends, the dividends take care of you,

03:50:34.120 --> 03:50:39.880
[Guest]: regardless of whatever, and they kind of grow on their own separately. I think building personal

03:50:39.880 --> 03:50:45.800
[Guest]: leverage is a concept of saying you're not just investing in yourself to be able to get a better

03:50:45.800 --> 03:50:54.120
[Guest]: salary. But you also want to build something that sustains itself, even if you aren't working. So

03:50:54.120 --> 03:51:00.200
[Guest]: you stop, the more personal leverage you build, the better it is. And so this is also the way the

03:51:00.200 --> 03:51:05.560
[Guest]: world thinks of you. So for instance, the tax department thinks of you, you have no personal

03:51:05.560 --> 03:51:10.440
[Guest]: leverage, you're an employee, you're an employee, you get a salary, that salary, they take the tax

03:51:10.440 --> 03:51:17.880
[Guest]: out, you get the remaining, you spend it. You own a business, you make some revenue from something,

03:51:18.600 --> 03:51:24.520
[Guest]: you get to spend money from it, and only on what's left do you pay taxes. Even better,

03:51:24.520 --> 03:51:30.040
[Guest]: you build a private limited company, the taxation is not 33%, but it's 25%. I've been telling you

03:51:30.040 --> 03:51:36.200
[Guest]: about this as well, that your tax suddenly falls to 25% if all you do is take the extra effort

03:51:36.200 --> 03:51:40.120
[Guest]: of creating a private limited company in India and doing the exact same thing.

03:51:40.120 --> 03:51:44.520
[Guest]: The money that stays, of course, stays in your own little private limited company, but that

03:51:44.520 --> 03:51:51.320
[Guest]: money is effectively yours to use at some point. The CAs may disagree, but by and large,

03:51:51.320 --> 03:51:57.240
[Guest]: it's a better way to allow your money to compound than to have to earn a salary. So the tax

03:51:57.240 --> 03:52:02.520
[Guest]: department recognizes the more personal leverage you have, the lower we should tax you. So maybe

03:52:02.520 --> 03:52:08.840
[Guest]: listen to the tax department. So this is a form of investment, but personal leverage also has

03:52:08.840 --> 03:52:15.320
[Guest]: different layers. If you build reputation, that's personal leverage. Because people in this world,

03:52:15.320 --> 03:52:21.160
[Guest]: trust is a deficit, it always will be a deficit. The more trust you can generate by being who you

03:52:21.160 --> 03:52:26.680
[Guest]: are, whether you're a creator or whether you're a speaker or someone who just, I don't know,

03:52:26.680 --> 03:52:34.360
[Guest]: does a bunch of things that make your face as recognition in a certain field that you really

03:52:34.360 --> 03:52:40.440
[Guest]: love to operate in. I know a bunch of people who, for instance, are super trustworthy for just

03:52:40.440 --> 03:52:46.040
[Guest]: knowing the historical sites in Bombay or Bangalore or Delhi, because they do it as a hobby.

03:52:46.040 --> 03:52:50.360
[Guest]: They just take people for a walk every Sunday. This is personal leverage at some level. They're

03:52:50.360 --> 03:52:54.200
[Guest]: not realizing it right now. They're probably doing it for free because they enjoy this stuff.

03:52:54.200 --> 03:52:57.880
[Guest]: But they're building an aspect of personal leverage that gives them the optionality that

03:52:57.880 --> 03:53:02.600
[Guest]: tomorrow this could be a business. And when I start that business, I already have the trust

03:53:02.600 --> 03:53:08.600
[Guest]: and the recommendation of hundreds of people who love what I have done and will recommend me for

03:53:08.600 --> 03:53:13.720
[Guest]: getting more business or perhaps pay me directly as well. That personal leverage is something if

03:53:13.720 --> 03:53:20.360
[Guest]: you focus on, it is way more satisfying emotionally and personally. But it's also something that will

03:53:20.360 --> 03:53:26.040
[Guest]: build you financial leverage at a later point in time. Yeah. And I think what many people don't

03:53:26.040 --> 03:53:31.400
[Amit Varma]: realize is that they have, like the guy who takes people for walks, for example, they have personal

03:53:31.400 --> 03:53:35.640
[Amit Varma]: leverage in ways that they are not using or monetizing or whatever. You know, you could

03:53:35.640 --> 03:53:40.360
[Amit Varma]: have some skills that people value, but you are not giving them a chance to pay you for it. And

03:53:40.360 --> 03:53:44.520
[Amit Varma]: you're not giving them a chance to benefit from it. So it's like, you know, it would be a positive

03:53:44.520 --> 03:53:48.920
[Amit Varma]: sum game if you do so. Like, you know, if this person with this deep knowledge organized tours

03:53:48.920 --> 03:53:53.160
[Amit Varma]: and took money for it and all that, I'm sure people are interested. Or if you, for example,

03:53:53.160 --> 03:53:57.480
[Amit Varma]: were to teach a course on, you know, how to invest, people would pay a massive premium.

03:53:57.480 --> 03:54:01.400
[Amit Varma]: No question about it. And you see in the creator economy, people realizing it,

03:54:01.400 --> 03:54:06.600
[Amit Varma]: like there's a great video link from the show notes by Ali Abdaal, where he talks about how

03:54:06.600 --> 03:54:12.040
[Amit Varma]: last year he made $2.7 million in income. Right. And what I love about many of these YouTubers

03:54:12.040 --> 03:54:15.720
[Amit Varma]: is a very transparent, they'll do a full video where they'll tell you I made so much.

03:54:15.720 --> 03:54:20.200
[Amit Varma]: And because people love such videos, they'll make even more. But, and it is such a mix of nice

03:54:20.200 --> 03:54:25.080
[Amit Varma]: things. So he's got passive income coming from courses and Skillshare, where he's got courses

03:54:25.080 --> 03:54:29.320
[Amit Varma]: on YouTubing and creating and this and that productivity, and that's passive income and

03:54:29.880 --> 03:54:35.400
[Amit Varma]: coming down to the equivalent of crores of rupees just from there. He's got a live cohort based

03:54:35.400 --> 03:54:40.680
[Amit Varma]: YouTubing course, you know, charging a premium because it's live and you know, personal mentorship

03:54:40.680 --> 03:54:44.680
[Amit Varma]: and all that and making tons of money from there, and so on. So he breaks it all down where the

03:54:44.680 --> 03:54:51.560
[Amit Varma]: 2.7 million is coming. And that's and what a person like that is doing is sitting down and

03:54:51.560 --> 03:54:56.440
[Amit Varma]: saying that, okay, what is valuable about me, you know, and these are the many things which are

03:54:56.440 --> 03:55:00.600
[Amit Varma]: valuable about me the little silos of knowledge in which I have something and I can help people

03:55:00.600 --> 03:55:05.080
[Amit Varma]: or whatever. These are the different ways in which I can express them. So online course, cohort based

03:55:05.080 --> 03:55:11.080
[Amit Varma]: course, blah, blah, blah. And then you kind of do that. And I think too many of us have value

03:55:11.080 --> 03:55:16.440
[Amit Varma]: locked up inside of us, you know, have that personal leverage already, which we don't

03:55:16.440 --> 03:55:21.640
[Amit Varma]: do enough to monetize, you know, and we are stuck in the old paradigm,

03:55:24.200 --> 03:55:28.600
[Amit Varma]: economy goes down, we get laid off, you know, we're like, shit, I'm worth nothing.

03:55:29.320 --> 03:55:33.720
[Amit Varma]: Nobody's worth nothing. Right? So that's what to get back to your book.

03:55:33.720 --> 03:55:39.480
[Guest]: No, no, but it's, you have a point. There's a reason why people don't like to build personal

03:55:39.480 --> 03:55:44.920
[Guest]: leverage, because there's a risk involved, that if you put yourself out there, what if you fail?

03:55:45.480 --> 03:55:50.200
[Guest]: This what if you fail, according to me, in today's world, there should be no consequences of

03:55:50.760 --> 03:55:55.400
[Guest]: if today there is a failure, what's going to happen? Nobody going to drive us,

03:55:56.200 --> 03:56:02.040
[Guest]: drive a stake into you and, you know, put you on this thing. But the problem is, we think like

03:56:02.040 --> 03:56:07.560
[Guest]: that. And the cost of failure today is lesser and lesser. And what happens if your YouTube channel

03:56:07.560 --> 03:56:13.960
[Guest]: fails? Almost nothing, there will be no graveyard and there will be no tombstone. You don't even

03:56:13.960 --> 03:56:19.480
[Guest]: have to think of it and you just it will just vanish into the ether. Like it never existed.

03:56:19.480 --> 03:56:26.200
[Guest]: There will be no, you know, so you Why are we then so fearful of failure? I don't understand

03:56:26.200 --> 03:56:31.000
[Guest]: that. But I think a lot of it comes down to, you know, this is why Indians like government jobs

03:56:31.000 --> 03:56:34.440
[Guest]: is because you can never fail in those government jobs, they can never fire you.

03:56:34.440 --> 03:56:40.360
[Guest]: And therefore, you know, the risk taking is is non existent. And yet India is a country that

03:56:40.360 --> 03:56:45.720
[Guest]: has more entrepreneurs than most of the Western countries. And from a numbers perspective,

03:56:45.720 --> 03:56:51.640
[Guest]: even if you add up all the Western countries, all the small entrepreneurs in the in those countries

03:56:51.640 --> 03:56:56.520
[Guest]: won't add up to even half of what India has. India is a very tiny part of our economy is

03:56:56.520 --> 03:57:02.440
[Guest]: actually salaried. Most of our economy is entrepreneurial or by nature or by force by so

03:57:02.440 --> 03:57:08.200
[Guest]: So we get risk, yet, we are afraid of taking those risks.

03:57:09.560 --> 03:57:14.840
[Amit Varma]: I think one of the reasons that so many people apply for government jobs and that charm of the

03:57:14.840 --> 03:57:19.320
[Amit Varma]: government jobs still remains where there'll be some lowly railway linesman position open at

03:57:19.320 --> 03:57:24.040
[Amit Varma]: 20,000 a month, and there'll be 8 lakh people applying for it. And, you know, with PhDs and

03:57:24.040 --> 03:57:27.800
[Amit Varma]: all of that. And it's a sad and poignant reason and you can't blame them, which is that we are

03:57:27.800 --> 03:57:32.120
[Amit Varma]: a desperately poor country. Those opportunities really aren't there. It's been 70 something years

03:57:32.120 --> 03:57:38.200
[Amit Varma]: of economic mismanagement where bad policies have kept millions of people in poverty. Where I am

03:57:38.200 --> 03:57:42.680
[Amit Varma]: hopeful is not that governance will change. You know, I have no hope there. Where I'm hopeful

03:57:42.680 --> 03:57:47.480
[Amit Varma]: is that technology in interesting ways can actually empower people. Like I tell the,

03:57:47.480 --> 03:57:51.240
[Amit Varma]: I've told the story, I think a couple of times on my show of this vlogger called MSK.

03:57:51.240 --> 03:57:55.480
[Amit Varma]: Have I told you about it? Let me quickly go through it. There's this guy called Mohammed

03:57:55.480 --> 03:58:00.040
[Amit Varma]: Saleem Khan, and born in a village in Bengal, I'll link to the talk where he talks about all

03:58:00.040 --> 03:58:05.960
[Amit Varma]: of this as well. Born in a village in Bengal, comes to Mumbai, staying in a slum in Dharavi.

03:58:05.960 --> 03:58:11.720
[Amit Varma]: And his mother is, you know, a domestic help in various houses. And his father is a watchman.

03:58:12.280 --> 03:58:17.080
[Amit Varma]: And when he's 15, he, his mother, his siblings, they go back to the Bengal village for a holiday.

03:58:17.080 --> 03:58:21.800
[Amit Varma]: And then they get a phone call saying that your father's gone mad, come home. So they come back

03:58:21.800 --> 03:58:25.400
[Amit Varma]: to the slum in Dharavi. And as they're walking towards their home, things from their house are

03:58:25.400 --> 03:58:30.360
[Amit Varma]: all outside. And inside the house, there is nothing, it's an empty house, and the father's just inside,

03:58:30.360 --> 03:58:35.880
[Amit Varma]: and he's lost it. But anyway, they control the situation, they get him treated. And after they

03:58:35.880 --> 03:58:40.200
[Amit Varma]: get him treated, and he's back to his senses, his mother asked his father that, you know,

03:58:40.200 --> 03:58:45.240
[Amit Varma]: over 15 years, everything we saved, we kept it in this little trunk, you know, where is that trunk?

03:58:45.240 --> 03:58:48.920
[Amit Varma]: And he says, Oh, I was going somewhere by auto and I didn't have change. So I gave the auto

03:58:48.920 --> 03:58:55.640
[Amit Varma]: driver that trunk. Right? So 15 years, working like this, lost everything. And MSK, Mohan Selim

03:58:55.640 --> 03:59:00.920
[Amit Varma]: Khan, he's a 15 year old kid. And at this point, he says he made two promises to himself. Right?

03:59:00.920 --> 03:59:05.960
[Amit Varma]: One of them, as you would understand, is I will buy my parents a house in Bombay. Right? And the

03:59:05.960 --> 03:59:11.800
[Amit Varma]: other one is what, because he's 15. And I'm really glad he made this one. He said, there is that

03:59:11.800 --> 03:59:17.880
[Amit Varma]: super bike I like, I will buy myself that super bike. He does both. Okay, he goes on YouTube,

03:59:17.880 --> 03:59:23.000
[Amit Varma]: starts shooting stuff with his phone, eventually becomes, you know, hugely popular vlogger. And

03:59:23.000 --> 03:59:27.000
[Amit Varma]: if you see any single video of his, you won't get why he's popular. But if you see a bunch of them,

03:59:27.000 --> 03:59:32.120
[Amit Varma]: you begin to feel that connection again, the economy, the economy of intimacy, right? And he

03:59:32.120 --> 03:59:37.160
[Amit Varma]: does all that. And this is a terribly inspiring story to me. Because so far, in our history,

03:59:37.160 --> 03:59:41.160
[Amit Varma]: you have to be even no matter how creative you are, you've had to have some kind of privilege

03:59:41.160 --> 03:59:46.680
[Amit Varma]: to just get into the starting door. Right? You just have to. And today that's changing. And

03:59:46.680 --> 03:59:50.600
[Amit Varma]: I'm not saying it's changing for everyone or a super easy, but you saw an element of that with

03:59:50.600 --> 03:59:55.320
[Amit Varma]: tik tok. And you see an element of that with people like this. And God knows how many kids

03:59:55.320 --> 04:00:00.120
[Amit Varma]: in how many parts of this country are watching MSK's videos, and he's a cult. So he's got,

04:00:00.120 --> 04:00:04.440
[Amit Varma]: you know, his followers are called MSK, wherever he travels, somebody or the other will recognize

04:00:04.440 --> 04:00:09.720
[Amit Varma]: him, come to him, show him around. Right? And he's an inspiration to so many and God knows what the

04:00:09.720 --> 04:00:16.440
[Amit Varma]: unseen impact of that is. So that gives me hope. But that's anyway, a digression. So to get back

04:00:16.440 --> 04:00:22.840
[Amit Varma]: to the book, your second chapter, I found really interesting, where you sort of talk in detail

04:00:22.840 --> 04:00:28.760
[Amit Varma]: about mutual funds, different kinds of mutual funds, and how one picks a firm, all the parameters

04:00:28.760 --> 04:00:33.880
[Amit Varma]: and all of that. And at this point, I want to tell you the story of an interesting scam,

04:00:33.880 --> 04:00:37.880
[Amit Varma]: that it's a thought experiment. So it's not in your chapter suckered, it's just a thought

04:00:37.880 --> 04:00:45.240
[Amit Varma]: experiment. But it's a game theory thing. Let's say that you and I decide that we will write to

04:00:45.240 --> 04:00:51.000
[Amit Varma]: 1000 people and tell them that I must have shared this with you, I wrote a post on it ages back,

04:00:51.000 --> 04:00:55.960
[Amit Varma]: you and I will write to 1000 people and we tell them that we'll tell you the result of the next

04:00:55.960 --> 04:01:01.640
[Amit Varma]: India Australia match or whatever the series is. And we won't charge you anything, we'll just

04:01:01.640 --> 04:01:06.680
[Amit Varma]: tell you and you see over a period of time what our track record is. And we say India will win.

04:01:06.680 --> 04:01:12.360
[Amit Varma]: Right now, but to 500 people, we say India will win to 500 people, we say Australia will win.

04:01:12.360 --> 04:01:17.400
[Amit Varma]: No matter what happens, we got it right for 500 people. Rinse and repeat, we get it right two

04:01:17.400 --> 04:01:22.280
[Amit Varma]: times in a row for 250 people, three times in a row for 125 people. And finally, once we get it

04:01:22.280 --> 04:01:27.720
[Amit Varma]: five times in a row, the people who are left are thinking, gosh, these people are geniuses. And

04:01:27.720 --> 04:01:31.800
[Amit Varma]: then they're paying us a subscription and we've made out like bandits and we get the hell out of

04:01:31.800 --> 04:01:36.840
[Amit Varma]: there and, you know, go somewhere else. And I hope Ashneet Grover is not listening to this. It's an

04:01:36.840 --> 04:01:43.640
[Amit Varma]: idea. So yeah, and this in a sense is also this is reflective of the survivorship bias. I had a

04:01:43.640 --> 04:01:49.960
[Amit Varma]: variety of different strategies, which were India, Pakistan, India, India, India, or India, India,

04:01:49.960 --> 04:01:53.480
[Amit Varma]: India, Pakistan, India, or I don't know where Pakistan came in and India, Australia series,

04:01:53.480 --> 04:01:57.960
[Amit Varma]: but you get my point. And similarly, the point that you've made with mutual funds is that you

04:01:57.960 --> 04:02:02.040
[Amit Varma]: have to watch out for the survivorship bias as well, that there'll be many, many funds with many

04:02:02.040 --> 04:02:07.560
[Amit Varma]: different strategies doing many different things. And there is no way of knowing if someone who's,

04:02:07.560 --> 04:02:13.080
[Amit Varma]: you know, got the best results over three years, whether they got kind of lucky or not. And the

