[Guest]: Peter Lynch was quite phenomenally successful. But then since then, the Magellan Fund hasn't

04:03:15.880 --> 04:03:21.560
[Guest]: performed quite as well. Warren Buffett himself for the last 10 years or 15 years, his stock

04:03:21.560 --> 04:03:27.960
[Guest]: hasn't performed quite as well as the S&P 500 itself. It's interesting because you see in India

04:03:27.960 --> 04:03:35.720
[Guest]: in 2000, in the 2004 to 2008 timeframe, you could ask anybody in your in India, which mutual fund

04:03:35.720 --> 04:03:39.080
[Guest]: should I buy? They'll tell you HDFC Mutual Fund. And there's a reason for that, because it was

04:03:39.080 --> 04:03:44.360
[Guest]: doing the best, it had a bunch of funds, they're all doing really well, and so on. In the 2010 to

04:03:44.360 --> 04:03:50.920
[Guest]: 2011-12-13 kind of timeframe, you would get IDFC Mutual Fund, the fund manager was a star and he

04:03:50.920 --> 04:03:57.160
[Guest]: did really well for a long time and so on. Then from 2000, maybe 15 to 17 or 18, there's a bunch

04:03:57.160 --> 04:04:05.400
[Guest]: of other guys. From 2018 to 2020 specifically was Axis. None of their funds could get anything wrong.

04:04:05.400 --> 04:04:09.800
[Guest]: There's a company called Mire Asset, they were doing really well. You look at their performances

04:04:09.800 --> 04:04:16.120
[Guest]: today, they are less than stellar. So the order of the top has changed, the HDFC guy started to

04:04:16.120 --> 04:04:22.040
[Guest]: come back today. If you chose just based on the best, they were those regimes which worked for

04:04:22.040 --> 04:04:27.400
[Guest]: a few years and then they stopped working. And if you stuck along with those people who had stopped

04:04:27.400 --> 04:04:33.400
[Guest]: over a 10 year period, you found that their good first two, three years notwithstanding,

04:04:33.400 --> 04:04:39.480
[Guest]: a 10 year return is less than what I would have got given an index fund. Now, because they're

04:04:39.480 --> 04:04:44.600
[Guest]: selling so much, they have to charge higher fees, they end up charging 1 to 2% as fees,

04:04:44.600 --> 04:04:51.960
[Guest]: the index fund charges 0.15 or 0.2% as fees. So if your performance just ends up being average,

04:04:51.960 --> 04:04:59.240
[Guest]: and you charge 2x the fees, chances are you will underperform just because of the fee differential.

04:04:59.240 --> 04:05:03.400
[Guest]: Why do index fund charge lower fees? Because they don't make any decisions on the stocks they buy,

04:05:03.400 --> 04:05:07.560
[Guest]: they just have to buy whatever's in the index, in the same weightage as the index. So they don't

04:05:07.560 --> 04:05:12.440
[Guest]: have to think too much, because and you pay the money for the thinking, so you put a much lower

04:05:12.440 --> 04:05:18.440
[Guest]: fee in there. This is very, very interesting. From a point of view of a person who's investing in the

04:05:18.440 --> 04:05:23.320
[Guest]: markets, it comes down to this. If over long periods of time, indexes tend to outperform,

04:05:23.320 --> 04:05:29.000
[Guest]: if that is true, no matter when I look, and I don't need to outperform, if I rank all those

04:05:29.000 --> 04:05:35.880
[Guest]: mutual funds in a certain list, and if I find that these index funds are in the top quartile,

04:05:35.880 --> 04:05:40.680
[Guest]: or maybe even the second quartile, so I call the second quartile thinking, that is if you were in

04:05:40.680 --> 04:05:48.840
[Guest]: the second quartile, that means between 26% and 50% of the range of any large list on any given

04:05:48.840 --> 04:05:55.560
[Guest]: year, but you are always in the second quartile, and all of the other guys were sometimes in the

04:05:55.560 --> 04:06:01.080
[Guest]: first, sometimes the third, last, and so they were randomly in all of them. The guy who's

04:06:01.080 --> 04:06:06.280
[Guest]: consistently in the second quartile will outperform everyone on a 10-year basis.

04:06:07.320 --> 04:06:12.120
[Guest]: So, unless you got somebody who was consistently in the first quartile, the second quartile guy

04:06:12.120 --> 04:06:17.960
[Guest]: always wins. So, the second quartile thinking is what drives my behavior towards index funds.

04:06:17.960 --> 04:06:22.280
[Guest]: It is saying, all you have to do, B is a little bit better than average, you will be a little

04:06:22.280 --> 04:06:27.000
[Guest]: bit better than average simply because of the fees, you are charging lower fees. Chances are

04:06:27.000 --> 04:06:32.120
[Guest]: over a 10-year time frame, you will outperform. Now, if you said, no, Deepak, I want to find who's

04:06:32.120 --> 04:06:36.200
[Guest]: in the first quartile, now that takes skill, because you're going to say, this guy is going

04:06:36.200 --> 04:06:39.160
[Guest]: to outperform in the first three years, then there's going to be another bunch of guys that

04:06:39.160 --> 04:06:43.400
[Guest]: will outperform in the next three years, that takes skill to identify. It requires you to

04:06:43.400 --> 04:06:47.560
[Guest]: understand that, oh, I have to do, I have to find the right kind of managers, what kind of stocks

04:06:47.560 --> 04:06:51.960
[Guest]: they're picking, is their philosophy consistent with my view of the market, is my view of the

04:06:51.960 --> 04:06:56.920
[Guest]: market right? Also, if I was so good, why don't I invest in the stocks directly, etc. These are

04:06:56.920 --> 04:07:01.640
[Guest]: the questions that come in. But let's say, whatever that questions are, the answer is,

04:07:01.640 --> 04:07:06.120
[Guest]: it takes a certain amount of skill and luck. To reduce the need for skill and luck,

04:07:06.120 --> 04:07:12.200
[Guest]: you want to go to the index fund. The most important thing that people don't have is time,

04:07:13.000 --> 04:07:18.360
[Guest]: which means time to understand these various funds, time to understand the market, time to

04:07:18.360 --> 04:07:23.480
[Guest]: understand whether you should be adding more money to X or Y and making those decisions.

04:07:23.480 --> 04:07:29.240
[Guest]: Every decision you make is a grey hair. And if you don't want that many grey hair,

04:07:29.240 --> 04:07:33.000
[Guest]: or you have enough decisions in your life already, I mean, I have enough decisions

04:07:33.000 --> 04:07:40.440
[Guest]: to make about what time to, each kid wants what. And because you have that many decisions already

04:07:40.440 --> 04:07:45.480
[Guest]: to make, adding to decision fatigue is a waste of time, then you want to choose the index fund.

04:07:45.480 --> 04:07:51.080
[Guest]: Now, we are crazy people who like the market so much that we go and analyze everything that's

04:07:51.080 --> 04:07:55.320
[Guest]: in the market. We say skip the mutual fund, we'll go directly to down to the stocks and buy the

04:07:55.320 --> 04:08:01.560
[Guest]: stocks and we want to find a bunch of stocks. I have the inherent feeling that if I am not

04:08:01.560 --> 04:08:09.000
[Guest]: able to beat the indexes over a very long period, then it is in my own best interest and my customer's

04:08:09.000 --> 04:08:14.360
[Guest]: best interest for me to tell them don't invest with me or give me money, I'll put it in index,

04:08:14.360 --> 04:08:22.520
[Guest]: I will not buy stocks based on my own thinking. But like every candidate who gives the IIT exam,

04:08:22.520 --> 04:08:28.840
[Guest]: and every average person in India does not make it to IIT, you have to aspire to be above average.

04:08:29.640 --> 04:08:34.520
[Guest]: But at the same time, you have to realize the limitations that this and this is not my time

04:08:34.520 --> 04:08:39.960
[Guest]: inclination or skill. Maybe I will give an exam if I want to get into the top colleges of the

04:08:39.960 --> 04:08:46.760
[Guest]: country. But if it is not my inclination or my skill to do so, I would rather just leave it out

04:08:46.760 --> 04:08:51.960
[Guest]: there and say, you know what, I'll outsource, I will give it to an index instead. The point over

04:08:51.960 --> 04:08:56.760
[Guest]: here is reduce decision fatigue, bank on the fact that the lower cost is going to make these guys

04:08:56.760 --> 04:09:03.000
[Guest]: above average over the long term, and simplify your investing life. I choose a simple strategy

04:09:03.000 --> 04:09:09.080
[Guest]: when I've mentioned this in the book saying you got a top 100 India top 100 us simple ways to

04:09:09.080 --> 04:09:13.080
[Guest]: access them. Of course, right now, everything sucks, because everything has fallen in the last

04:09:13.080 --> 04:09:17.480
[Guest]: two or three months. But that doesn't matter. Over a period long period of time, these things will

04:09:17.480 --> 04:09:24.200
[Guest]: still make a lot of money for people. And I believe that this might be a simpler strategy for

04:09:24.200 --> 04:09:30.280
[Guest]: most people to follow. It sounds so bad because my pure business, my business is that we tell

04:09:30.280 --> 04:09:35.400
[Guest]: people that we're good at identifying stocks. At the same time, we tell people and we're probably

04:09:35.400 --> 04:09:40.200
[Guest]: the only people to have something called an index strategy where we charge a very low fee to just be

04:09:40.200 --> 04:09:46.040
[Guest]: able to tell people in a disciplined manner, invest in the top 100 US and top 100 in there,

04:09:46.040 --> 04:09:56.040
[Guest]: we'll do it for you. So I think our ability to do or to get that done is valuable because it's

04:09:56.040 --> 04:09:59.480
[Guest]: it's it's advisors actually good for a significant number of people in the market.

04:10:00.280 --> 04:10:04.120
[Guest]: But we're also at the same time saying, listen, we have some stuff that we think can beat it.

04:10:04.120 --> 04:10:08.920
[Guest]: And so we'll have to prove it to you over time. But if you are able to prove it, then

04:10:08.920 --> 04:10:12.440
[Guest]: we want to be consistent in that first quarter and not even in the second quarter.

04:10:13.080 --> 04:10:17.560
[Amit Varma]: You know, we have like, maybe another 40 minutes to talk, which is really not much.

04:10:17.560 --> 04:10:21.720
[Amit Varma]: So we can't go through your book in the kind of detail I would have liked. So you know,

04:10:21.720 --> 04:10:26.600
[Amit Varma]: you know, one day Deepak, I'm just going to have to do eight hour episodes and nine hour episodes

04:10:26.600 --> 04:10:31.480
[Amit Varma]: because every freaking four hour episode I do, it ends with this lament that shit,

04:10:31.480 --> 04:10:36.440
[Amit Varma]: that shit, we didn't discuss half the things we wanted to. And then, you know, listeners will

04:10:36.440 --> 04:10:40.120
[Amit Varma]: also write in saying, hey, you know, you didn't cover this, you didn't cover that, you didn't

04:10:40.120 --> 04:10:44.120
[Amit Varma]: cover this, you didn't cover that. I'm not going to feel squeamish about not covering some of your

04:10:44.120 --> 04:10:47.720
[Amit Varma]: book, because I just think it's one of those essential books everyone should have, frankly,

04:10:47.720 --> 04:10:52.520
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, you're making money for what you owe it to your money to understand how you spend

04:10:52.520 --> 04:10:56.680
[Amit Varma]: it. I'm not actually telling my listeners that invest with Deepak, that's a good idea. But I

04:10:56.680 --> 04:11:01.560
[Amit Varma]: am telling them that for understand, get a conceptual framework, through which you can look

04:11:01.560 --> 04:11:05.480
[Amit Varma]: at your money and kind of talk about that. Now, your chapter on mutual funds is actually very

04:11:05.480 --> 04:11:10.120
[Amit Varma]: illuminating the kind of detail you've gone into, I absolutely haven't done justice by asking this

04:11:10.120 --> 04:11:13.960
[Amit Varma]: one question and kind of lumping everything, you know, you've described the different kinds

04:11:13.960 --> 04:11:18.760
[Amit Varma]: of mutual funds, you've described the different sort of parameters, which one uses when one makes

04:11:18.760 --> 04:11:23.560
[Amit Varma]: a judgment. And, you know, we've got different juicy stories like the Franklin Templeton saga

04:11:23.560 --> 04:11:29.000
[Amit Varma]: and all that. So there's a lot of funky stuff happening there. Now, you know, moving on from

04:11:29.000 --> 04:11:34.040
[Amit Varma]: that in your next chapter, you spoke about a practical approach to investing and why it's

04:11:34.040 --> 04:11:39.800
[Amit Varma]: important to plan for after you die. And the best part that you know, the best part of all this was

04:11:39.800 --> 04:11:43.400
[Amit Varma]: figure out who you are, where you're right. And I'll quote this, because I think it's such an

04:11:43.400 --> 04:11:48.440
[Amit Varma]: important line, where you're right, figure out who you are a strong fundamentals based investor,

04:11:48.440 --> 04:11:52.760
[Amit Varma]: a price based technical investor, or simply a person who prefers to stay passive, because man,

04:11:52.760 --> 04:11:57.560
[Amit Varma]: you have better things to do with your life, stop quote. And that's important, because it's not as

04:11:57.560 --> 04:12:02.040
[Amit Varma]: if there is one alpha male approach or one particular kind of approach, which works.

04:12:02.040 --> 04:12:06.440
[Amit Varma]: The point is, whatever you do has to be in sync with your personality and your expectations and

04:12:06.440 --> 04:12:11.160
[Amit Varma]: your needs and all of that. And you've handled each of these really separately in different

04:12:11.160 --> 04:12:17.960
[Amit Varma]: parts to kind of talk about that. And I sort of found it illuminating. And you also in this

04:12:17.960 --> 04:12:22.840
[Amit Varma]: shared a couple of aphorisms by Larry Height, one of which is, if you don't bet, you can't win.

04:12:23.480 --> 04:12:29.080
[Amit Varma]: And the other one is, if you lose all your chips, you can't bet. So I sort of like this,

04:12:29.080 --> 04:12:34.120
[Amit Varma]: your next chapter is about, you know, shares your own journey and all of that. And one of

04:12:34.120 --> 04:12:41.160
[Amit Varma]: the interesting points that you make in your own journey is a fantastic point, where you say that

04:12:41.160 --> 04:12:46.120
[Amit Varma]: working a job is just crazy. And you write quote, you work on a job and you get paid a salary,

04:12:46.120 --> 04:12:50.280
[Amit Varma]: you stop working, the salary stops. But that's crazy. Because a lot of the things you help to

04:12:50.280 --> 04:12:55.080
[Amit Varma]: build will continue to serve the business you work for, stop good. So elaborate on this a bit,

04:12:55.080 --> 04:13:02.440
[Amit Varma]: because people often think of working a job as a safe route, and doing other things as a not so

04:13:02.440 --> 04:13:08.760
[Amit Varma]: safe route. But actually working a job when you see it under the seed by this lens is incredibly

04:13:08.760 --> 04:13:15.320
[Guest]: wasteful. Well, unfortunately, it's the way it is. Okay, I'll give you an example of when you

04:13:15.320 --> 04:13:20.280
[Guest]: build things. So when you're working for a business, you're usually helping build something

04:13:20.280 --> 04:13:25.480
[Guest]: now that something could be whatever asset it is. So if you're a customer service executive, also,

04:13:26.040 --> 04:13:31.160
[Guest]: that customer service that you're doing is helping build confidence and trust in that company. And

04:13:31.160 --> 04:13:35.560
[Guest]: you're you're, you know, when you leave that trust still remains in that company that you

04:13:35.560 --> 04:13:43.640
[Guest]: were there at that point and help all that stuff. The issue with not having any ownership in what

04:13:43.640 --> 04:13:50.760
[Guest]: you've built is that you lose it all when your job stops. But if you had a bit of ownership,

04:13:50.760 --> 04:13:56.120
[Guest]: that ownership would help you realize some of that potential in the longer term in years to come.

04:13:56.680 --> 04:14:00.760
[Guest]: You could own it as a piece of your own business, you could own it as a piece of someone else's

04:14:00.760 --> 04:14:08.440
[Guest]: business. And whether you help it or not is a different aspect. But this having a job and

04:14:08.440 --> 04:14:15.720
[Guest]: hoping that it will make you those big amounts of money, I think in the future will become

04:14:15.720 --> 04:14:21.480
[Guest]: less and less and less viable. That's because employers are out here and you know, honestly,

04:14:21.480 --> 04:14:26.840
[Guest]: we write we do stock market trading and we write today there's an artificial intelligence algorithm

04:14:26.840 --> 04:14:30.600
[Guest]: that can write and there's an artificial intelligence algorithm that can trade the

04:14:30.600 --> 04:14:35.240
[Guest]: markets. These guys are going to come and wipe me out at some point in time. I know that if I

04:14:35.240 --> 04:14:40.520
[Guest]: were thinking of this entire business as a job, I would be threatened. If I'm thinking of it as a

04:14:40.520 --> 04:14:46.760
[Guest]: business owner, I want to find that intelligence algorithm, make it right and make it trade and

04:14:46.760 --> 04:14:52.360
[Guest]: reap the benefit. Instead of saying I'm employed with an organization where I should be writing

04:14:52.360 --> 04:14:57.400
[Guest]: and I should be trading. And if they replace me with an algorithm, I'm finished. The thing like

04:14:57.400 --> 04:15:03.000
[Guest]: a business owner, you want to replace yourself, you think like an employee you hate to be replaced.

04:15:03.000 --> 04:15:10.600
[Guest]: So that's the point I was trying to make is that it's crazy because you get to not participate

04:15:10.600 --> 04:15:14.520
[Guest]: in the benefits of what you build, you get to not make yourself redundant,

04:15:15.080 --> 04:15:19.720
[Guest]: because all the incentives are against you to make yourself redundant, when you're actually

04:15:19.720 --> 04:15:24.520
[Guest]: adding value to the business that you've created by making yourself redundant in the first place.

04:15:24.520 --> 04:15:28.280
[Guest]: Very few businesses recognize this and the ones that do promote you.

04:15:28.280 --> 04:15:37.800
[Guest]: And so I think the interesting point about this whole part of this book was to generate a feeling

04:15:38.920 --> 04:15:43.800
[Guest]: that you have to have a piece of ownership in a business. And that is what gives you

04:15:43.800 --> 04:15:48.840
[Guest]: the eventual satisfaction of having, you know, participated in that business.

04:15:49.480 --> 04:15:53.640
[Guest]: I mean, as an as a shareholder, you may not participate in helping the business in any

04:15:53.640 --> 04:15:58.920
[Guest]: meaningful way. But sometimes you will be surprised how little public companies even know

04:15:58.920 --> 04:16:05.080
[Guest]: of how to handle the simplest and silliest things that for you maybe, you know, I'll tell you this,

04:16:05.080 --> 04:16:14.520
[Guest]: your knowledge of podcasting itself is so valuable that if any of the top 50 companies started to do

04:16:14.520 --> 04:16:20.840
[Guest]: this, any like literally any one of them saw some of the senior leadership, even build a podcast

04:16:20.840 --> 04:16:27.880
[Guest]: around their own company, I would probably buy their shares. Their knowledge of this business is

04:16:27.880 --> 04:16:38.040
[Guest]: so clinically vague, I mean, so little that that just the just my recognizing that there is a pulse

04:16:38.040 --> 04:16:43.720
[Guest]: somewhere that has shipped itself in this direction. Why aren't our biggest technology

04:16:43.720 --> 04:16:48.840
[Guest]: companies? Why don't they have a podcast on technology or anything like that or

04:16:48.840 --> 04:16:55.000
[Guest]: anything of the sort? Whereas in the US you find people in large companies very easily adapting to

04:16:55.000 --> 04:16:58.120
[Amit Varma]: Podcasts, newsletters, the works, they put themselves out there.

04:16:58.120 --> 04:17:05.240
[Guest]: And so, you know, there is a there is a political scientist who analyzes newsletters produced by

04:17:05.240 --> 04:17:09.320
[Guest]: the chamber of whatever the US Congress. Wow.

04:17:09.320 --> 04:17:14.680
[Guest]: They just analyze the number of times any word and you can search for Narendra Modi and you can

04:17:14.680 --> 04:17:21.160
[Guest]: search for, you know, X and Y and Z and Putin and all that stuff by because they just do an analysis

04:17:21.160 --> 04:17:28.520
[Guest]: of the list of newsletters produced by the US Congress. Our parliament barely produces words

04:17:28.520 --> 04:17:35.320
[Guest]: of coherence, which are not in a newsletter format. But I'm just saying that it's kind of

04:17:35.320 --> 04:17:42.600
[Guest]: amazing and surprising that you get, you don't get anything of this sort in any other place.

04:17:42.600 --> 04:17:49.400
[Guest]: But what I'm trying to really say is that you could help a business by giving them a way to

04:17:49.400 --> 04:17:56.120
[Guest]: podcast, but you could own their shares and benefit from the amount of outreach they get

04:17:56.120 --> 04:18:00.920
[Guest]: from that podcast itself. And the second one is quite as important as the first. The first will

04:18:00.920 --> 04:18:05.560
[Guest]: earn you an amount of money for a limited period of time. The second will probably earn you money

04:18:05.560 --> 04:18:09.320
[Guest]: at a later date, but a much larger amount and for a much longer period of time.

04:18:09.320 --> 04:18:14.840
[Amit Varma]: Yeah, exactly. So a question that I was saving for close to the end, but since you brought it up

04:18:14.840 --> 04:18:21.400
[Amit Varma]: is about AI, right? Now, my sense is like exactly like what you said, that at some point, AI will

04:18:21.400 --> 04:18:26.520
[Amit Varma]: make even my writing redundant, frankly, right? It, you know, we used to think I used to think

04:18:26.520 --> 04:18:31.080
[Amit Varma]: till a while ago that there are certain things that are a bridge too far for AI. Can AI write

04:18:31.080 --> 04:18:36.440
[Amit Varma]: a novel that will make me weep and so on? I think it will. Today, I think it will. I think we should

04:18:36.440 --> 04:18:42.200
[Amit Varma]: have had more humility, we've underestimated what AI can do. And whatever I see on the frontiers is

04:18:42.200 --> 04:18:46.280
[Amit Varma]: just kind of blows me away. And I think that's a damn good thing. It fills me with happiness.

04:18:46.280 --> 04:18:51.080
[Amit Varma]: If AI takes over all of this, and it, it kind of means that one, we have more good books to read,

04:18:51.080 --> 04:18:56.280
[Amit Varma]: right? And we have a far higher quality of life, the kind of value that will be saved.

04:18:56.280 --> 04:19:00.920
[Amit Varma]: Like once, you know, if AGI ever comes artificial general intelligence, for example,

04:19:00.920 --> 04:19:05.560
[Amit Varma]: people paint a dystopian vision of the future. You know, I'm not worried about it, because

04:19:05.560 --> 04:19:09.800
[Amit Varma]: at least in the short term, I think what will add like in the extreme short term, yeah, sure,

04:19:09.800 --> 04:19:14.360
[Amit Varma]: there is that kind of displacement, which new technology does. But always, when that happens,

04:19:14.360 --> 04:19:19.640
[Amit Varma]: the benefits are way more than the costs. And this could just be something that eliminates

04:19:19.640 --> 04:19:24.360
[Amit Varma]: poverty. Now in your field, it's kind of inevitable that when you're dealing with

04:19:24.360 --> 04:19:31.320
[Amit Varma]: large flows of information, with patterns and trends that are beyond human comprehension,

04:19:31.320 --> 04:19:36.040
[Amit Varma]: that eventually, AI will completely own the scene. Now, you've taken the pragmatic view

04:19:36.040 --> 04:19:40.680
[Amit Varma]: that of course it will. So I will be the business owner who will use AI in the best way possible.

04:19:40.680 --> 04:19:45.640
[Amit Varma]: But taking an even longer view than that, isn't it kind of inevitable that at one point,

04:19:45.640 --> 04:19:50.840
[Amit Varma]: not just the employee, you know, say an investment firm, but the investment firm itself

04:19:50.840 --> 04:19:56.520
[Amit Varma]: will be redundant, because people will be, you know, just able to kind of do it all themselves.

04:19:56.520 --> 04:20:00.680
[Amit Varma]: And also, you know, as a related kind of question, because this is not really a question,

04:20:00.680 --> 04:20:05.080
[Amit Varma]: it feels like an observation. I feel like one of those old men at this book launch,

04:20:05.080 --> 04:20:09.000
[Amit Varma]: who will stand up at the end and say, I have a question, and then they will ramble for 10 minutes

04:20:09.000 --> 04:20:14.360
[Amit Varma]: and not ask anything. I think I'm turning into one of those uncles. But my actual question is,

04:20:14.360 --> 04:20:21.240
[Amit Varma]: that, you know, whatever the state of the world is, at any point in time, you know, it normalizes,

04:20:21.240 --> 04:20:26.920
[Amit Varma]: and then we assume this is the natural state of things. And we are looking at stock markets and

04:20:26.920 --> 04:20:33.160
[Amit Varma]: a financial system like that, where the, you know, the basic paradigms, you assume it will stay like

04:20:33.160 --> 04:20:38.520
[Amit Varma]: this forever, that this is why stock markets came into being. And, you know, those purposes will

04:20:38.520 --> 04:20:43.800
[Amit Varma]: always be served by something that looks like this. But if you peer into the future, you know,

04:20:43.800 --> 04:20:48.520
[Amit Varma]: if you sort of look at the Wild West forming around us, and any Wild West, like, you know,

04:20:48.520 --> 04:20:53.480
[Amit Varma]: crypto and Web3 and all that is initially full of frauds and very nebulous and all of that.

04:20:53.480 --> 04:20:57.720
[Amit Varma]: But there is something there to look at, which could look completely different 30 years from now.

04:20:57.720 --> 04:21:03.800
[Amit Varma]: So, do you see in a way that these ramparts itself changing that, you know, a future where

04:21:04.440 --> 04:21:08.600
[Amit Varma]: the things that we achieve through stock markets or the financial system and all of that,

04:21:08.600 --> 04:21:14.440
[Guest]: are achieved in a very different kind of setup? It's possible. I mean, we've always seen,

04:21:14.440 --> 04:21:19.240
[Guest]: we've seen financialization only in the last 100-150 years. Before that, there was a lot of

04:21:19.240 --> 04:21:23.720
[Guest]: other stuff that was happening, barter, for instance, and all that stuff. The way the

04:21:23.720 --> 04:21:29.720
[Guest]: financial economy is today can easily change to a different kind of financial economy in the in the

04:21:29.720 --> 04:21:36.280
[Guest]: future, where you're the crypto in crypto, if you put the non-scammy part of crypto is like this,

04:21:37.320 --> 04:21:44.520
[Guest]: I pay you with something that can appreciate in value. So, instead of paying you 100 rupees,

04:21:44.520 --> 04:21:50.200
[Guest]: which you know is worth 100 rupees now and 100 rupees tomorrow, I pay you in the form of 100

04:21:50.200 --> 04:21:55.800
[Guest]: coins and those coins can go up in value in terms of rupees tomorrow. You want to deal with me

04:21:55.800 --> 04:22:00.200
[Guest]: because you think that the value of these things. So, for you, it's a double edged thing. It's not

04:22:00.200 --> 04:22:06.200
[Guest]: only that I'm paying you for the work that you do, but also that I'm paying you in something that can

04:22:06.200 --> 04:22:14.760
[Guest]: potentially grow by itself. For some, this paradigm is interesting. It's like me paying

04:22:14.760 --> 04:22:22.760
[Guest]: you by the shares of my company, rather than by cash, shares of my company, I can still print

04:22:22.760 --> 04:22:26.200
[Guest]: and give it to you. Today, there are regulatory frameworks that don't allow me to do this very

04:22:26.200 --> 04:22:31.160
[Guest]: easily. But assuming I was able to do it, I could have created another company that owns a bunch of

04:22:31.160 --> 04:22:37.320
[Guest]: my shares. And I can pay you through that company whenever I want saying instead of paying a 1 lakh

04:22:37.320 --> 04:22:44.200
[Guest]: rupees worth this thing, I'll be in 1 lakh rupees of my shares and effectively print my own money.

04:22:44.200 --> 04:22:50.760
[Guest]: If I was able to do this, then a lot more avenues open. Banks are not banks are currently the only

04:22:50.760 --> 04:22:55.480
[Guest]: guys allowed to print money, banks print money by nature, but banks are heavily regulated. So,

04:22:55.480 --> 04:23:01.320
[Guest]: they have certain things, but companies are not so they could issue shares at at whatever valuation

04:23:01.320 --> 04:23:06.920
[Guest]: to somebody else and issuing shares, you could replace the word share by a coin, and you would be

04:23:07.960 --> 04:23:16.040
[Guest]: roughly the same. So, building a framework like this, out of crypto and into the real world

04:23:16.040 --> 04:23:21.560
[Guest]: is not very difficult, we can absorb that stuff and build it here. We can use the same concepts

04:23:21.560 --> 04:23:27.960
[Guest]: that crypto is doing. So, crypto is something called automated market making a form of saying

04:23:27.960 --> 04:23:36.360
[Guest]: that if you pay me one share of Reliance, I can pay you back 100 rupees or 2000 rupees or whatever

04:23:36.360 --> 04:23:40.520
[Guest]: that number is that is discovered by the market today. But what if I told you I'll exchange your

04:23:40.520 --> 04:23:47.800
[Guest]: one share of Reliance for one share of TCS. So, you the difference between the two is that I don't

04:23:47.800 --> 04:23:52.680
[Guest]: even have shares of Reliance and TCS. Somebody else has given me shares of Reliance and some

04:23:52.680 --> 04:23:57.080
[Guest]: other person has given me shares of TCS. I am just building a balanced pool of them too. So,

04:23:57.080 --> 04:24:00.920
[Guest]: when you give me a Reliance, I give you a TCS for a predefined exchange rate

04:24:00.920 --> 04:24:07.880
[Guest]: that's currently ongoing, this can be completely automated. The net result of this is you can trade

04:24:07.880 --> 04:24:14.920
[Guest]: with me. And I don't need to be a human being, I can be a complete algorithm that is determining

04:24:14.920 --> 04:24:20.600
[Guest]: the prices dynamically based on supply and demand. This is already happening in the crypto world.

04:24:20.600 --> 04:24:24.440
[Guest]: This has been happening in the forex world for the longest amount of time. So, you can give me USD,

04:24:24.440 --> 04:24:30.600
[Guest]: I'll give you INR. They're almost all run by computers, 97%. Has this removed the need for

04:24:30.600 --> 04:24:37.080
[Guest]: a human being to exist? I think no, they just go one level higher. Which means instead of the guys

04:24:37.080 --> 04:24:41.720
[Guest]: who are trading, they are the guys who are designing these algorithms. They are the guys

04:24:41.720 --> 04:24:47.320
[Guest]: who are figuring out how to get more done through these algorithms, to the extent where some today,

04:24:47.320 --> 04:24:52.040
[Guest]: it has helped a lot of people. For instance, when you travel, you use a card, they charge you a 3%

04:24:52.040 --> 04:24:56.360
[Guest]: fee, then a 0.5% fee, then something else and GST and so on. So, you end up paying some 4 or 5%

04:24:57.080 --> 04:25:01.800
[Guest]: as a transaction fee. There's a startup that's come and built an algorithmic trading framework

04:25:01.800 --> 04:25:06.440
[Guest]: that says, when you swipe the card, we'll give you the best price possible because we've eliminated

04:25:06.440 --> 04:25:12.040
[Guest]: all the intermediate bullshit that happens in this whole picture. And you can swipe a card for

04:25:13.160 --> 04:25:20.040
[Guest]: $100 and we'll charge you only 75 rupees when the going rate is 74.80. So, the only 20 paisa

04:25:20.040 --> 04:25:27.080
[Guest]: spread versus a 76 rupees, which would have, you know, had to pay otherwise. So, this is technology

04:25:27.080 --> 04:25:32.200
[Guest]: where the actual trading, which would otherwise have been done manually, has been done by a

04:25:32.200 --> 04:25:37.880
[Guest]: computer. But the benefit that's being provided is being intermediated by a human being who's

04:25:37.880 --> 04:25:41.960
[Guest]: selling you, listen, I have the tech to do all this stuff. I'm going to simplify your life,

04:25:41.960 --> 04:25:46.200
[Guest]: I'm going to make it cheaper for you to travel. And guess what, this allows you to travel more,

04:25:46.200 --> 04:25:52.120
[Guest]: more destinations, less painful to do all these transactions, and more deterministic. So,

04:25:52.120 --> 04:25:56.120
[Guest]: you can actually tell you that if you swipe right now, this is the price you'll get on an app,

04:25:56.120 --> 04:25:59.960
[Guest]: versus otherwise you'd have to call somebody and say, what's the rate today? And you know,

04:25:59.960 --> 04:26:04.840
[Guest]: that stuff. So, I think we'll just kick ourselves one level higher. Instead of writing the books,

04:26:04.840 --> 04:26:10.840
[Guest]: we'll be doing something one level higher, which is not writing the books, but finding ways to

04:26:10.840 --> 04:26:16.440
[Guest]: distribute them, finding ways to get them across. Whether it is the context in which those books are

04:26:16.440 --> 04:26:21.480
[Guest]: written, or whether it is something else, I don't know. I can't foresee it that much. But all I know

04:26:21.480 --> 04:26:26.520
[Guest]: is that we will be one level higher. Humans have always found a way to evolve to a point where

04:26:26.520 --> 04:26:31.880
[Guest]: their need is, or not just that their need is, it's like saying, you know, just because you've

04:26:31.880 --> 04:26:38.520
[Guest]: bought a harvester doesn't mean people stopped farming. It's the same people that were otherwise

04:26:38.520 --> 04:26:43.480
[Guest]: plowing the fields that are now using harvesters, there are more fields to plow. So, we'll find more

04:26:43.480 --> 04:26:50.600
[Guest]: fields within the same thing, and do things better. Tomorrow, it may be that the same concept

04:26:50.600 --> 04:26:54.840
[Guest]: can be used for five different things, rather than that one thing, which is writing a book.

04:26:54.840 --> 04:26:58.920
[Guest]: Tomorrow, I mean, it's already happening, right? Earlier, it was only books. Now, it is books,

04:26:58.920 --> 04:27:07.720
[Guest]: blogs, videos, podcasts, X, same content delivered or rendered five different ways. Maybe that's what

04:27:07.720 --> 04:27:13.960
[Guest]: the AI will end up helping with, which is, what's the best way to produce this format that allows

04:27:13.960 --> 04:27:20.280
[Guest]: you to visualize and see this. Books will come to life in more meaningful ways than us just having

04:27:20.280 --> 04:27:24.280
[Amit Varma]: to write them. Yeah, I think there'll be unknown unknowns. I think we'll also write, but I once

04:27:24.280 --> 04:27:29.400
[Amit Varma]: said about Trump that Trump would fail the Turing test. So, I think humans should have a little bit

04:27:29.400 --> 04:27:33.720
[Amit Varma]: of humility about their own natural intelligence, so to say. So, my next question is also a broad

04:27:33.720 --> 04:27:40.280
[Amit Varma]: one. And this is again, at one level, it is me thinking aloud and also asking a question which

04:27:40.280 --> 04:27:44.680
[Amit Varma]: I've chatted about with the two guests I recorded with over the last two days. And here's the thing,

04:27:44.680 --> 04:27:49.880
[Amit Varma]: earlier, we spoke about how the mainstream is dissipating. Media is dissipating, music,

04:27:49.880 --> 04:27:54.600
[Amit Varma]: where the mainstream is dissipating, everywhere the mainstream is dissipating, what you're having

04:27:54.600 --> 04:28:00.680
[Amit Varma]: is a certain kind of decentralization, right? Now, in the context, like I was chatting with the

04:28:00.680 --> 04:28:05.640
[Amit Varma]: with former Foreign Secretary and Ambassador Nirupama Rao day before yesterday, she's written

04:28:05.640 --> 04:28:12.680
[Amit Varma]: an excellent book on China, The Fractured Himalaya. And she was talking about how in Tibet earlier,

04:28:12.680 --> 04:28:16.680
[Amit Varma]: when they would make maps, they would not put those lines of nation states, a mountain was a

04:28:16.680 --> 04:28:21.320
[Amit Varma]: mountain, a river was a river, those are the maps they would make. And her additional point to that,

04:28:21.320 --> 04:28:27.560
[Amit Varma]: which I feel is so true, is that, you know, when you look at peoples, it's almost as if peoples

04:28:27.560 --> 04:28:32.600
[Amit Varma]: with exactly the same culture, with cultural continuity have been divided by these artificial

04:28:32.600 --> 04:28:37.880
[Amit Varma]: lines of nation states. Now, I think you and I understand data well enough to know that a sample

04:28:37.880 --> 04:28:44.040
[Amit Varma]: size of years for which nation states has existed is really too low to come to a conclusion about

04:28:44.040 --> 04:28:48.360
[Amit Varma]: them or say that they're inevitable, or they're always here to stay. In fact, many modern problems

04:28:48.360 --> 04:28:54.600
[Amit Varma]: come about because of our rigid notions of nation states and these artificial boundaries, which

04:28:54.600 --> 04:29:00.760
[Amit Varma]: divide us where no divisions need exist. And I'm again thinking, you know, one of the things that

04:29:00.760 --> 04:29:05.800
[Amit Varma]: people who talk about crypto say that decentralization, that, you know, it's one way to

04:29:05.800 --> 04:29:11.880
[Amit Varma]: get away from the tyranny of nation states, from the oppressiveness of, you know, parasitic nation

04:29:11.880 --> 04:29:17.160
[Amit Varma]: states, and so on and so forth. And I find it interesting. So this is not really a question

04:29:17.160 --> 04:29:21.880
[Amit Varma]: about finance per se, for a moment, we've moved away from your book. But is this something that

04:29:21.880 --> 04:29:27.000
[Amit Varma]: you kind of think about that we take it for granted, but is the primacy of nation states

04:29:27.000 --> 04:29:31.480
[Amit Varma]: in our thinking that even if they exist, maybe they won't be so important. Maybe they won't be

04:29:31.480 --> 04:29:36.680
[Amit Varma]: such a big deal. Maybe by necessity borders become more fluid. Maybe physical borders don't become

04:29:36.680 --> 04:29:41.320
[Amit Varma]: more fluid, but other borders do. I'm just kind of thinking a lot because it seems to me to be this

04:29:41.320 --> 04:29:47.320
[Amit Varma]: secular trend of decentralization across everything that you can think of. So you know, isn't that,

04:29:47.320 --> 04:29:53.000
[Amit Varma]: you know, just as a mainstream media newspaper or a Hollywood studio might at some point become

04:29:53.000 --> 04:29:56.200
[Amit Varma]: redundant, why would central banks not become redundant and so on?

04:29:56.200 --> 04:30:01.640
[Guest]: Well, it's true, it could happen even now. Let's not take crypto. Let's say we were all playing,

04:30:01.640 --> 04:30:07.560
[Guest]: I don't know, Minesweeper, or I mean, some game, Minecraft. And you earned a few things in that

04:30:07.560 --> 04:30:12.120
[Guest]: Minecraft, you had a bunch of chests, and it had certain objects in it. And you could trade those

04:30:12.120 --> 04:30:18.280
[Guest]: objects with each other. And all those objects had very nicely predefined values. So I could trade

04:30:18.280 --> 04:30:24.440
[Guest]: with you, you can then surpass the trade nation state by just playing Minecraft. You could say I

04:30:24.440 --> 04:30:29.480
[Guest]: want this particular thing. And I don't care if you're in Croatia or Serbia, or you know,

04:30:29.480 --> 04:30:36.280
[Guest]: South Southern Sudan, but I will give you something worth five sickles. If you know,

04:30:36.280 --> 04:30:42.200
[Guest]: now, you don't need crypto for this. Crypto is a nice way to do it. But barter has existed for

04:30:42.200 --> 04:30:47.400
[Guest]: centuries. The reason we've stuck on currencies is because nobody can agree on the value of anything.

04:30:48.200 --> 04:30:54.280
[Guest]: In the end, it comes down to listen, I got to know what $1 means. And if I know what $1 means,

04:30:54.280 --> 04:31:00.280
[Guest]: more than I know that what one sickle means, I'll go to the dollar. So the dollar has been a medium

04:31:00.280 --> 04:31:05.000
[Guest]: of exchange, the rupee has been a medium of exchange, only for that reason that people

04:31:05.000 --> 04:31:10.120
[Guest]: could not agree on the value of something. If they're able to find something else where they

04:31:10.120 --> 04:31:13.400
[Guest]: agree with the value of and one of the biggest things they agree on the value of is gold,

04:31:13.400 --> 04:31:17.480
[Guest]: for instance. But gold comes with challenges of being used as a currency because of its nature,

04:31:17.480 --> 04:31:23.000
[Guest]: you can't cut it beyond a certain point and all that stuff. But digital things like sickles and

04:31:23.000 --> 04:31:27.160
[Guest]: all that stuff can be and I can buy one fourth of a sickle. Somebody has just put something in

04:31:27.160 --> 04:31:32.440
[Guest]: court to it. I think it's a very interesting construct. But don't you think that the

04:31:32.440 --> 04:31:42.200
[Guest]: the separation of nation state and economics has already happened. We consume Google, or Amazon,

04:31:42.840 --> 04:31:48.120
[Guest]: well Google to some extent Facebook, anybody in the world can advertise to us.

04:31:48.920 --> 04:31:54.600
[Guest]: They have surpassed the nation state by saying we are Facebook, you can find a guy in India.

04:31:54.600 --> 04:31:59.160
[Guest]: And if you're a person in Denmark, you can advertise to that guy in Bangalore. This is

04:31:59.160 --> 04:32:03.160
[Guest]: amazing, because earlier you needed the physical approach, you need to send something over here

04:32:03.160 --> 04:32:06.840
[Guest]: and then get it out. Now you can do this worldwide. We've surpassed the nation state

04:32:06.840 --> 04:32:13.400
[Guest]: through technology in many, many ways. I could now order digital goods from the Kindle store,

04:32:13.400 --> 04:32:17.880
[Guest]: which is produced anywhere else in the world, in any language, I could buy a Swahili book,

04:32:17.880 --> 04:32:22.840
[Guest]: earlier it was impossible. So once you've got past the, I mean, even within the nation,

04:32:22.840 --> 04:32:28.440
[Guest]: the state boundaries of whatever they were, I am a weird guy when it comes to shoes. Okay,

04:32:28.440 --> 04:32:34.360
[Guest]: so in a sense, I hate buying shoes. But I find it fascinating that today I can buy something for

04:32:34.360 --> 04:32:43.000
[Guest]: 499 rupees, that's made in Punjab, that the guy is making a 50% profit on by selling it to me at

04:32:43.000 --> 04:32:49.880
[Guest]: 499. And yet, I could not find that thing in a shop in Bangalore for the last 15 years. I can

04:32:49.880 --> 04:32:54.840
[Guest]: go to Amazon today and pick it up or Flipkart today and pick it up by just going online and

04:32:54.840 --> 04:32:59.240
[Guest]: seeing it because for him, the logistics of bringing it to Bangalore have been sorted out

04:32:59.240 --> 04:33:05.880
[Guest]: by multiple third parties in the middle, so that his 499 price point also yields him a 50% profit.

04:33:05.880 --> 04:33:11.400
[Guest]: I find this fascinating that that has already been done within India. But because of its physical

04:33:11.400 --> 04:33:18.120
[Guest]: nature, it's not transcended the nation state. But the digital good has. Today, I could read

04:33:18.120 --> 04:33:23.480
[Guest]: books, I could read anything I could, if it was possible, invest in stocks abroad.

04:33:23.480 --> 04:33:28.680
[Guest]: If they were willing to take my rupees. But outside of India, the other nation states have

04:33:28.680 --> 04:33:33.960
[Guest]: figured out how to deal with Neetha's currency seamlessly. We have our own little RBI sitting

04:33:33.960 --> 04:33:42.040
[Guest]: on our head with a hammer. But you could buy stocks of any country sitting anywhere else in

04:33:42.040 --> 04:33:49.160
[Guest]: the world by just using the internet today. This is a way we've surpassed it. We've just not found

04:33:49.160 --> 04:33:55.800
[Guest]: the right ways to pay for things worldwide. But eventually, if Facebook were to issue its own

04:33:55.800 --> 04:34:01.960
[Guest]: coin, and people were able to pay each other with Facebook coins, that could become a currency of

04:34:01.960 --> 04:34:05.640
[Guest]: the world. And by the way, this is not just me saying it, they're thinking it actively,

04:34:05.640 --> 04:34:09.880
[Guest]: they're going to build something called the metaverse, where they're going to do exactly

04:34:09.880 --> 04:34:14.520
[Guest]: this, which is to have their own world, because they can't have a real one, they want to make

04:34:14.520 --> 04:34:20.120
[Guest]: one, they want to make a virtual one. In that all the currencies will be Facebook's own currency.

04:34:20.120 --> 04:34:24.360
[Guest]: The minute you're in it, and because there are other people in it from God knows which other

04:34:24.360 --> 04:34:29.240
[Guest]: state, they are nation state, they're all going to want to interact with each other, they're all

04:34:29.240 --> 04:34:33.160
[Guest]: going to pay a Facebook a tiny piece of that pie, not tiny, it's going to be a big piece of that

04:34:33.160 --> 04:34:39.080
[Guest]: pie. But their fascination is to do that, you know, the minute this dream comes close to becoming a

04:34:39.080 --> 04:34:45.800
[Guest]: reality, you can bet that the guys with guns will react violently and take down some part of this

04:34:45.800 --> 04:34:51.560
[Guest]: operation. And the same with crypto. At some point, the guys with guns will come in and say no. So I

04:34:51.560 --> 04:34:55.560
[Guest]: don't know what that point is. And maybe I'm getting it wrong. And maybe the guys with guns

04:34:55.560 --> 04:35:00.760
[Guest]: are the ones that already own these bitcoins and all of that stuff. And they're laughing all their

04:35:00.760 --> 04:35:06.760
[Guest]: way when we are saying that, you know, but I'm just saying that the paradigms will shift,

04:35:06.760 --> 04:35:11.880
[Guest]: we will change, it will change and it's already transcending the nation state in ways we can't

04:35:11.880 --> 04:35:15.880
[Amit Varma]: imagine. I think the guys with guns will get together with the guys with money. That's how

04:35:15.880 --> 04:35:19.880
[Amit Varma]: it always happens, right? So there's a good friend of mine, I won't name him, but we used to play

04:35:19.880 --> 04:35:24.520
[Amit Varma]: together a lot in Mumbai when I was playing live cash games. And then of course, I retired and

04:35:24.520 --> 04:35:28.920
[Amit Varma]: he went on to become perhaps the country's finest player based in Delhi, but now taken permanent

04:35:28.920 --> 04:35:34.840
[Amit Varma]: residency in Dubai, where he once played a nine crore pot equivalent of that. But anyway,

04:35:34.840 --> 04:35:39.480
[Amit Varma]: I gossip about all of that is offline. So I was hanging out with him recently, when I went to

04:35:39.480 --> 04:35:43.880
[Amit Varma]: Delhi, he also happened to be there. And I was kind of chatting with him about what the poker

04:35:43.880 --> 04:35:49.960
[Amit Varma]: economy is like. And so much of the poker economy is now crypto, right? So he's in Dubai, no taxes,

04:35:49.960 --> 04:35:54.520
[Amit Varma]: some of the money is whatever currency you want it in, but a lot of it is crypto. And then he can

04:35:54.520 --> 04:36:01.000
[Amit Varma]: use that crypto to deposit money in US gambling sites where he can play poker, and he can withdraw

04:36:01.000 --> 04:36:06.360
[Amit Varma]: from there in crypto, right? And it's a and the complexity of it all like from the outside,

04:36:06.360 --> 04:36:14.040
[Amit Varma]: we sometimes get the impression that it's a wild west and, you know, and all of that, but there's

04:36:14.040 --> 04:36:19.800
[Amit Varma]: a very sophisticated economy kind of running in there, which is fascinating. And everything you

04:36:19.800 --> 04:36:26.760
[Amit Varma]: say resonates like how the nation state is actually so much less relevant in our lives today,

04:36:26.760 --> 04:36:32.440
[Amit Varma]: than it was 30 years ago, that is kind of just mind blowing. So we have 12 minutes to go. So

04:36:32.440 --> 04:36:37.560
[Amit Varma]: I'll ask my final question. I think that alone is something we can iterate on a bit, which is

04:36:38.200 --> 04:36:43.960
[Amit Varma]: that supposing a person like me, and although I will never get down to it, but it's an intention,

04:36:43.960 --> 04:36:48.520
[Amit Varma]: supposing a person like me comes to you and says that boss, you know, I really respect your

04:36:48.520 --> 04:36:52.680
[Amit Varma]: knowledge of finance and investing and all of that. And I find it fascinating just at an

04:36:52.680 --> 04:36:58.680
[Amit Varma]: intellectual level, I also want to learn, right? But what are the resources? How do I learn this?

04:36:58.680 --> 04:37:04.280
[Guest]: This is a very good question. Because the question isn't, it's like saying I want to learn music.

04:37:05.720 --> 04:37:10.200
[Guest]: Because then my first question would be what kind of music? Because there are there's the

04:37:10.200 --> 04:37:15.960
[Guest]: Carnatic and Indian classical, there's Western classical, there's hip hop, there's rock,

04:37:15.960 --> 04:37:20.040
[Guest]: there's pop, there's a bunch of others. And then there's new paradigms like EDM that

04:37:20.040 --> 04:37:24.600
[Amit Varma]: Okay, let me clarify that and pause that because I recorded recently with Warren Mendonca of

04:37:24.600 --> 04:37:29.800
[Amit Varma]: Blackstrat Blues. And he told me that increasingly as he listens to different kinds of music across

04:37:29.800 --> 04:37:33.720
[Amit Varma]: the world, he's coming to the conclusion that they all have something in common,

04:37:33.720 --> 04:37:37.320
[Amit Varma]: which could be the pentatonic scale or whatever, you know, but they all have,

04:37:37.320 --> 04:37:41.000
[Amit Varma]: there's a universal pentatonic as it were. Is there something like that in?

04:37:41.000 --> 04:37:47.960
[Guest]: There is, I mean, in the end, the similarity with almost all forms of investing is that if I put in

04:37:47.960 --> 04:37:56.600
[Guest]: X, I want to get more than X out of it. If X was a commodity of some sort, there was no chance you

04:37:56.600 --> 04:38:01.800
[Guest]: could get more out of it. For instance, when you invest in gold, you take the gold, you can't get

04:38:01.800 --> 04:38:06.200
[Guest]: more gold out of it, it's never going to produce anything more than just the gold that it is.

04:38:06.840 --> 04:38:10.840
[Guest]: But when we invest in certain other things like a house, you want to invest in a house,

04:38:10.840 --> 04:38:14.120
[Guest]: somebody's going to pay you some rent and the house is going to be worth more when you sell it.

04:38:14.120 --> 04:38:20.200
[Guest]: If you invest in a stock, you're expected to pay some dividends and give. So I think this is

04:38:20.200 --> 04:38:25.960
[Guest]: universal as a phenomenon that you want to achieve out of it. But there are concepts that remain.

04:38:26.680 --> 04:38:32.840
[Guest]: If you divide this world into people who have the skill, inclination and time to invest,

04:38:32.840 --> 04:38:39.400
[Guest]: and people who don't. So just to the people who don't necessarily have to find someone else who

04:38:39.400 --> 04:38:44.760
[Guest]: does and hand them over their money. Or choose something as safe as a government bond or a fixed

04:38:44.760 --> 04:38:49.080
[Guest]: deposit to invest. So for them, the choices are very clear. Find the right person who will make

04:38:49.080 --> 04:38:53.960
[Guest]: the right decisions or, you know, so that is, that is, I think, a universal phenomenon, no matter

04:38:53.960 --> 04:39:00.440
[Guest]: what. So if you want to learn about it, your idea would essentially be, how do I learn about the

04:39:00.440 --> 04:39:05.880
[Guest]: various forms of investing that's out there that I don't want to do myself, I want to use a vehicle

04:39:05.880 --> 04:39:11.160
[Guest]: like a mutual fund to do, I just need to be able to select the right kind of mutual funds to do it.

04:39:11.160 --> 04:39:16.360
[Guest]: You can go to varying degrees of complexity here, similar to music, where you could do something in

04:39:16.360 --> 04:39:22.600
[Guest]: x now x degrees or the simplest form would be passive funds that are spread broadly across

04:39:23.160 --> 04:39:27.640
[Guest]: the world. The more complex would be I want to invest in different sectors and I want to find

04:39:27.640 --> 04:39:33.240
[Guest]: a manager who will do the best in each sector and so on. Another form would be directly investing

04:39:33.240 --> 04:39:38.040
[Guest]: in stocks or not, well, since we're still giving money to other managers, we're just finding the

04:39:38.040 --> 04:39:44.360
[Guest]: right managers. I find a guy who can invest in startups that have a potentially large return,

04:39:44.360 --> 04:39:49.960
[Guest]: I give him 5% of my money. My job is to figure out if should I give him 5% of my money or 20%

04:39:49.960 --> 04:39:55.880
[Guest]: of my money. That's my allocate, I'm an allocator. So my knowledge goes to the aspect of saying I

04:39:55.880 --> 04:40:00.600
[Guest]: understand which asset class I want to invest in. My job is to find the right managers and give them

04:40:00.600 --> 04:40:05.480
[Guest]: money. I could be on the flip side of the table where I have the time, inclination, and skill,

04:40:05.480 --> 04:40:08.840
[Guest]: where I say, listen, I'm directly going to invest, which means I'm going to take my money,

04:40:08.840 --> 04:40:15.720
[Guest]: I'm going to allocate it to some startups, some which I understand and analyze, some stocks,

04:40:15.720 --> 04:40:22.040
[Guest]: which I analyze, or something else. So there's a bit of the passive and a bit of the active in

04:40:22.040 --> 04:40:28.760
[Guest]: each one of us. So while I typically suggest the path should be start with passive and go down to

04:40:28.760 --> 04:40:35.960
[Guest]: active, a typical person's path is like this, he starts with active, goes to zero, then comes back

04:40:35.960 --> 04:40:42.040
[Guest]: into passive, then gets excited a little goes into active, puts a little too much into active,

04:40:42.040 --> 04:40:46.520
[Guest]: then figures out passive is better, and then starts balancing the two. So it's a little bit of a

04:40:47.640 --> 04:40:51.560
[Guest]: lizard's walk or a snake's walk across these two paradigms.

04:40:51.560 --> 04:40:53.000
[Amit Varma]: Lizards walk down Wall Street.

04:40:53.000 --> 04:40:59.400
[Guest]: Down there you go. So this is this is unfortunate, but this is how people are by behavior. And I

04:40:59.400 --> 04:41:03.320
[Guest]: think we should promote that because if you tell them that there's only this path to go there,

04:41:03.320 --> 04:41:10.600
[Guest]: they will never do it. So I hate to say this, but if you force people down the virtuous path,

04:41:11.160 --> 04:41:18.280
[Guest]: they will shun you. So you have to give them the bad part, make them learn from their mistakes.

04:41:18.280 --> 04:41:21.400
[Guest]: And then, I mean, you have to give them the option of the good and the bad part,

04:41:21.400 --> 04:41:25.480
[Guest]: and they'll take the bad part and come to the good part eventually. Or when I say good, I mean,

04:41:25.480 --> 04:41:28.840
[Guest]: it doesn't necessarily mean good from my perspective, I'm looking at averages here.

04:41:28.840 --> 04:41:34.520
[Guest]: So there will always be some people who shine at what they do right from day one. But having said

04:41:34.520 --> 04:41:39.480
[Guest]: that, I think the point over here that you have to look at from an investing perspective is,

04:41:39.480 --> 04:41:44.680
[Guest]: do you understand what you're investing in? And are you taking the active path or the passive

04:41:44.680 --> 04:41:49.000
[Guest]: path? And be really clear about the difference between the two. For instance, if I choose a

04:41:49.000 --> 04:41:53.000
[Guest]: mutual fund manager, and then every month I look at which stocks he's bought, and call him up and

04:41:53.000 --> 04:41:57.000
[Guest]: say, why have you bought this stock? Like, boss, what are you doing? Are you trusting the manager

04:41:57.000 --> 04:42:00.840
[Guest]: or you want to do it yourself? Why don't you buy the stocks directly? Take the active route. Now,

04:42:00.840 --> 04:42:05.480
[Guest]: why are you going on this passive route and haranguing the manager, fund manager for this?

04:42:05.480 --> 04:42:10.440
[Guest]: On the other hand, if you're, if you're taking the active route, and then, you know,

04:42:10.440 --> 04:42:15.160
[Guest]: trying to feel miserable, you're feeling miserable that the passive guys are doing so much better

04:42:15.160 --> 04:42:20.440
[Guest]: than you are, then, you know, you're doing the wrong thing, you should just be putting in more

04:42:20.440 --> 04:42:24.440
[Guest]: money into the passive route. I don't know if there's any commonality over here. But I think

04:42:24.440 --> 04:42:27.720
[Guest]: this would apply to whether you're investing in real estate, whether you're investing in crypto,

04:42:27.720 --> 04:42:34.600
[Guest]: whether you're investing in stocks and debt and mutual funds, or in fact, investing in art.

04:42:34.600 --> 04:42:38.840
[Guest]: There are some people who just get art, there's some people like me, who can look at an image for

